<LI><A HREF="#Parcel" onMouseOver="self.status=''; return true">Pass the parcel</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Seminars" onMouseOver="self.status=''; return true">A Bilbrough & Co Seminars</A>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<H3>Fair dues</H3>
PROMPT payment of calls is an important aspect of the mutuality on which P&I
clubs rest, according to Lance Johnson, claims director. "The bulk of our members pay their calls on time and appreciate the consequences of any failure to do so," says Mr Johnson. "They understand they are pooling their funds and resources on a mutual basis. It would be unfair on the whole membership if a member failed to pay by the due date."
<P>
Mr Johnson says premium income for the International Group is almost $1.65bn,
and the London Club's annual premium is about $103m. "These are substantial
sums and one measure of a Club's efficiency is the promptness with which it gets the premium revenue in. We work hard to develop a real understanding of member's needs," says Mr Johnson. 
<P>
"Sometimes, some shipowners can misinterpret that as being soft on collecting
dues. But we would be failing in our duty to our members if we didn't act swiftly to ensure members pay on time." The London Club prides itself on having the lowest debtors to premiums ratio in the International Group, which is the other side of the coin to having one of the best reputations for service and working closely with members.
<P>
Calls are collected against debit notes which are issued for two instalments of advance calls. If members do not pay by the due date, they prejudice their P&I cover, claims files may not be handled, claims will not be reimbursed and the provision of security will not be considered. Interest may also be charged for the period that the payment remains overdue. 
<P>
Mr Johnson says there are occasional extreme cases where a member simply does
not pay. "In those cases we issue a notice of cancellation, followed by legal
proceedings on an international basis which may lead to an eventual arrest of
vessels. Fortunately, fair dues prevail and we don't have to do this often."
<P>

<BR><A NAME="crew"></A>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Keeping healthy</H3>

IF MEMBERS rely on local agents to inform local P&I correspondents of problems, they face the danger that the message may not get through. A recent case in which a sick seafarer was hospitalised in the USA with a serious illness could have had serious financial consequences for the shipowner. "In this case, the seafarer recovered," says Ernie Chaplin, assistant director responsible for crew claims. "But the member did not let us know until the treatment was well advanced. It was a very serious case and we would have used a healthcare management service to oversee the treatment, and the costs, if we had known."
<P>
Under Rule 17.1 and 17.1.1, members are obliged to notify the managers of any
event which could give rise to a claim, and Mr Chaplin says members cannot rely on their agent in a port to inform the local P&I correspondent. "We followed up on this case, and the owner's agent said he would not notify P&I correspondents unless expressly ordered to by the shipowner. He saw his duty as only to notify the owner, his principal, of the hospitalisation. The owner should have informed us, but didn't."
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Approved agreements</H3>

MEMBERS are taking risks if they don't keep aware of changes to employment
contracts, and get those contracts approved by the club, according to Ernie Chaplin. "We have found that some members are still not aware of the substantial increase in compensation benefits for death in service of Filipino seafarers which became payable in accordance with the POEA Standard Contract which took effect from March 19, 1994," says Mr Chaplin. "This puts up death benefits to $50,000 plus $7,000 for each child under 21. Members must take account of this, and have their crew employment contracts approved by the Club." 
<P>
Mr Chaplin also highlighted recent cases where crew agreements contained annuity clauses which would entitle an injured seafarer to a life annuity of 86 per cent of basic pay. The Club made clear in 1993 that it would not cover agreements carrying such a clause entered into after February 20, 1993. It is in the interests of all members to ensure that contracts and crew agreements are submitted to the Club for approval, as they will not be covered for liabilities under contracts not approved. 
<P>
<BR>
<A NAME="Calls"></A>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Conservative calls</H3>

THE London Club has been known as possibly the most conservative and cautious
of all the major group Clubs. That caution was reflected at the annual overseas committee meeting, held in Monte Carlo in mid-October. The committee agreed a general increase in calls of five percent for the 1997/8 policy year. That decision has to be ratified by the Finance & Audit Committee in December, and like all decisions made by such an active board as that of the London Club, it was not arrived at without strong debate.
<P>
Underpinning the decision to raise rates was the knowledge that this year we, and perhaps more so other clubs, have begun to see a rising trend in claims. Also, the committee is clearly aware of the continual increase in legal liabilities which shipowners are facing.
<P>
The committee urged the managers to play a leading role in negotiating a reduction in the International Group's reinsurance premium, and noted with satisfaction that shipowner opinion, and some other clubs, have now swung behind the realistically collectible limit on cover we advocate.
<P>
Despite the caution, the meeting, the first, but hopefully not the last, we have held in Monte Carlo, was characterised by a feeling that our Club is on the move, and growing stronger and more influential.
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<I><CENTER><CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn8_1.jpg" ALT="S Ofer" WIDTH=271 HEIGHT=200 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM></CENTER>
Sammy Ofer hosted a dinner party during the Monte Carlo committee meeting. He is seen here above (centre) with two London Club committee members, Frank Chao (left) and Michael Lemos (right).
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn8_2.jpg" ALT="Monte Carlo" WIDTH=270 HEIGHT=184 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=BOTTOM ALIGN=right></CENTER>
Italian guests at the Club's October meeting in Monte Carlo. From left to right: Stefano Rosmini, Captain Piero Vincenti, Alfio Delorenzi and Vittorio de Gaspari.</CENTER></I>
<P>
<BR>
<A NAME="Turkey"></A>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Stowaway warning</H3>

SHIP masters may be faced with a two year jail sentence if stowaways held on
board abscond in a Turkish port. Istanbul-based Omur Marine warns that the Turkish Marine Police are tightening procedures on stowaways, and applying the regulations rigorously.
<P>
According to Omur, the Turkish immigration law demands that masters declare the presence of stowaways on the vessel on arrival in a Turkish port. The stowaways must then be held on board and the master is responsible for their detention. If they abscond, the master will be brought before a criminal court and may be sentenced to two years' jail and a heavy fine.
<P>
If the master fails to declare the stowaways, and the Marine Police find out that they are on board, the master will face the same sentence as above, and in addition, the stowaway will get six months in jail. 
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Pollution monitoring</H3>

THE Malaysian government is to introduce a 24 hour surveillance, early warning and detection system for oil pollution in Malaysian waters. It will monitor both oil and illegal sludge dumping and discharge.
<P>
According to Singapore-based Spica Services, the system will be based on a sensor buoy system. Fixed buoys will be located in pollution hot spots. Sensors on the buoys will detect oil in the water and relay the information via satellite to a command centre.
<P>
<I>For information on the club's loss prevention activities call Lance Johnson on +44 (0)171 772 8000, or send an email for his attention using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co'; return true">form</A>.</I>
<P>

<BR>
<A NAME="Parcel"></A>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Pass the parcel</H3>

ARRESTING vessels can be a tricky business, not least because ships are paid to keep on the move. And these days, the power of arrest is sometimes blatantly abused.
<P>
A sense of uniformity is needed, but nobody is holding their breath at the outcome of an IMO/UNCTAD meeting in Geneva later this year which is charged with updating - although, sadly, not shortening the name of - the International Convention for the Unification of Certain Rules Relating to the Arrest of Seagoing Ships 1952. In the meantime, things will doubtless go on pretty much as they have been for the past decade, which has been a boom period for arrests.
<P>
Most of these arrests use accepted methods, and recognised ways of finding out where the ships are going to be so that they can be arrested in a suitable jurisdiction. But there are other ways.
<P>
A ship's master recently received a telex at sea from a so-called parcel services company which said, "We have a package for you and missed you in Poland. Please advise your next port of call." Since he wasn't expecting a parcel, the master did a little detective work and found that the parcel services company's telex answerback was the same as that of a well-known claims recovery agent which acts for cargo underwriters in claims against shipowners, and which is not above seeking the arrest of ships to obtain security.
<P>
This ship had an aware master. But we would be failing in our duty if we didn't point out that there are times when shipping, like everybody else, should beware of suspect packages.
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Peru brings in ballast rules</H3>

PERU's Maritime Authority has decreed that all vessels calling at Peruvian ports must renew their ballast completely while on the high seas, at least 12 miles from the Peruvian coast. Lima-based Overseas Service Agency warns members that the new rules apply to all Peruvian ports, including the Amazon port of Iquitos. All ships entering port will be checked to ensure that their deck and engine logs record the exact date, time, location and volume of ballast water pumped out and replaced by clean seawater.
<P>
If vessels cannot change their ballast water at sea, they have to treat the tanks with Sodium Hypochlorite. The rules make ship agents responsible for informing masters in time before arrival of the clean ballast requirements.
<P>

<BR>
<A NAME="Seminars"></A>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Seminars</H3>

BILBROUGH is developing its programme of in-house seminars, and during October and November two well attended events were held. London law firm Ince & Co held a one day course on Emergency Response, covering legal implications, managing the media, oil pollution, co-ordination and communication. Canadian law firm Bull, Housser & Tupper, which has an office in Shanghai, sent its partner Clive Ansley to give a presentation to Bilbrough's staff on the current situation in China.
<P>
A Bilbrough & Co welcome suggestions for seminars and have a well appointed and flexible venue to hold them in at their Leman Street office. The seminars are normally for Bilbrough's staff, but members are welcome to attend. Queries and suggestions to Lance Johnson on +44 (0)171 772 8000.
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
SOCIAL events at the Monte Carlo committee meeting in October included a dinner party at the Yacht Club given by Sammy Ofer. The trio of gypsy musicians inspired Frank Chao to sing Italian love songs.  The following night Bilbroughs hosted a dinner party in the ornate fin-de-siecle Salle Belle Epoque at the Hotel Hermitage. Members of the committee and their ladies were joined by a number of the Club's Italian members, brokers from Italy and the Club's Marseilles correspondent. Reports that some of the hosts tried out the famous Monte Carlo Casino are true, but as all are at their desks we can assume no-one made a fortune.
<P>
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
AS the UK weather turns nasty and the days shorten, thoughts turn to traditional indoor competitions. London office staff held a darts match at the Scarborough Arms on October 29. Ergin, Wendy, Mike Berry, Pat Carter and Steve West were the winning team, followed by runners-up Paul Hinton, Moira, Jamie, Anna and Donna.
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
THE first person from Bilbroughs' Hong Kong office to get to the race track at the weekend is Cecilia Chan. She lists horse racing, gambling, mahjong, the Mark Six lottery and fishing as her hobbies. But Cecilia, who joined the office when it opened twenty years ago, does not take her work home. If she did, the petty cash would not balance, as it always has done, to the last cent. 
<P>
Another reason for not taking work home is that colleagues might have found it strange to meet her flatmate. For many years Cecilia kept a duck in her flat, and it lived to a ripe old age. She now has a dog, which she claims is very expensive to keep. But perhaps she has two homes, as she says one home is the Guardian House office, where she likes all the other staff and their families. "We socialise and go for meals together and there is a nice atmosphere," smiles Cecilia (right).<IMG SRC="images/lcn8_3.jpg" ALT="Cecilia Chan" WIDTH=130 HEIGHT=162 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM> "I've been here twenty years and I still like it."
<P>
Colleagues say that Cecilia can find a way to organise anything, which is just as well, because she has been office manager since 1988. Before that, she worked as a secretary for all the resident directors, developing her knowledge of P&I. "I knew nothing about insurance when I started," says Cecilia. "I found it confusing and a little dull." But Cecilia studied and began to understand the fascination of the cases and the negotiating at the heart of dealing with claims and members in a busy regional office. Members who call at the office have never found Cecilia dull. And if things get a little dull for her, she can always think of the weekends, when if she is
not at the races, you will find her out fishing. Who says P&I isn't a gamble?
<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
The managers go from strength to strength in their eternal tussle with London's law firms. Two convincing wins by Bilbroughs' football team against Bentley, Stokes and Lowless, and against Jackson Parton, have convinced the captain at least that Wembley is the next step.
<P>
December marks the 20th Anniversary of the opening of the Hong Kong office of A Bilbrough & Co. There will be a reception for Far East members and
correspondents, and the famous noon-day gun will be fired to mark the occasion.
<P>
Judith Scammell has rejoined the company as a Senior Systems Analyst, having
previously worked with us from 1983 until 1987.
<P>
John Walker, IT Manager and Assistant Director, retired in November after twenty years' service in the IT department. Gary Durham takes over as manager of the IT department.
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
