<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR><BR>
<BR><A NAME="chairman"><H3>CHAIRMAN'S REPORT</H3></A><BR>
<P>
At the Committee meeting in January 1996 I was elected to succeed
Russell Peters as Chairman of the Committee.  Having been a
Member of the Committee for 16 years  and Vice-Chairman for the
last four, I was honoured to accept this responsibility and
intend to provide active and energetic leadership to the London
Club in developing its business.
<P>
I wish to pay tribute to my predecessor, Russell Peters, who
provided excellent leadership as Chairman with great charm, tact
and diplomacy, during a period of steady recovery for the Club,
both in terms of financial strength and membership growth, over
the last four years.
<P>
Over the last year, the Club has made steady progress in terms of
financial strength and growth of membership and I am quite
confident that the Club is now in a position to capitalise on
this improvement by taking a larger market share of good quality
tonnage.
<P>
The balance sheet at 20th February 1996 shows assets totalling
US$372m, an increase of 5% on the previous year, and accumulated
reserves of US$81m, up from US$38m in the previous year, an
increase of 116%.  The Club has never been in a stronger
financial position.
<P>
There is no doubt that the Club is continuing to attract interest
as its growing financial strength gains recognition in the
market.  Moreover, the Club continues its very selective policy
towards new business; and the gradual improvement in the quality
of the entered tonnage over the last few years is well reflected
in the Club's favourable claims experience of recent years.  The
Club's tonnage continues to be dominated by vessels involved in
the bulk trades, with the average size of ship entered in the
Club being about 26,500 gt.  Furthermore, the Club has maintained
its reputation for good service to Members.
<P>
The Club has a reputation for having a very active Committee,
which plays a pivotal role in determining the Club's policy on
important general issues.  I feel that there is a healthy balance
in the relationship between Committee and Managers within the
Club.  The Committee respect the competence, commitment and
experience of the Club's Managers and give careful consideration
to all their recommendations but the Committee do not 'rubber
stamp' these recommendations.  Equally the Managers pay careful
attention to the Committee's views and are scrupulous in
executing their decisions.  The Committee regard it as their
proper role and responsibility carefully to examine all issues of
general importance and to consider all possible approaches,
before reaching its own decision.  As the Board of a mutual Club,
the Committee has proper regard for its duty and responsibility
towards the membership in reaching decisions on matters of
general policy which are in the best interests of the Members as
a whole.  In the Committee's view, it cannot abdicate from this
duty and responsibility or delegate it to the Managers.
<P>
It is for this reason that the Committee is sometimes perceived
to take a strong and independent line on matters of general
policy - such as the issue of limit on Club cover.  The Committee
was unanimous in rejecting the compromise proposal for limitation
on Club cover, by way of the introduction of a limit on Members'
liability for catastrophe or overspill Calls at 20% of their
entered ships' limits of liability for property damage under the
1976 Limitation Convention, on the ground that these limits,
aggregating US$20 billion for the total International Group
tonnage, were not realistically collectible; and do not protect
shipowners from the risk of financial ruin in the case of a
catastrophe.  Since that time, in April 1995, the Committee has
continued its campaign for a reduction in these limits to 2-3% of
ships' limits for property damage under the 1976 Convention,
producing an aggregate limit for the Group's tonnage of US$2-3
billion.  This would produce an overall limit on Club cover of
US$3.5 - 4.5 billion, once the Group's reinsurance contract is
taken into account.
<P>
For a long period, the proponents of the compromise proposal
identified the opposition as confined to one sector of the
shipping community.  However, it is now quite clear from the
decision reached by the Asian Shipowners' Forum at its meeting in
Hong Kong in May 1996 and from responses received from Members to
questionnaires on the subject sent by the United Kingdom, the
London, the Swedish, the Newcastle and the West of England Clubs
that the overwhelming majority of shipowners worldwide are in
favour of the limit being reduced to a realistically collectible
level.  At the moment, there is no clear agreement as to what is
a realistically collectible level, although the majority appear
to favour 2-3%.  I believe that the International Group will in
due course agree a significant reduction in the present limit;
and that the position taken by the London Club from April 1995
onwards will be fully vindicated.
<P>
Another matter of common concern to shipowners is the current
cost of the Group's reinsurance programme.  For the five Policy
Years up to 1995/96, this programme has cost the Group US$1.6
billion, whilst claims paid and outstanding total US$317m, a loss
ratio of 20%.  The Club will argue for a substantial reduction in
premium cost on the next renewal, whether involving substantial
increases in the Group's retention of risk or developing new
markets for the placement of this programme.
<P>
When the Committee elected me as Chairman, it also elected Peter
John Goulandris and Robert Alexander Ho as Vice-Chairmen.  Peter
John is Chairman of the International Tanker Owners Pollution
Federation and a leading and respected figure within the tanker
industry.  Robert has recently played a very active and
enthusiastic role within the insurance committees of the Hong
Kong Shipowners' Association and Asian Shipowners' Forum and has
done much to alert shipowners in the Far East to the implications
of the compromise limitation proposal.
<P>
Indeed, I was pleased to make a trip to the Far East in May 1996,
with Graham Edmiston and Lance Johnson of the Managers, visiting
Hong Kong at the time of the Intertanko and Asian Shipowners'
Forum meetings, and then to Kuala Lumpur and Singapore.  I met
many of our Members and other prominent shipowners.  I was
impressed by the steady growth of shipping in that area and by
the very good reputation which the London Club enjoys in the Far
East, which its very active Hong Kong office under John Williams
has clearly helped to establish.  My trip to the Far East leads
me to hope that the Club will continue to develop its business in
that part of the world, notwithstanding the tough competition
between Clubs.
<P>
The last year has been a very active one for the Club, with the
move to Leman Street and the corporate restructuring in Bermuda;
and I wish to express my personal thanks and that of the
Committee to the Managers for their commitment and dedication to,
and energy and enthusiasm for, the affairs of the Club which have
given it fresh vigour.
<P>
I sincerely hope that this augurs well for the future and that my
period in office as Chairman of the Committee will coincide with
steady growth in the Club's size and importance.  I have no doubt
that the Club has all the basic ingredients for success amongst
the Committee, Members and the Managers, and that we can look
forward to the future with confidence.  I will certainly do all
that is within my power to see that the Club fulfils all of its
present promise.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
