<A NAME="Top"></A><B><FONT  SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT  SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT  SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association - </FONT><FONT  SIZE=+1>About this site</FONT></B>
<P><IMG SRC="images/anilogo1.gif" ALT="Animated LSSO logo" WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60 ALIGN=right>
<BR>
This site has been created to serve a number of purposes:<BR>
<UL><LI>A conduit for communications into the Club, from Members, Correspondents, brokers and all other interested visitors. To move to our pages of contact information, click <A HREF="contact.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Contact info for the Managers and Correspondents worldwide'; return true">here</A>.
<P>
<LI>A means of making information about the London Club, and the P&amp;I industry, available to a wider readership.
<P>
<LI>A means of making the most up-to-date information available to Members and Correspondents, between our issue of publications on paper.
<P>
<LI>A useful resource for any visitor with an interest in maritime industries, including an up-to-date selection of web links. Click <A HREF="#Links" onMouseOver="self.status='List of related web links';return true">here</A> to move to our annotated list of web links.
</UL>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Management of the site</H3>

<H4>Compatibility</H4>
The site was created using the <a href="http://www.sausage.com"; onMouseOver="self.status='Sausage Software Home Page';return true"><IMG SRC="images/hotdog.gif" height=15 width=16 hspace=4 ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM  border=0><strong>Hot Dog Pro</strong></a> Web Page Editor, and Netscape <A HREF="http://home.netscape.com" onMouseOver="self.status='Netscape Home Page'; return true"><IMG SRC="images/navigatr.gif" height=15 width=16 hspace=4 ALIGN=ABSBOTTOM border=0><STRONG> Navigator</STRONG></A> browser software. It has been tested using Mac and Windows editions of Navigator versions 2.02 and 3 - the current <EM>de facto</EM> world standard browsers (Summer 1996). It may not appear at its best using another browser; if any features of the site fail to work (such as the animated <A HREF="#Top" onMouseOver="self.status='Let me have another look: I must have missed it before...'; return true">logo</A> at the top of this page, or the client-side image-<A HREF="contact.htm#Correspondents" onMouseOver="self.status='Select area from a world map, then select country'; return true">map</A> of the Association's Correspondents around the world), I would recommend switching to Netscape. 
<P>
Also, if you are using earlier versions of Netscape, it is worth upgrading. Version 2.02 for Windows seems more stable than version 2.01, and version 3 seems slicker and more capable still. New content added after 19 August 1996 will be enhanced for Navigator 3, which can be found at the touch of this button:<A HREF="http://home.netscape.com" onMouseOver="self.status='This recommendation does not create any legal relationship...'; return true"><IMG WIDTH=88 HEIGHT=31 SRC="images/netnow3.gif" ALIGN=TOP BORDER=0 HSPACE=4 VSPACE=0></A> 
<P>
At present I do not recommend Microsoft's Internet Explorer, versions of which have been remarkably slow and had difficulty with certain graphics, or have crashed when accessing the <A HREF="#Links">links</A> below. It may be that the final release of Internet Explorer version 3 fixes these problems.
<P>

<H4>Updating schedule</H4>
The information in this site will be updated whenever suitable new material is ready for publication, but we shall remove anything which becomes out-of-date whether or not there is new material ready to replace it. For the moment, the site will be managed in-house at Bilbrough's London Office, enabling very fast updates to be made.
<P>
Members can therefore rely upon this site to contain the most up-to-date information available about the Club - more so than paper publications.
<UL>
<LI>The London Club News will be posted approximately every two months,<BR> and
<LI>The StopLoss Bulletin will be posted quarterly<BR>
<BR>
 - the posting dates being published in advance on the <A HREF="newslets.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='The London Club News and StopLoss Bulletins'; return true"> Newsletters</A> page<BR><BR>
<LI>Stop Press items may appear at any time without notice, but will be flagged from the <A HREF="home.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='London Club website Home Page';return true">Home</A> page and the <A HREF="newslets.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='The London Club News and StopLoss Bulletins'; return true">Newsletters</A> page<BR>
<BR>
<LI><A HREF="contact.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Contact info for the Managers and Correspondents worldwide'; return true">Contact and Correspondents</A>' information will be updated as we receive it
</UL><BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="Links"></A>
<H3>Links to other web sites</H3>
All web sites now seem to have numbers of links to other sites, but often these are listed without any hint of what one can expect to find, which invariably wastes time. With this in mind, the following focussed list is not intended to be an exhaustive survey of the maritime web - although by moving through sites which <I>are</I> trying to provide such a service, <A HREF="#Jump-off" onMouseOver="self.status='Jump-off points to other nautical web sites';return true">listed below,</A> it should be possible quickly to navigate to a specialist maritime topic which is not in our list. 
<P>
If you have any suggestions for other web sites which would enhance the usefulness of our list, please let us know their names and URLs. Also, if you find any of these links have become dead ends, please lets us know and we will update the list. Click here for a pre-addressed <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co';return true">e-mail</A> form.
<P>

<H4>Resources for the commerical shipping world</H4>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.seanet.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='SeaNet -  general commercial shipping site';return true" target=_top>SeaNet</A><dd>- various resources targetted at shipmanagers, owners and charterers, including news, weather, a trading area, and dedicated areas for different aspects of shipping, and further information for SeaNet subscribers
<DT><A HREF="http://www.fairplay-publications.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='Fairplay Magazine, current press releases, and much info';return true" target=_top>Fairplay Magazine</A><dd>- the latest published issue, plus up-to-date press releases, the Fairplay shipping database, links to other web sites with brief notes and other resources (some of which are available to subscribers only)
<DT><A HREF="http://www.llplimited.com" onMouseOver="self.status='LLP Limited - publishers of Lloyds List';return true" target=_top>Lloyds List</A><dd>- daily newspaper on Shipping, Insurance, Energy, Trade and Finance; website subscribers will have access to an enhanced version of the full text of the day's paper
<DT><A HREF="http://www.open.gov.uk/maib/maibhome.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='UK Government Marine Accident Investigation Branch home page';return true">UK Government Marine Accident Investigation Branch</A><dd>- includes summaries of the official investigations for UK-registered vessels, and a concise collection of links to related web sites
<DT><A HREF="http://www.dot.gov/dotinfo/uscg/" onMouseOver="self.status='The US Coast Guard home page';return true">US Coast Guard</A><dd>- they state: "Our goal is to provide the public with as much information as possible about the Coast Guard and its worldwide missions and activities" - this includes an enormous collection of links to other maritime web sites
<DT><A HREF="http://www.shipguide.com" onMouseOver="self.status='Carrier shipping schedules webpage';return true">Electronic Shipping Guide</A><dd>- a database of container shipping schedules of over 60 carriers for voyages in and out of the U.S. and Canada - to be expanded to worldwide during 1996 - along with Port News and Information pages and separate lists of links for carriers, ports worldwide, agents/services and "other" 
<DT><A HREF="http://www.seanet.co.uk/baltic00.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Baltic Exchange home page';return true">Baltic Net</A><dd>- home page for the Baltic Exchange, London's shipping-related trading floor
<DT><A HREF="http://www.seanet.co.uk/classifi/marassoc/chamber/cham00.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='UK Chamber of Shipping home page';return true">UK Chamber of Shipping</A><dd>- home page for the trade association for British shipowners and shipmanagers
<DT><A HREF="http://thunder.met.fsu.edu/~nws/buoy/" onMouseOver="self.status='Automated marine meteorology webpage';return true">Interactive marine observation</A><dd>- an up-to-date visual interface to automated marine weather stations worldwide 
</DL>
<A NAME="Jump-off"></A><H4>Jump-off points to other nautical web sites</H4>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.efn.org/~jkohnen/boatlink.html" onMouseOver="self.status='The Boatlink collection of web links';return true">Boatlink</A><dd>this dedicated links website, in attempting to be a comprehensive jump-off point for the nautical web, is organised into about thirty categories, most links being annotated with a one-sentence description...
<DT><A NAME="GENS"></A><A HREF="http://www.gens.no/" onMouseOver="self.status='The GENS maritime server';return true">GENS</A><dd>a maritime information provider based in Norway, with commercially-<WBR>orientated links divided by category into simple lists. GENS calls itself "The Professional Maritime Server", where "you can get an overall view of the entire shipping industry"
<DT><A HREF="http://www.mglobal.com/" onMouseOver="self.status='Marine Global Net home page';return true">Marine Global</A><dd>another commerical access-point for the marine side of the internet with categorised lists of links; this home page is rather high-tech, requiring a large screen and an up-to-date browser, but as with GENS, the lists are rather sparse and not annotated
</DL>
<H4>Sundry</H4>
<DL>
<DT><A HREF="http://www.whoi.edu/" onMouseOver="self.status='Independent American oceanography institution';return true">Woods Hole</A><dd>the independent American oceanographic research institution's home page, "dedicated to the study of all aspects of marine science and engineering and to the education of marine scientists and engineers"
<DT><A HREF="http://www.cf.ac.uk/uwcc/masts" onMouseOver="self.status='Dept of Maritime Studies, University of Wales, Cardiff';return true">Department of Maritime Studies and International Transport, University of Wales, Cardiff</A><dd>the academic angle on the maritime and transportation industries, including its own focused links page; this department has also been funded by the International Transport Workers Federation to research ways of bringing seafarers into the mainstream internet community
<DT><A HREF="http://www.lib.utexas.edu/Libs/PCL/Map_collection/Cartographic_reference.html" onMouseOver="self.status='The Perry-Casta&ntilde;eda Library Map Collection, University of Texas';return true">The Perry-Casta&ntilde;eda Library Map Collection, University of Texas</A><dd>this collection contains maps of the world prepared by the US Central Intelligence Agency, sorted into "current interest" and by region, including the most up-to-date political maps.  It also has links to other cartographical web sites
<DT><A HREF="http://www.marineart.com" onMouseOver="self.status='Reference information for marine art, photography, museums, etc., and on-line gallery';return true">The Marine Art Information Centre</A><dd>a picture gallery of marine art and photogaphy, with information on marine art auctions, galleries, history, photography, reference materials and museums
</DL>
<BR>
<P>
