<BODY BGCOLOR="#90C4FF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">


<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association</FONT></B>
<P><BR>
<FONT  SIZE=+2 COLOR=#350060>Report and Accounts</FONT><BR>
<FONT  SIZE=+1 COLOR=#350060>Year ended 20 February 1996</FONT><P>
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<BR>
<FONT  COLOR=#350060><H3>Extracts from the Association's 1995/96 Report and Accounts</H3>

<P><BR><A NAME="managers"></A><H3>REPORT OF THE MANAGERS</H3><BR>
<P>
<H4>Financial Position</H4>
During 1995/96 the London Club's financial position continued to
strengthen significantly and the Balance Sheet as at 20th
February 1996 shows the strongest ever financial picture.  Assets
stood at US$371.778m, an increase of 4.8% on the previous year,
and accumulative reserves had more than doubled to US$81.481m
from US$37.689m a year earlier.  As noted below under
"Presentation of Financial Information" the statutory solvency
margin which the Club is required to meet by the United Kingdom
Department of Trade and Industry is covered 4.82 times, thus
providing a reasonably comfortable buffer.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Class 5 - Protecting & Indemnity</H4>
1992/93 Policy Year was formally closed by the Committee in 1995,
and its credit balance was transferred to the Closed Year fund. 
After taking account of movements in outstanding claims estimates
on previous closed Policy Years, the resulting balance on the
Closed Year fund of US$38.6m was then transferred to the Calls
Equalisation Account, in accordance with previous practice.  A
new US$50m Contingency Account has been established by a transfer
from the Calls Equalisation Account, leaving a balance of US$3.8m
on that account.
<P>
1993/94 Policy Year, which is scheduled to be closed formally by
the Committee in 1996, now shows a credit balance of US$18.4m. 
1994/95 Policy Year, in respect of which a 30% Supplementary Call
was levied in August 1995 (compared with the original estimate of
40%), now shows a small credit balance of US$1.5m.
<P>
1995/96 Policy Year shows a deficit of US$12m after taking credit
for the 30% Supplementary Call to be levied in August 1996
(again, compared with the original estimate of 40%).  However,
recent history suggests that this deficit is likely to shrink or
disappear, as the projection of Incurred But Not Reported claims
reduces, and additional investment income is allocated to the
year.
<P>
After adding in Unrealised Gains on investments of US$16.1m,
which are not allocated to Policy Years, the total balance for
the Class stands at US$77.8m, which compares with an equivalent
balance at 20th February 1995 of US$34.0m.
<P>
First indications show that claims costs in 1996/97 Policy Year
may be running higher than in the last few years, but at this
early stage of the year, give no undue cause for concern.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Class 8 - Freight, Demurrage and Defence</H4>
It was noted in the 1995 Managers' Review that the Class had
experienced a very substantial increase in costs in respect of
one claim, arising in the closed 1990/91 Policy Year, and the
reserve in respect of that claim has again increased during the
course of the 1995/96 financial year.  However, the credit
balance resulting from the closure of 1992/93 Policy Year led to
a transfer from the Closed Year fund of US$2.4m to the Calls
Equalisation Account, which now stands at US$5.1m.
<P>
Small deficits are shown in respect of each of the open Policy
Years, but it is anticipated that these deficits should reduce or
disappear as a result of a reduction in the IBNR element of the
outstanding claims estimates, and additional investment income. 
After taking account of Unrealised Gains on investments of
US$1.1m, the overall surplus of the Class stands at US$1.6m.
<P>
The Optimum Calling Philosophy which was adopted by the Committee
in 1990 for Class 5 - P&I, has led to early Supplementary Calls
being levied in respect of that Class.  However, the potential
volatility resulting from unexpected escalation in cost of the
occasional expensive claim incurred in Class 8 has persuaded the
Committee that the Optimum Calling Philosophy is not appropriate
for this Class.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Presentation of Financial Information</H4>
The Club prepared its Financial Statements as at 20th February
1994 and 1995 in a format which anticipated the requirements of
the EU Insurance Accounts Directive, passed into law in the
United Kingdom as the Companies Act 1985 (Insurance Company
Accounts) Regulations 1993; these Regulations are now mandatory
for British insurance companies.  Most Members will now be
familiar with the statutory format.  However, some additional
data has been included in the Financial Statements as at 20th
February 1996, providing a full and explicit picture of the
Club's financial position.
<P>
The following list summarises the principal enhancements.  The
Committee, and the Managers, would be pleased to consider any
ideas for further disclosure which Members, and other interested
parties, might care to submit.
<P>
<STRONG>1. Reinsurance Premiums: Contribution to other Associations' Pool Claims.</STRONG><BR>
The treatment of Pool claims has been somewhat inconsistent, as
paid Pool claims have been treated as reinsurance premiums,
whereas outstanding Pool claims have been treated as outstanding
claims.  The Club's contributions to all Pool claims, whether
paid or outstanding, are now shown as reinsurance premiums, and
1995 figures have been accordingly restated.
<P>
<STRONG>2. Outstanding Claims.</STRONG><BR>
For the best part of a decade, Consulting Actuaries have assessed
Incurred But Not Reported ("IBNR") uplifts to add to the
Managers' estimates in respect of the cost of notified claims. 
It makes sense for the IBNR element of the total outstanding
claims to be shown separately, and Note 16 - Technical Provisions
- Claims Outstanding provides a complete breakdown of the
constituent elements of the Technical Provisions shown  in the
Balance Sheet.
<P>
<STRONG>3. Debtors - Members.</STRONG><BR>
The amount written-off as bad debts is now shown, in addition to
disclosure of the Provision for Doubtful Debts.
<P>
<STRONG>4. DTI Return.</STRONG><BR>
The Club is required to submit an annual Return to the United
Kingdom Department of Trade and Industry ("DTI"), in a prescribed
format.  A copy of the full DTI Return is included for the first
time within the Financial Statements, for the convenience of
Members and other interested parties.
<P>
The statutory solvency margin which the Club is required to meet,
as at 20th February 1996, is US$18.156m.  The excess of available
net assets over the required minimum margin is US$69.275m, and
therefore the statutory solvency requirement is covered 4.82
times.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Corporate Restructuring</H4>
Over the last two or three years it has become increasingly
apparent that the corporate structure allowing the Club to
reinsure the majority of its risks with its subsidiary companies
was outmoded. 
<P>
The Committee wished to continue to take advantage of the Club's
location in the United Kingdom, bringing with it the benefit of
the ability to trade freely in Europe, and to be regulated
intelligently and sympathetically by the Department of Trade and
Industry.  UK tax legislation, however, was potentially
unfriendly to the parent-subsidiary relationship operating
between the Club and its wholly-owned reinsurer, London & Bermuda
Reinsurance Co. Ltd. ("London & Bermuda").
<P>
In January 1995 the Committee agreed to move towards a more
efficient structure.  After examining several ideas, the
Committee decided upon a parallel structure as being the most
appropriate arrangement whereby reinsurance would be effected
through a contract with a parallel mutual organisation, to be
owned by the Members of the Club.  By this means the Club could
remain British, but could also avoid the potential tax pitfalls
of a parent-subsidiary reinsurance arrangement. 
<P>
At the behest of the Members in 1978, a suitable mutual company,
The London Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association
(Bermuda) Limited ("LSSO Bermuda") had been set up in Bermuda but
had never traded, and this company was therefore activated in
1995.  Its Board operates independently of the Club's Committee,
with only one common member, Mr. R.A. Peters who stood down as
the Chairman of the Club in January 1996, and immediately assumed
the Presidency of LSSO Bermuda.
<P>
From 20th February 1996 LSSO Bermuda has reinsured 90% of the
Club's P&I and FD&D risks.  Following arms-length negotiations
between London & Bermuda and LSSO Bermuda, the former company's
liabilities have been assumed by the latter company, the
consideration being the major part of London & Bermuda's assets. 
The remaining assets are expected to be repaid to the Club during
the course of 1996, by way of dividends, following which London &
Bermuda will be rendered dormant.
<P>
The present Board of LSSO Bermuda comprises:<BR>
<UL>
<LI>Mr. R.A. Peters - President
<LI>Mr. N.B. Dill - Vice-President
<LI>Mr. C.T. Collis - Vice-President
<LI>Mr. D. Ezekiel - Vice-President and Managing Director
<LI>Dr. D. Saul
<LI>Mr. R. Rans
<LI>Mr. S. Tsitsopoulos
<LI>Mr. S. Kellner
<LI>Mr. E-O. Nedelmann
<LI>Ms. M. Coye is the Secretary.
</UL>
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Investments</H4>
A highly conservative investment policy was followed from the
third quarter of 1994 until  October 1995, with about half the
funds being held as cash.  In October 1995 two additional fixed
income fund managers were appointed by London & Bermuda,
respectively to manage a short term ultra-conservative US
Treasury portfolio, and an international top-quality bond
portfolio with currency hedging.
<P>
At 20th February 1996, therefore, London & Bermuda had three
fixed income portfolios amounting in total to US$207m and a
US$57m US Equity portfolio.  LSSO Bermuda agreed to continue to
use the same investment managers as London & Bermuda, but have
subsequently also appointed a fifth investment manager to manage
a global non-US equity portfolio, whilst the appointment of a
further equity manager is also anticipated.
<P>
Investment returns were much more satisfactory in 1995/96 than in
the previous year.  The total investment return, including
Unrealised Gains on investments, amounted to US$38.048m,
representing a return on the average total assets (including
debtors etc.) of 10.5%, and a return on invested funds of 13.2%.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Reinsurance</H4>
The Chairman has emphasised the London Club's concern about the
cost of the Group's reinsurance programme.  An initiative,
referred to as "Designated Reserves", was commenced in 1992, and
has now been fully implemented, to strengthen Clubs' ability to
rely upon each other financially so that, if necessary, pooling
could be very considerably expanded, thus reducing dependence
upon market reinsurance arrangements, during periods of adverse
market conditions.  At the time of writing, in July 1996, it does
appear likely, however, that very significant reductions in the
cost of reinsurance for 1997/98 should be achieved.
<P>
The Club continues to
benefit from its very worthwhile and beneficial relationship with
European reinsurers, who provide protection for claims within the
Club's retention, including protection against the Club's
contribution to its own Pool claims.  To date, no claims have
been made under these reinsurance arrangements which have now
been in place for three years.  The Group has taken 15% vertical
co-insurance of the first layer of the Group Excess Loss
Reinsurance Contract, and therefore limited additional cover has
been purchased for 1996/97 to protect against a string of very
large claims falling upon this co-insurance layer.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Membership</H4>
The Club's directly entered tonnage continued to grow during
1995/96 and at 19th February 1996 stood at 26.97m gt - an
increase during the year of 1.18m gt.  The majority of this
increase resulted from new purchases by existing Members and the
Club continues its very selective policy towards new business;
and continues to concentrate on vessels involved in bulk trades,
with the average size of ship entered in the Club being about
26,500 gt.
<P>
On renewal at 20th February 1996, the Club suffered the
disappointment of losing one major fleet and this was the
principal reason for a reduction in the Club's directly entered
tonnage on renewal to 25.26m gt.  Since 20th February 1996, the
tonnage has increased to 25.67m gt.
<P>
Notwithstanding the loss of a major fleet on renewal, and the
consequent reduction in entered tonnage, the general trend in the
Club's business remains upward and positive, with the Club
continuing to attract interest, and business, from leading
shipowners.  The Club's improving reputation has enabled it to
pursue a rigorous attitude towards both existing and new
business.  The Club has declined to renew entries, where the
Member's performance has proved unsatisfactory, in terms of ship
condition and maintenance and in payment of premium, and the Club
adopts restrictive criteria in the acceptance of new business,
declining to quote on much of the business which it is offered. 
Although this restrictive policy militates against a rapid
expansion in the Club's tonnage, it is also the main reason for
the Club's improved claims experience in recent years.  The Club
presently enjoys the best Pool claims record of any Group Club.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Limit on Club Cover</H4>
At a specially convened meeting in London on 10th November 1995,
the Committee decided to follow the lead taken by the
Boards/Committees of ten out of the thirteen International Group
Clubs in agreeing to implement the compromise proposal for the
introduction of a limit on a Member's liability for a catastrophe
or overspill claim at 20% of his entered ships' limits of
liability for property damage under the 1976 Limitation
Convention, with effect from 20th February 1996.  If the
Committee had continued to reject the compromise proposal, the
London Club would have been excluded from the International
Group's Pooling Agreement.  At the same time, the Committee
determined to continue its efforts to promote awareness amongst
shipowners and their associations of the implications of the
compromise proposal and to continue to press for the introduction
of a limit on Club cover for all claims at a realistically
collectible level.
<P>
In January 1996, the Committee heard that responses to a
questionnaire sent by the UK Club to its Members indicated
overwhelming support for its Board's longer term strategy of
seeking to achieve a limit on cover at a realistically
collectible level.  Furthermore, in May 1996 the Asian
Shipowners' Forum also decided that the limit on Club cover had
to be reduced to a realistically collectible level and that the
constituent associations comprising the ASF would encourage their
shipowning Members to lobby their Clubs for a reduction in the
current limit.
<P>
In April 1996 the London Club sent a questionnaire to its
Members, and Members representing 72% of the Club's directly
entered tonnage have replied.  Of those replies, 90% are in
favour of ship's limits for overspill calls being reduced to 2-3%
of ships' Convention limits and 4% would like to see the
percentage reduced to 1%.  The polls recently sent to Members by
the Swedish, Newcastle and West of England Clubs have produced a
similar response from a broad geographical spectrum of their
Members.
<P>
It is quite clear from the position now taken by the Asian
Shipowners' Forum and from the responses to recent Club
questionnaires that opposition to the very high limit introduced
by the compromise proposal is broadly based and is spreading
amongst shipowners around the world.
<P>
The Committee is therefore confident that, in due course, sanity
will prevail and that the Group will agree on a reduction in the
limit on Club cover to a level which is realistically
collectible.  Moreover, the position adopted by the Committee at
the start of this debate, when the compromise proposal was first
circulated in April 1995, appears to have been vindicated by
later events and to be supported by a majority of the world's
shipowners.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Oil Pollution</H4>
According to figures from the International Tanker Owners
Pollution Federation (ITOPF) the world tanker industry spilled
the least amount of oil in 1995 (5,000 tons) than in any other
year since the ITOPF started keeping records 25 years ago.  
However, two spills are likely to prove costly, since they
occurred in the same area of South Korea where there is extensive
fish and seaweed farming, and were from Korean tankers in the
same Hoyu Tankers fleet, entered in the UK Club.
<P>
Although the "SEA PRINCE" only spilled 700 tons of bunker fuel,
pollution claims approaching US$300m have arisen, which greatly
exceed the limit of US$87m available under Civil Liability
Convention (CLC) and the International Oil Pollution Compensation
Fund (IOPCF).  The "HONAM SAPPHIRE" spilled about 1,000 tons of
crude but claims arising are expected to stay within the CLC
limit of US$20m.
<P>
In February 1996, the "SEA EMPRESS" spilled 75,000 tons of crude
off Milford Haven in the UK.  The oil affected some 100
kilometres of coastline, consisting of sandy beaches and cliffs,
much of it part of the Pembrokeshire Coast National Park, a
nature reserve, and although the clean-up was conducted quickly
and efficiently, substantial claims are expected for damage to
the environment and also from the local fishing and tourist
industries which are likely to be seriously affected.  Claims are
presently estimated at between US$50m and US$72m.
<P>
For much of the last twelve months shipowners and the
International Group have lived in the hope that pressure from the
shipping industry in Washington would lead to legislative changes
to OPA 90 resulting in some alleviation of the burden placed on
shipowners in obtaining Certificates of Financial Responsibility
(COFRs) for US trading.  However, the industry is now resigned to
the fact that no legislative changes to OPA 90 will take place
during the present US Congress and for at least some time after
the Presidential election in November 1996.  Indeed the Group has
been advised by its Washington counsel that no relaxation of the
COFR requirements will take place without the agreement of the
environmentalists, who are a powerful political lobby.
<P>
At a recent Congressional oversight hearing on OPA 90 COFR
regulations, a US shipowner testified that his firm had sustained
major losses in 1995 due to the cost of compliance with COFR
requirements and that shipowners are now divided between
'winners', who are sufficiently substantial to self-insure and do
not have to pay additional premium costs and 'losers', who cannot
self-insure and must assume the 'enormous expense' of purchasing
COFRs from one of the COFR guarantor insurance schemes available,
First Line or Shoreline.  The annual premium cost to shipowners
of obtaining COFRs through these schemes has been estimated at
US$60 - US$70m; and these charges cannot be included in
Worldscale and therefore, as a matter of course, passed on to
Charterers.  At the recent oversight hearing, an industry
spokesman asserted that the COFR requirement 'provides no added
value to the US consumer, or the US public' and 'simply provides
nothing more than a piece of paper, a ticket to trade to the US,
[with] no additional protection and no additional cover'. 
Shipowners have talked of the desirability of developing a
shipowner - or Club - sponsored COFR scheme, but to date none has
materialised.
<P>
In January 1996 the US National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration (NOAA) issued its Final Rule on the use of Natural
Resource Damage Assessment (NRDA) by OPA 90 - designated trustees
(federal, state, American Indian tribal, and foreign officials)
against responsible parties involved in oil spills under OPA 90,
and these regulations subsequently came into effect.
<P>
Unfortunately, the NOAA has taken very little notice of strong
and well argued criticism of their previous proposals by the
International Group and other industry groups; and the most
objectionable features of earlier drafts have been retained.  The
Rule gives the trustees the power to use a considerable variety
of different methods to assess environmental damage, including
Contingent Valuation Methodology (CVM) to determine non-use or
passive use values, the use of simplified assessment procedures,
including unproven computer models and compensation formulae and
the power to use recoveries to fund chosen regional restoration
projects.
<P>
The American Petroleum Institute (API) has filed an appeal with
the Federal Court of Appeals in Washington seeking judicial
review of the final regulations and the International Group and a
number of industry groups have intervened in support of this
action.
<P>
On 30th May 1996 important changes took place in the law
governing compensation for pollution in most major maritime
states - apart from the USA - with the entry into force of the
1992 Protocols to the Civil Liability Convention (CLC) and the
Fund Convention 1971.
<P>
The main change is an increase in compensation from the previous
limit of 60m SDRs (about US$87m) to a new maximum of 135m SDRs
(about US$200m).  As before, the first tier of compensation is
paid for by the shipowner and his Club under CLC - the limit
being based on a sliding scale according to the tonnage of the
ship concerned up to a maximum of 60m SDRs (about US$87m) - and,
in larger cases - the second tier is available from the
International Oil Pollution Compensation Fund (IOPCF).  The
shipowners' proportion is significantly increased; but the
Protocols have been strongly supported by the shipping and
insurance industries as they maintain the viability of a system
which has worked very well in practice over the years, to the
advantage of claimants and industry alike.
<P>
One improvement introduced by the 1992 Protocols is to limit
claims for damage to the environment to the cost of reasonable
measures of reinstatement actually incurred or to be incurred. 
The need for this restriction became apparent from the "HAVEN"
case (146,000 tons spilt in Italy in 1991) in which the Italian
Government presented a claim for environmental damage of US$362m
without any evidence in support.  Claims of this nature have the
effect of prejudicing the interests of genuine victims of the
spill such as fishermen, hoteliers and others with undoubted
claims for loss of income, since they threaten a situation in
which all claimants must accept reduced settlements.
<P>
The tendency for Governments or national agencies to pursue
speculative claims for alleged economic loss and non-economic
loss against the IOPCF has protracted the resolution of claims
arising from a number of major spills in recent years, including
the "HAVEN", the "AEGEAN SEA" (80,000 tons spilt in Spain in
1992) and the "BRAER" (84,000 tons spilt in the Shetlands, UK, in
1993).  Claims for damage to the environment are invariably based
upon the premise imported from the USA and enshrined in the
concept of NRDA that even a single spill causes permanent damage
to the environment.  However, there is very little scientific
evidence that spills have significant adverse long term effects
on the environment, provided they are properly and  promptly
cleaned up.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Hazardous and Noxious Substances</H4>
A recent IMO diplomatic conference held in London in April/May
1996 resulted in agreement on a new International Convention on
Liability and Compensation for Damage in connection with the
Carriage of Hazardous and Noxious Substances (HNS) by Sea and
also of a Protocol to the 1976 International Convention on
Limitation of Liability for Maritime Claims (LLMC Convention)
which increased shipowners' limits of liability for personal
injury and property damage by 235%.
<P>
The HNS Convention and the 1976 Limitation Convention were
considered by the conference together since the International
Group and International Union of Marine Insurers ( IUMI) had
consistently maintained that unless there was 'linkage' between
the two Conventions, that is, unless HNS claims were initially
dealt with in the general limitation fund constituted under the
Limitation Convention, with the HNS Convention providing a
supplementary fund in respect of HNS claims, the capacity of the
insurance market would be greatly reduced.
<P>
In the event, it was not possible to achieve linkage of the HNS
Convention with earlier  general limitation Conventions since
linkage could have created gaps in claimants' compensation.  This
would have arisen if a shipowner had been able to limit his
liability under a general limitation regime at a lower level than
his liability limits under the new HNS Convention.  Such a
situation would have arisen if the ship concerned was registered
in a state which had not adopted the HNS Convention but caused
damage in a state which had done so, and where both states were
party to the same general limitation regime.
<P>
The HNS Convention introduced two tiers of compensation, the
first being strict liability and compulsory insurance for
shipowners with a sliding scale limit based on the ship's tonnage
with a minimum liability of 10m SDRs (US$15m) for ships up to
2,000 gt and a maximum liability of 100m SDRs (US$150m) for ships
of 100,000 gt and over.  The second tier of liability consists of
an International HNS Fund, to be funded from levies on HNS
receivers in contracting states, with a limit of 250m SDRs
(US$375m).
<P>
The International Group argued that the substantial increase in
the limits under the 1976 Limitation Convention was not justified
once linkage was abandoned.  Their arguments were ignored.
<P>
The high levels of limitation introduced by the HNS Convention
and the Protocol are a disappointment to many shipowners but the
Group has acknowledged that the HNS Convention maintains
international uniformity of maritime law and recognises the
principle of shipowners' rights to limit liability and the
principle of liability sharing between shipowning and cargo
interests.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Salvage</H4>
The International Convention on Salvage came into force on 14th
July 1996, having been adopted in April 1989 to replace the 1910
Brussels Convention.
<P>
The new Convention combines the traditional 'no cure no pay'
principle, under which a salvor is only rewarded for his services
if the operation is successful, with a provision under Article 14
for enhancement of the salvage award to take account of the
salvor's skill and efforts in preventing or minimising damage to
the environment and also for Special Compensation to be paid to
salvors who have failed to earn a reward in the normal way by
recovery of property.  The compensation allowed consists of the
salvor's actual expenses, plus an uplift, which will not normally
be more than 30% of these expenses - but in exceptional
circumstances may be up to 100%, if environmental damage has been
minimised or prevented - and fair rates for his own men and
equipment.  These so-called 'safety net' provisions under Article
14 have been incorporated into the latest versions of Lloyd's
Open Form of Salvage Agreement, most recently LOF 95.  Special 
Compensation claims under Article 14 are covered by the P&I Clubs
and a Code of Practice has now been agreed between the
International Salvage Union and the International Group for
cooperation between the salvor and the P&I Club when salvage
services involve pollution prevention and a claim for Special
Compensation.
<P>
Nevertheless there is concern on both sides as to how Article 14
is operating in practice and is being applied by salvage
arbitrators and by the Courts, with salvors taking the view that
they are receiving inadequate compensation whilst the Clubs take
the view that they have no proper control over services being
performed for their account and indeed that the Salvage
Convention and LOF 95 do not represent satisfactory means of
determining salvage liability.  At the same time there are clear
signs of crisis in the salvage industry.
<P>
With these considerations in mind, the International Group
recently determined to investigate, in consultation with
shipowners, underwriters and salvors, whether an alternative
contractual arrangement to LOF could be developed with salvors.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>The ISM Code</H4>
For the majority of vessels the certification process under the
International Shipmanagement (ISM) Code is scheduled for
completion by the end of July 1998.  It appears that there are a
considerable number of Owners and vessels which have yet to
commence the process of compliance with the Code and doubts have
been raised as to whether the task can be completed within the
time available.  Some major trading nations have indicated that,
so far as they are concerned, there will be no extension to the
time limit and vessels without the requisite ISM certification
will not be allowed in their jurisdictions after July 1998.
<P>
Shipowners' compliance with the ISM Code could have effects not
originally contemplated by those drafting the legislation.  The
Code requires senior levels of management to be fully involved in
all safety and operational matters and a designated person or
persons, with access to the highest level of management, who is
responsible for monitoring the safety and pollution prevention
aspects of each vessel's operation.  This means that if claims
for damage or injury arise from casualties or accidents due to
breaches or failures in shipmanagement safety systems or
procedures, it will be more difficult for the shipowner to invoke
the defence that he exercised due diligence to make the ship in
all respects seaworthy prior and at the commencement of the
voyage.
<P><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>
<H4>Class 8 - Freight Demurrage & Defence</H4>
In the 1995/96 Policy Year, 783 ships were entered for Freight
Demurrage & Defence cover, which number compares with 729 in
1994/95 and 689 in 1993/94.  However, in contrast to this steady
increase in entered ships, the number of new disputes notified to
the Managers during these policy years has slightly reduced, 669
new cases being notified in 1993/94, 666 in 1994/95, and 570 in
1995/96.
<P>
However, the total amounts paid against these years, namely
US$3,788,151 in 1993/94, US$3,309,884 in 1994/95, and
US$4,420,714 in 1995/96, suggests that, while the timing of the
payment of legal costs in any particular dispute will always be
somewhat fortuitous, there has been an increasing cost in going
to law and, hence, a continuing need for the Managers to exercise
vigilance in the supervision of disputes.
<P>
The reduction in the number of disputes being referred to the
Managers for handling is possibly a consequence of Members'
ability to resolve potential disputes in their infancy, and
perhaps also reflects an increasing dissatisfaction in the
shipping community at large with the cost, in terms of both money
and time, of legal proceedings.  This attitude is reflected in
the Managers' policy of handling as many FD&D cases in-house as
is consistent with achieving the best results for Members, and,
when instructing lawyers to handle the more complex disputes,
ensuring that the cases are run on an efficient and cost-effective basis.  In this respect, there is evidence of an
increasing tendency amongst lawyers in general, and London
solicitors in particular, to be more competitive over their legal
charges and this will hopefully contribute in time to a
moderation in the cost of litigation.
<P>
A deeper analysis of Freight Demurrage & Defence costs in the
1995/96 Policy Year also reveals the fact that, as between
London, New York, and other jurisdictions, London is by far and
away the preferred jurisdiction, with London lawyers, in
consequence, benefiting to the exclusion of their brethren
elsewhere.  Of the total costs paid to lawyers (as distinct from
non-legal correspondents, surveyors, consultants, experts and
arbitrators) in 1995/96, US$2,419,103 was paid to UK lawyers,
while US$521,276 was paid to US lawyers and US$790,260 to lawyers
in other jurisdictions. 
<P>
The more substantial litigation or arbitration will inevitably
produce the heaviest legal costs and this is illustrated by the
fact that five major cases accounted for 26%, or US$1,153,569, of
the costs paid in the 1995/96 Policy Year.  The nature of cases
giving rise to these costs were an unlawful arrest in Algeria, a
total loss involving an indemnity action against charterers, a
claim against loss of hire underwriters, a general charterparty
dispute, and a drydocking dispute.
<P>
The continuing popularity of London jurisdiction for the
resolution of disputes, and more especially London Arbitration,
is demonstrated by the fact that, of the 33 cases referred to the
Association's Committee for support in 1995/96, 23 involved
London Arbitration proceedings and 4 involved English High Court
proceedings.  As is perhaps traditional and predictable, some 30%
of these cases involved disputes over the non-payment of hire or
off-hire, while 20% of the cases involved claims for demurrage.
<P>
Consistent with the Managers' objectives of handling Freight
Demurrage & Defence disputes in-house and of striving to provide
Members with the service which they demand, namely careful and
timely advice, the Managers have recruited three young lawyers
over the last year to join the other ten lawyers within the
Managers' London, Piraeus and Hong Kong offices. It may be of
interest to note that their legal qualifications have been earned
in England, Louisiana and South Africa.

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>

