<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>London P&amp;I Club</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association - </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>NEWS</FONT></B>
<BR>
<BR>
Leading Article from <EM>Lloyd's List</EM>, 21 August 1996
<P><BR>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica, Swiss">
<H3>Restless spirits</H3></FONT>

<FONT SIZE=+2></FONT>IT may not be the biggest P&amp;I club in existence, but the medium-sized London Club has established a singular reputation for taking a markedly independent line on matters which it regards as issues of fundamental principle.
<P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
   Last year at the time of its annual report it was taking an uncompromising stance on the limit of club cover.
<P>
   With some markedly strong-minded members from Greece and the Far East and a management which likes to take account of their views, it perhaps was not surprising that the London Club's committee was unanimous in rejecting the compromise proposal put forward to International Group members.
<P>
   It was, pointed out the London Club committee, "not realistically collectable", with the limits providing owners with little real protection from the risk of financial ruin in the case of a catastrophe.
<P>
    A year has passed and this year's annual report notes that the London Club still fights its corner on this important issue, continuing its campaign for a reduction in these limits to 2%-3% of ships' limits for property damage under the 1976 Convention.
<P>
   And, according to chairman J M Lyras, it would appear that this unequivocal line is at long last gaining more general support.
<P>
   Certainly, a strong message of impatience at the status quo comes from the Far East, where the recent Asian Shipowners' Forum found strong support circulating for a limit reduction.
<P></MULTICOL><CENTER>...</CENTER><P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
   A similarly strong line is being taken by the club on the current cost of the International Group's reinsurance programme, with the London members, described as "restless" on this point, arguing for a "substantial reduction" on premium cost at the next renewal.
<P>
   The club is arguing from a position of some financial strength, having more than doubled its reserves last year. One suspects that its tough-minded members will be unlikely to favour much compromise in this direction.
<P>
   It is a message that the insurance world needs to take on board. For some years now, after <EM>Exxon Valdez</EM> and the anticipation of US horrors, there has been the suggestion that marine insurance is predicated upon catastrophe.
<P>
   Luck has a lot to do with it, but there is another side to the story; one in which the incidence of major maritime loss has been inexorably reduced. Last year saw the smallest amount of marine losses ever, and the quantity of pollution reduced to unprecedented levels.
<P>
   It is time, argue the strong-minded shipowning members of mutuals, that reinsurers recognised reality.
<P></MULTICOL><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>

<BR><BR>
