<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>London P&amp;I Club</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association - </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>NEWS</FONT></B>
<BR>
<BR>
Article from <EM>Lloyd's List</EM>, 21 August 1996
<P><BR>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica, Swiss">
<H3>P&amp;I clubs seek huge reinsurance cost cuts</H3></FONT>

<BR>
<EM>By Liz Shuker</EM><P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT> MASSIVE cut in the cost of shipowners' liability reinsurance will be sought by the world's leading protection and indemnity clubs next year.
<P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
   The 16 major P&amp;I clubs, which together insure more than 90% of the shipping fleet, will be looking to cut up to a third off the price of the International Group reinsurance contract when terms are renegotiated in February.
<P>
  The clubs have threatened to reduce their reliance on commercial reinsurance if underwriters cannot meet their pricing requirements.
<P>
   "Shipowners will not tolerate the huge amount of money going out of the industry. It is unjustified and there must be change," said Bryan Gaze, deputy chairman of the London P&amp;I club.
<P>
   Mr Gaze, who is a member of the International Group reinsurance sub-committee, expressed his personal view that the programme should cost "in the order of $200m".
<P>
   Shipowners paid $330m for their reinsurance cover this year.
<P>
   Although clubs enjoyed a good, solid relationship with their principal insurers, they "had paid too much" in the past, Mr Gaze said.
<P>
   The contract - the largest reinsurance policy in the world - covers shipowners for liability claims falling between $30m and $1.53bn, and is largely underwritten in London.
<P>
   About 80% of the risk is placed in the Lloyd's market, with additional participation from the London companies market, and Bermuda-based reinsurers such as Ace and XL.
<P>
   While softness in worldwide reinsurance markets resulted in a $58m reduction in the price of the contract this year, there remains concern that it is overpriced in relation to the clubs' loss record.
<P>
   Shipowners have paid $1.6bn for the policy in the five years preceding February 1996.</MULTICOL><P><HR WIDTH=5% ALIGN=center SIZE=1><P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
   By contrast, reinsurers have paid out just $317m in claims, producing an abnormally low loss ratio of 20%.
<P>
   The clubs believe this warrants a major price reduction, and according to Mr Gaze, they will resort to more self-insurance if the terms offered by reinsurers next year are not acceptable.
<P>
   The clubs fired a warning shot to this effect earlier in the year by increasing their participation in the first, and most exposed, layer of the reinsurance contract from 10% to 15%.
<P>
   The move was described by one club as "a message to the market that self-insurance can be preferable to the price of reinsurance".
<P>
  Financial trusts established in Bermuda this year will also guarantee clubs' commitment to high-level losses, permitting them to self-insure with more confidence.
<P>
  Meanwhile, large reductions in the cost of reinsurance would benefit the overwhelming majority of the world's shipowners, who have seen the cost of their P&amp;I insurance escalate in recent years.
<P>
   The extent of the discount received by owners entered in the International Group clubs will depend on members' individual loss records and ship type, although it is likely most shipowners would receive substantial reductions in premium.
<P></MULTICOL><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
