Content-type: text/html
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>London P&amp;I Club</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association - </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>NEWS</FONT></B>
<BR><BR>
Leading Article from <EM>Insurance Day</EM>, 21 August 1996
<P><BR>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica, Swiss">
<H3>Like-minded</H3></FONT>

<BR>
<MULTICOL COLS=2>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A </FONT> CLUB, be it a sporting institution or an association of philosophic thought, is an institution of the like-minded. It functions best because of this unanimity of purpose and it is sensible that those who dissent seek solace elsewhere. P&I clubs are little different in this respect and although the historical mutuality might be tempered by the use of claims pooling, the best club is one in which the members are encouraged to set the same course and are more effective for this unity of purpose.
<P>
   It is interesting to see the common features exhibited by the membership of the London P&I Club, despite their considerable geographical diversity. They are members of a medium-sized club, but operate mostly big ships. They tend to be specialists in bulk shipping, in both dry and wet trades. And they have a substantial membership in both Greece and the Far East; a membership which tends to express itself forcefully on matters of 'mutual' interest.
<P>
   The London, according to its chairman John M. Lyras, likes to think of itself as a 'conservative' club with a traditional view of mutual insurance and indeed the operation of ships. 
<P>
   There is a high proportion of very serious shipowners who run family fleets, and their values clearly communicate themselves to other members. It is significant to see the common ground that is increasingly held between the members from the Far East,  who number some very big players with modern and growing fleets, and those from the older shipping families of Greece.
<P>
    It is significant that the growing impatience of the Asian shipowners with the northern Europeans does not seem to communicate itself to the Greeks. And that is crucial, too, because the increasing participation of the Asians in such associations must be encouraged at all levels. Asia needs to be properly represented in terms of the tonnage that is owned in this region. This is, after all, where the growth is to be found.
<P></MULTICOL><CENTER>...</CENTER><MULTICOL COLS=2><P>
   The alternative, of some sort of global divide with Asian owners developing their own institutions to duplicate those of the West must be considered wasteful, and a very real risk. The institutions of Europe need to be very mindful of the risks of such a geographic schism. 
<P>
   If Europe gets it wrong, the shipping world could find itself hopelessly divided, with Asian representative institutions, Asian insurance systems, Asian opinion hardening against 'old-fashioned' European maritime ideas. Any institution that brings the like-minded of these important regions together must be unreservedly welcomed, and the efforts of the London Club in this respect are to be commended.
<P>
     Any club, it has been said, must have a strict policy on new membership, lest its aims and objectives be diluted, and it is notable that that the London Club has "declined to quote on much new business". 
<P>
   Market share becomes second to shared values and possibly this is important too. P&I underwriting is a singular branch of insurance, but it is forcibly brought home, in times when the hull market appears to be softening fast, that it is the quality of the clientele that is invariably more important than the number of ships entered or even the spread of risk. 
<P>
   A restrictive policy on membership is nothing to despise, if the end product is a smaller group of people that can be comfortable with each other and agree upon their collective policies on important issues. The markedly independent line taken by the London on issues like club cover limits last year, and its current campaign on reinsurance costs is indicative of the sort of confidence which is produced by like minds.
<P></MULTICOL><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>

<BR><BR>
