<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>London P&amp;I Club</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association - </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>NEWS</FONT></B>
<BR><BR>
Article from <EM>Insurance Day</EM>, 21 August 1996
<P><BR>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica, Swiss">
<H3>International Group seeks reductions of $100m in reinsurance costs</H3></FONT>

By Claire Wilkinson
<P>
<EM>Call for P&amp;I premium cut is played down</EM>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>A </FONT>N attempt by the International Group of P&amp;I clubs to secure reductions of at least $100m in their reinsurance costs was yesterday played down in the Lloyd's market.
<P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
"P&amp;I clubs are always trying to keep reinsurance costs down to a minimum. This is nothing new," said a leading Lloyd's underwriter heavily involved in the programme who preferred to remain anonymous.
<P>
    Members of the International Group of P&amp;I clubs, comprising 16 clubs, paid out around $330m in reinsurance costs last year and some believe this could be reduced by more than $100m next year.
<P>
    However, a leading Lloyd's underwriter said the P&amp;I clubs were posturing and that calls for reductions were unlikely to affect rates next year.
<P>
   "This is a specialised area which has undergone a few years of beneficial loss experience and rates have reacted favourably and probably will do so some more. However, we are a long way from February 20 (the renewal date) and there is plenty of time for major casualties between now and then," said the underwriter.
<P>
   "Obviously market forces will affect rates but not individual statements by clubs about what they expect. I do not anticipate dramatic reductions in rates to follow," he added.
<P>
   The issue was brought to the fore yesterday as the London P&amp;I club expressed concern about the cost of the International Group's reinsurance programme in its 1995-1996 annual report.
<P>
   "For the five policy years up to 1995/96, this programme has cost the group $1.6bn, while claims paid and outstanding total $317m, a loss ratio of 20%. The club will argue for a substantial reduction in premium costs on the next renewal," said London Club chairman John Lyras.
<P></MULTICOL><CENTER>...</CENTER><P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
   An initiative begun in 1992, known as Designated Reserves, had been fully implemented to strengthen clubs' ability to rely upon each other financially.
<P>
   The initiative allows for considerable expansion of pooling, reducing the clubs' dependence on market reinsurance arrangements, during periods of adverse market conditions.
<P>
   "At the time of writing, in July 1996, it does appear likely, however, that very significant reductions in the cost of reinsurance for 1997/98 should be achieved," the club's report said.
<P>
   Michael Hill, underwriting director at the London Club, added: "The fact that clubs do have designated reserves whereby we are in a better position to take a larger part of the risk ourselves, means we will take more of the risk if we cannot get the right premium."
<P>
   He confirmed that members of the International Group had already increased their level of self-insurance to 15% in 1996, up from 10% in 1995.
<P>
   According to its annual report, the London Club now has total assets of $372m and an accumulated reserve of $81m, up from $38m last year. Investment return for the year was 13.2%.
<P></MULTICOL><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>

<BR><BR>
<BR><BR>
