<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>London P&amp;I Club</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">

<B><FONT SIZE=+2>The</FONT> <FONT SIZE=+6>L</FONT><FONT SIZE=+2>ondon Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association - </FONT><FONT SIZE=+1>NEWS</FONT></B>


Article from <EM>Insurance Day</EM>, 21 August 1996
<P>
<FONT FACE="Arial, Helvetica, Swiss">
<H3>Liz Shuker's P&amp;I focus</H3>
<EM>London Club says that Far East owners will be the key to drive to reduce limit on clubs' exposure</EM></FONT>

<H4>Cosco adds its weight to the cover cap lobby</H4>
<MULTICOL COLS=2>
<FONT SIZE=+2>P</FONT>RESSURE from Asian shipowning giants such as the China Ocean Shipping Company (Cosco) will be a decisive factor in reducing the limit on P&amp;I cover, claims the London P&amp;I Club.
<P>
The club believes the industry will be unable to ignore the strength of feeling in favour of a lower cap in the Far East, given that the influence of the region's shipowners will stretch into the next century.
<P>
   Details of the club's recent survey on the issue showed 34% of replies were from the Far East. A further 45% were from Greek members, and 20% from Europe and the Near East.
<P>
   Cosco, one of the largest shipowners in the world, has opted to support a $2bn cap on overspill after considering the potential exposure of the various options.
<P>
   Funding a claim of $3.5bn, shipowners' maximum exposure under the limit suggested by Cosco would require club members to pay an overspill call roughly equal to 100% of their supplementary, considered by Cosco to be a manageable figure.
<P>
   Although the owner has the largest vessel entries in the UK, West of England and London clubs - avid supporters of a low limit - it also has tonnage entered in the Steamship Mutual which has yet to come out for or against a reduction in the limit.
<P>
   The size of the company and growth projections means it wields considerable clout within the P&amp;I industry.</MULTICOL><P><CENTER>...</CENTER><P><MULTICOL COLS=2>
   "The Asian owners took a bit longer to analyse the situation, but once they did, they reached the same conclusion as shipowners in other areas - that the limit must be brought down," said John Lyras of the London Club.
<P>
"Statements such as that made by Cosco cannot be ignored."
<P>                                                     
The club believes the limit can realistically be reduced in time for the 1998 renewal.
<P>
It was sceptical about increasing the clubs' reinsurance cover to meet a lower limit - quite apart from the cost implications for the clubs.
<P>
   Although it is possible that current reinsurance capacity could support a $3.5bn-worth of cover, thereby eliminating overspill calls under a 2% limit, there would be significant concerns over reinsurers' ability to honour such high cover, said the club, particularly if there were more than one claim in any year.
<P>
   Security had always to be borne in mind when buying reinsurance protection, said Bryan Gaze, the club's deputy chairman.
</MULTICOL><P><CENTER>...</CENTER><P>
<MULTICOL COLS=2>
   Announcing its results for 1995/96 yesterday, the club said it was now enjoying the strongest financial health ever.
<P>
   Club assets are up from $285m three years ago to $372m, while reserves have been increased by $43.79m to $81.48m - described as a "comfortable rather than excessive" cushion.
<P>
   Much improved investment returns, as enjoyed by all clubs last year, contributed $38m to the overall result, against just $400,000 in the previous year.
<P>
   Greater selectivity by the managers has also contributed to another year of moderate claims, and the club recorded the best pool record of the International Group clubs during 1995/96.
<P>
   More tonnage was rejected than accepted by the club during the year, leading to an improvement in the average age of its members, which now stands at 16.5 years, against the worldwide average of 18 years.
<P>
   Average size of members also leapt to 26,500 gt, or 40,000 dwt, by far the highest in the group, and in line with the club's philosophy to focus on bulkers and tankers.
<P>
   The club believes recent efforts by classification societies and governmental bodies to remedy the historically poor safety record of bulkers makes them one of the most highly regulated ship types, a factor which could have a beneficial effect on the club's overall claims record.
<P>
   The club believes it is now poised to take over a larger share of the P&amp;I pie, and could become a large, medium-size club in future.
<P></MULTICOL><HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=3><BR>

