<HTML>
<HEAD><TITLE>Back issues - London Club News</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFE0" LINK="#000080" VLINK="#400080" ALINK="#004000">
<A NAME="Top"></A>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn_logo.gif" ALT="London Club News logo" WIDTH=202 HEIGHT=58 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 ALIGN=right>
<H2>The London Club News</H2>
<H4>Issue 7 -<br>
October 1996</H4>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<H3>In this issue</H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="#Claims" onMouseOver="self.status=''; return true">Proactive approach reduces claim costs</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Corres" onMouseOver="self.status=''; return true">Correspondents - a two-way commitment</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Undertaking" onMouseOver="self.status=''; return true">Letters of undertaking - an essential part of the P&amp;I system</A>
<LI><A HREF="#Pandiman" onMouseOver="self.status=''; return true">Pandiman - focus on Philippines correspondent</A>
</UL>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="Claims"><H3>Proactive approach reduces claim costs</H3></A>
THE refocusing of the London Club's business on more substantial owners operating larger vessels has reduced both the cost and volume of claims. It has also had a significant effect on the way in which larger P&amp;I claims are handled. 
<P>
The reduction in the numbers of smaller claims has enabled the club's managers to concentrate their own resources and to become much more proactive and aggressive when helping members deal with individual cases, particularly the larger ones. 
<P>
The managers had been concerned for some time that the traditional approach of reacting to events was depriving members of the opportunity to defend claims in the most effective manner. 
<P>
The refocusing of resources and the adoption of a new proactive approach involves making a commitment, at the outset, to collecting information about the cause of a casualty and establishing the issues which would determine the outcome of the claim. 
<P>
A strong investigating team is formed with the objective of painting as complete a picture as possible within a short time. In this way, it is possible for the member and the club to establish an aggressive claims handling strategy, with a degree of certainty that there will be no unpleasant surprises later to throw the plan off course.
<P>
There is now emerging a pattern of claims development, over the club as a whole, which indicates that the new approach is reaping rewards.
<P>
The graph reproduced below shows typical policy years in terms of reported claims developments for the 1980s and the 1990s. When compared, it will be noted that the shape of the two developments is quite different.
<P>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn7_1.gif" ALT="Typical claims development" WIDTH=398 HEIGHT=277 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 ALIGN=middle></CENTER>
<P>
Whereas during the 1980s it took four years from the beginning of each policy year before sufficient information was available to enable the full cost of claims to be assessed, development over recent years shows that it now takes two years or less.
<P>
Even more significantly, during the 1980s the estimated total cost of claims then remained relatively constant as time passed, implying that, as individual cases were being negotiated and litigated, any good news was being balanced by adverse developments. But, in the 1990s, the overall estimated cost of claims has tended to reduce after their value has been assessed, which indicates that the ability to establish and maintain a claims handling strategy in each individual case avoids adverse developments, and produces better results.
<P>
This approach demands teamwork and a change in claims handling culture. It requires the owner, the club and the various other support services such as lawyers, club correspondents and surveyors to share the same objective.
<P>
In various sectors of all these industries there is a tendency to minimise the level of response and to hope for the best. It has been argued that the proactive approach simply encourages claimants to be more aggressive.  But the club's recent claims results show that this is not the case, and the managers are determined to improve on this even further.
<P>

<BR>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Undertaking"><H3>Loss Prevention</H3></A>

CLUB letters of undertaking are an essential part of the P&amp;I system. They can save shipowners large sums of money by providing rapid and effective security when club members are faced with claims. But recent cases in South Africa have highlighted how lawyers acting for cargo interests can sometimes use the threat of demanding bank guarantees instead of accepting a letter of undertaking as a means of advancing their claims.
<P>
In some parts of the world, notably New Zealand, a letter of undertaking from an International Group P&amp;I Club has the same legal status as a bank guarantee, although, in most countries, courts will actually demand bank guarantees. In direct dealings with claimants, however, club letters of undertaking will very often be acceptable.
<P>
Claimants' lawyers in South Africa recently offered to accept a letter of undertaking as security for a cargo claim, but only if the member admitted that as vessel owners they were also the "carrier" of the cargo under the bill of lading. This would have put the member at a disadvantage, and the club refused to provide  letters of undertaking on such forms, preferring to put up a bank guarantee instead. The club makes every effort to provide letters of undertaking when members need security, and understands that this sort of case can cause delay and expense for owners. But members do understand that the club cannot allow the legal position of its members to be compromised simply in order to save bank charges or limited delay.
<P>
<I>For information on the club's loss prevention activities call Lance Johnson on +44 (0)171 772 8000, or send an email for his attention using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co'; return true">form</A>.</I>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Corres"><H3>Correspondents - a two-way commitment</H3></A>
<TABLE><TD>A P&amp;I club correspondent is at the sharp end of delivering service to club members. It is to the correspondent that the hard-pressed shipmaster turns  with a problem, and the correspondent that must sort out tangled problems with local bureaucracy. Bilbrough prides itself on working closely with members, and the quality of the correspondents it appoints to represent it around the world is crucial. Garry Stevens,  the claims adjuster
in Bilbrough's London office who has recently taken over the day-to day responsibility for correspondents, says, "There's a two-way commitment. We have to make an effort to retain our links with correspondents even when there is a low level of work for them to do. The service we offer is very important to us, and the correspondents have to be as efficient as we are."
</TD><TD>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn7_2.jpg" ALT="G Stevens" WIDTH=182 HEIGHT=142 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1><BR><I><FONT  SIZE=-1>Garry Stevens will be helping the club to strengthen its links with correspondents</CENTER></FONT></I><br><br>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P>
Under the guidance of Ian Ferguson, the director with overall responsibility, Garry Stevens will be sharpening  the manager's focus on the worldwide network of club correspondents. "We don't often change correspondents," says Garry Stevens. "We've had relationships with some going back almost a hundred years. But it is too easy to lose touch. We are going to work hard to strengthen our links with our network, and we shall be looking for our correspondents to respond to that.
<P>
"We look for correspondents which are small firms with the right mix of expertise. Ideally, they should also be dedicated to P&amp;I work and have access to a wide range of local legal and technical advice. That means, in effect, that we encourage them to work for other clubs."  But conflicts of interest are rare.
<P>
Garry Stevens is expanding the information on correspondents which is already
available on the club's Internet Web Page. There, the interactive map of
correspondents leads members directly to the details of the local correspondent. "We will be putting further information behind that," says Garry Stevens, "so members and our own staff can get quickly to details of people in the organisation and the skills available. We want to receive information from correspondents, and we want to know what is happening in their country, even when there are no problems. We are going to take a critical look at our relations with all our correspondents, and set out to encourage those we don't hear from to understand the importance of keeping us up to date with local events which affect our members."
<P>
Bilbroughs also sees the role of the correspondent as one of lobbying for the P&amp;I movement as a whole. 
<P>
"It is one of the roles of the correspondent to educate local officials and other bodies as to what P&amp;I clubs are, what they can do, and what they can't do," says Garry Stevens.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>London Club makes its voice heard</H3>
P&amp;I clubs have an important and influential voice in the international shipping industry. On this website you will find a <A HREF="../stop_prs.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Recent published articles by the London Club Managers'; return true">selection of articles from the international shipping press</A> which illustrate how the London Club uses that voice in the best interests of its members.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=RIGHT WIDTH=50%><FONT SIZE=-1><EM>A LUNCHTIME reception was recently held by the club at the Yacht Club in Piraeus. It was well-attended by members, prospective members and others. Pictured here at the reception are, left to right, John M Lyras, chairman of the London Club, Tony Mavrakakis, Piraeus-based club member, and A Bilbrough &amp; Co chairman Graham Edmiston.</EM><TD ALIGN=CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn7_3.jpg" ALT="Greek Reception" WIDTH=286 HEIGHT=192 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1></FONT></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<P>
<UL>
<EM><LI>The club's Piraeus office has moved temporarily to 15-17 Hatzikyriakou while its premises are being refurbished. Contact numbers remain the same. It is hoped the refurbishment will be completed by the end of the year.
</UL></EM>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Pandiman"><H3>Pandiman - focus on Philippines correspondent</H3></A>
FREDDIE Clemo won't necessarily  be the first person you meet when you visit the offices of Pandiman Philippines Inc, the club's correspondent in Manila. But Freddie is such a flamboyant character that it would not require a great leap of imagination to believe that he might be the first person you meet when you arrive in the Philippines.
<P>
Freddie, a UK shipping executive, arrived in the Philippines in 1950. He worked there for US Lines until 1968, when he retired and entered into a partnership with Filipino colleagues to represent a number of foreign shipping companies in the local market. In 1977, Freddie (right),<IMG SRC="images/lcn7_4.jpg" ALT="F Clemo" WIDTH=133	 HEIGHT=153 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>became a naturalised Filipino citizen and assumed sole proprietorship of Aquila Maritime Business Inc, which in 1982 launched Pandiman as a registered correspondent for P&amp;I clubs. 
<P>
Freddie has two right-hand men, both of them women - Cora Tabuena, who has just been promoted to co-manager, and Celia Ordinario, who, in addition to her other duties, spends a lot of time monitoring the effects of ITF contracts and the new regulations governing Filipino crew employment.
<P>
Freddie values his long association with the London Club. He says, "The personal relationship between us has greatly added to the effectiveness of claims handling procedures."
<P>
Freddie is a legendary figure in Philippines shipping circles. He is also one of a select band of shipping people to be awarded the MBE. When asked why he was given it, Freddie say, "One never knows what it is for, although they did say it was due to my efforts to promote British interests in the Philippines." And the rest.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Social News</H3>
Assistant director Willie Constantine retired from A Bilbrough & Co on August 27, after more than 9 years of service as a claims adjuster. A presentation was made at a retirement party in the boardroom. At the same time, a presentation was made to Ernie Chaplin, assistant director, to mark his forty years of service with the company.
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Colleen Halsey has joined the company as an audio typist for the 3rd floor claims team.
<P>
<LI>Andrew Sissons has joined the company as an office junior/postal clerk.
<P>
<LI>Richard Sacre has transferred from the post room to the filing department as a filing clerk.
<P>
<LI>Donna Sievey has transferred from the filing dept to help desk assistant within the IT dept.
</UL>
<BR>
It has been a very busy period on the sports and social front.
<P>
<STRONG>Cricket</STRONG>. The final two matches of the season were played against Ince &amp; Co and Jackson Parton. Sadly, both matches ended in defeat for Bilbroughs, neither of them on a legal technicality.
<P>
<STRONG>Football</STRONG>. An inter-office boys v girls match was played at Spitalfields Market. Both teams conducted themselves honourably in the encounter, and reputations remained unblemished. A six-a-side match was played against Steamship Mutual, and Bilbrough's victorious run continued.
<P>
<STRONG>Sailing</STRONG>. The last in the autumn series of races took place at Millwall Docks. The team came third overall out of nine entrants.
<P>
<STRONG>The Annual Pensioners' Lunch</STRONG> was held in the boardroom, attended by a total of 51 pensioners and guests. 
<P>
And the <STRONG>Annual Staff Outing </STRONG>was held at Walthamstow Greyhound Stadium. Hardly any shirts were lost.
<P>
