<BR>
<A NAME="Limit"><H3>Massive support for lower limits on cover</H3></A>
<TABLE><TD>THE overwhelming majority of London Club members say they want a substantially lower limit on overspill calls. Members with over seventy per cent of the club's tonnage replied to a
questionnaire seeking their views on the present twenty per cent compromise and its alternatives.
Members with ninety-five per cent of the tonnage were in favour of a lower limit, and most of
those, ninety per cent, called for overspill calls to be limited to between two and three per cent
of entered ships' Convention limits. Eighty-four per cent of those members went further, and
supported the idea of fixing limits at a level at which the International Group could obtain
reinsurance, which would leave members with no exposure at all to overspill calls.</TD><TD>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn6_1.jpg" ALT="G Edmiston" WIDTH=110 HEIGHT=110 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1><BR><I><FONT  SIZE=-1>Graham Edmiston says members from right across the club's membership support a lower limit on overspill calls</CENTER></FONT></I><br><br>
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
Chairman of A Bilbrough & Co, Graham Edmiston, says, "We are encouraged by this level of
support, and especially by the fact that it has come from right across the spread of membership."
Forty-five per cent of the replies were from Greek tonnage, thirty-four per cent from the Far East and twenty per cent from Europe and the near East. 
<P>
"We have seen other clubs in favour of a limit receive similar support from their members," says Mr Edmiston. "We now believe that once the clubs in favour of a realistic limit agree on what 
that limit should be, they can win the support of the remainder of the International Group to that limit. There is growing acceptance that last year's compromise has not laid this difficult and divisive subject to rest, and that a lower limit will have to be agreed if group unity is to be maintained."
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Results"><H3>Assets and reserves up</H3></A>

THE LONDON P&I Club's reserves surged by $43.79m to $81.48m during the 1995-96 policy
year, following several years of mild claims experience. And a strong investment return of 11.79
per cent for the year has boosted assets. "The club has never been in a stronger financial
position," says John M Lyras, chairman of the London Club.
<P>
The 1996 accounts for the London Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association, approved
by the committee on July 3, show that the balance available in excess of estimated outstanding
claims has risen to $53m, or nineteen per cent of the claims. "We have worked hard to develop
this strong position," says Bryan Gaze, deputy chairman of A Bilbrough & Co. "We want to make
sure our members will not be faced with unexpected supplementary calls." A succession of years
with good claims experience has helped develop the reserves.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<TABLE><TR><TD ALIGN=CENTER WIDTH=60%><IMG SRC="images/lcn6_2.jpg" ALT="Bunga Mas Satu" WIDTH=280 HEIGHT=155 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1><BR>
<FONT SIZE=-1><I>The 1995-built Bunga Mas Satu was recently entered with the London Club.<br>
The 7,998 gt vessel is owned by MISC, which is one of the top ten members of the club, with well over half a million gross tonnes of entered tonnage.<br>
MISC has been a member of the London Club since 1969.
</FONT></I></TD></TR></TABLE><BR>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Poland"><H3>Pollution of Polish waters</H3></A>

CLUB members are exposed to substantial penalties for even negligible oil pollution in a variety
of jurisdictions. The most recent confirmation of this comes from Poland, where the club's
correspondent, Morska Agencja Gdynia (MAG), warns that "there is no direct connection
between the amount of fines imposed for pollution and the amount of pollutant leaked".
<P>
MAG points out that there is a strict obligation under Polish maritime law to inform port state
control of any trace of pollution of whatever nature. In the case of oil pollution, masters should immediately inform the local club correspondent and, where necessary, take samples and help with any investigation carried out by the Polish Maritime Board.
<P>
MAG says that fines for minor oil pollution in the port of Gdansk rarely exceed $10,000, but in
the port of Gdynia fines are never less than $50,000. Incidents of pollution in Polish territorial waters, meanwhile, are deemed much more serious, and fines imposed amount to "hundreds of thousands of dollars".
<P>
Fines imposed in Poland for pollution of Polish maritime waters are immediately 
executable under local law. Cash or appropriate bank guarantees covering the amount of any fine
are required by law.
<P>
It is therefore important that members exercise the utmost care and attention to pollution 
prevention and, where necessary, to reporting procedures, in whatever part of the world they are
operating to.
<P>
<I>For information on the Club's loss prevention activities call Lance Johnson on +44 (0)171 772 8000, or using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co';return true">e-mail form</A>.</I>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="Partners"><H3>Good partners</H3></A>

Why use one P&I club rather than another?  Some owners might say rates matter most. Every owner wants to minimise expenditure on insurance. But the great majority look beyond the rate they pay for P&I cover. 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn6_3.jpg" ALT="A Mavrakakis" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=110 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left>Anthony Mavrakakis (left), a Piraeus-based tanker owner, has been a member of the London Club for five years. His fleet has been entered at various times with other group clubs, but he says he expects that any new tonnage he gets will go to the London Club. "I came to the London Club because of my personal link with Graham Edmiston, of Bilbroughs," says Mr Mavrakakis. "But we are very satisfied with the club. They are always there if we need help."
<P>
Mr Mavrakakis says club managers should be partners with the members. "They should act as if we were all in the same business," he says. "I think Bilbroughs thinks like that." Part of that way of thinking is helping owners when they need it, without being a soft touch for owners who should know better. Mr Mavrakakis says, "What makes a good club is well-organised members who don't waste the club's time. That way, the managers have time for the good members when they need it." Mutuality means equal time and support for each member. "We can call when we need help, and we get it," he says. "Bad members cost the rest of us, and good members have less claims anyway. We see that Bilbroughs is careful and selective and takes only good members."
<P>
Having a local office is a major point for Mr Mavrakakis. "Bilbroughs has a fully staffed Piraeus office, and we find that very useful," he says. "It is part of the professional attitude that I like. They identify with the owner's needs, not the manager's needs. Even when they employ a surveyor or a lawyer you get the feeling that they are working for the member. With some clubs it can feel that they are working to protect the managers or the club, which is not the same thing. Clubs are there to protect members against third party liabilities, not to protect the managers of the club."
<P>
What about representation? "It would be constructive if other clubs chose really professional
members for their boards, not just people who will give the managers an easy ride," insists Mr
Mavrakakis. "Too many clubs choose directors who are their friends, or who are yes-men," he
says. "It is much better for everyone to have owners on the board who have some real input. I am
very happy that the London Club and Bilbroughs think this way."
<P>
Does the question of limitation of liability influence his choice of  P&I Club? "My main concern
is that when I have a problem I am covered," says Mr Mavrakakis. "The exact limit on cover is
less important than the question of how it is fixed. We should be consulted, and listened to before these decisions are made. Bilbroughs does tell us what is going on, and it does listen to what we say. I like that."  
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Toxic"><H3>Toxic cargo problems</A></H3>

A NUMBER of incidents involving problems arising from the carriage of thiourea dioxide have
been drawn to the attention of the club's claims handlers. Overheating has resulted in claims for corrosion, discolouration and odour both to these cargoes and to other cargoes stowed in the same hold of the ship.
<P>
Thiourea dioxide is a moisture- and heat-sensitive toxic solid which, when shipped in plastic
bags in containers, can break down and begin to overheat and combust. It is not listed as a
hazardous cargo in the IMO dangerous goods code, but it is known that, when it starts to break
up, it produces sulphur dioxide, which is an irritant to the eyes, skin and respiratory system. 
<P>
Investigations into the causes of the overheating and combustion are continuing. Meanwhile,
members are warned to exercise extreme care when dealing with this cargo.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="NYPE"><H3>NYPE agreement updated</A></H3>

THE International Group of P&I Clubs has updated the Inter-Club Agreement on the apportionment of cargo claims under the New York Produce Exchange charterparty. 
<P>
The 1996 Agreement follows the same basic format as the previous agreements which have become industry standard clauses over the last twenty-five years. The changes made since the last revision in 1984 broaden the definition  of cargo claims to include related customs  dues and fines and certain interest and costs. Claims arising under Through Transport or Combined Transport bills of lading are allowed, provided the damage was caused while the cargo was in the vessel. 
<P>
The Agreement now also applies to the Hamburg Rules and includes modification to the time bar provision. 
<P>
The club will be distributing copies of the new agreement to members, and it urges them to adopt it for all charterparties on the NYPE forms or the Asbatime Form 1981. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="STCW"><H3>Brazil gets tough on STCW</A></H3>

PORT authorities in Brazil are taking strong action against ships which fail to produce certificates of crew competence on demand.
<P>
The club's correspondent in Santos, Representacoes Proinde Ltda, reports that four vessels - each flying a different flag - were recently detained by the port captain after failing to produce the  necessary documentation. 
<P>
Both national and foreign-flag vessels should ensure that they have on board the necessary certificates of crew competence - together with originals or properly authenticated photocopies of classification documents - in order to facilitate clearance through Brazilian ports. Failure to do so will oblige the owner or operator to arrange for replacement of the master and crew by
suitably qualified personnel. The alternative is for the ship to be barred from calling at Brazilian ports.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME"Web"><H3>On the web</A></H3>

KEEN as ever to keep ahead of changes in technology, the London Club has set up an internet
website. "This is an important enhancement of our service to members," says Bilbroughs director
Lance Johnson.
<P>
The site has been designed for speed and ease of use. Initially, it will hold information about the club and the insured risks, copies of The London Club News and StopLoss Bulletins, plus an
online database of the club's correspondents around the world, which will be updated as changes
occur.
<P>
The London Club website can be accessed on http://www.lsso.com
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME"Brokers"><H3></A></H3>
