<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Social News</H3>

The Bilbroughs cricket team has refrained from tampering with any balls, and has managed a
respectable fifty per cent loss ratio in matches against Sinclairs, Richards Butler, Holmans and
Andrew Weir.
<P>
Congratulations to the football team, who beat the West of England  3 - 1 at Southwark Park, and
who were Plate Winners at the Lloyd Thompson Summer Football Tournament. The Plate came in useful at the barbeque which followed.
<P>
Bilbroughs boasts considerable nautical expertise, which helped at the Brookes Bell dinghy
sailing evenings held over the last three months. Bilbroughs came third out of eight teams, and
Marcus Bucknall was third on the helms ladder. But the hot air in Ian Carter's boat did not
increase its speed, although he did admit later that if he had put the centreboard down he would
have performed better.  
<P>
Bilbroughs staff will be going to the dogs for their annual party, to be held at Walthamstow
Greyhound Stadium on September 17.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>First Person</H3>

IF Martyn Hughes were a library book, he would be carrying a hefty fine. The London Club
borrowed him in 1990 and never gave him back. Today, he heads up the club's office in Piraeus,
which looks after the interests of its Greek membership.
<P>
The club borrowed Martyn, a qualified solicitor, from Holmans early in 1990 for "a couple of
months" to help it through a particularly busy renewal period. A few months later Martyn joined
Bilbroughs' staff, and in 1992 went out to Piraeus to become the third man in the Bilbroughs
office.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn6_5.jpg" ALT="M Hughes" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=110 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left>"I'd always wanted to work overseas," says Martyn (left). "My father had worked overseas, so it didn't seem an odd thing to do." Greece, he felt, had a lot to offer young, free, single people. But he came anyway, and within little more than six months his wife - also a qualified solicitor - had given birth to the first of their two daughters.
<P>
The thing that strikes you about Martyn's office is that it is a working office. It isn't untidy, but it is dominated by files. "We do pretty much the same sort of work as they do in London," explains Martyn. "But having an office in Piraeus enables us to be closer to an important part of our membership, and it is tangible evidence of the club's commitment to those members."
<P>
There are a few things that Martyn and his family miss, like hearing English spoken around them,
and the green of the English countryside. But they don't miss the weather, or the commuting. For
the future, Martyn would like to improve his "atrocious" command of the Greek language, and
he wants to get out and meet more of the club's members. "Piraeus is a proper shipping community," he says. "It is like a village. In the end, this business is about relationships. We have to develop and maintain them in order to go forward." 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Social news</H3>

Charlie Mold, who served the Club well as senior underwriting director, has retired. Fellow
directors gave Charlie a silver salver, his staff wrote him a poem:
<P>
<TABLE BORDER=6><CENTER>
<TD>Dear Charlie .....<BR>
The twilight of your career has finally arrived<BR>
Let us briefly look back at how it was contrived<BR>
A new fleet arrives - Declined or Approved?<BR>
You'd come back from lunch to find our office had moved<BR>
Binding renewals on many different premises<BR>
and passing opinion on Eddie Charman's lettuces<BR>
Many a lunchtime spent jogging round the Tower<BR>
You'd return to the office - but alas there was no shower<BR>
Faces have come and gone - including Owner or Broker<BR>
We hope your departure won't be too much of a choker<BR>
You'll spend sunny days practising your swing<BR>
And if you try hard - you'll forget everything<BR>
So farewell Charlie from us all at the Club<BR>
and by the way - its your round at the pub!<BR></TD>
</TABLE></CENTER>
<P>
<BR>
<LI>Paul Papalazarou, Mike Berry and Moira Maresky have all joined the company as claims
adjusters.
<P>
<LI>Margaret Gare has left her job as claims adjuster to enjoy early retirement with her husband Denis.
<P>
<LI>A daughter, Harriet, has been born to Simon and Emma Chapman.
<P>
<LI>Keely Goodge (Claims Support) married Paul Herring in July.
