<A NAME="Surprises"></A><BR>
<H3>Cutting out surprises</H3>

A good relationship with major European reinsurers is helping Bilbroughs to make sure club members
don't have any nasty surprises. But the London Club's managers haven't moved all of the club's
reinsurance away from London.  "The International Pool structure is there for major claims," says
Bryan Gaze, deputy chairman of Bilbroughs. "But we have to protect our members against the
consequences of a bad claims year. We have been able to find $23m of protection for the lower levels
for a premium of about $2.1m, which we think is sensible."
<P>
Bilbroughs has three layers of reinsurance for this year, much of it placed with Munich Re. "We
started two years ago insuring claims of $3m over a $2m excess for each claim," says Mr Gaze. 
"Munich Re provides seventy-five per cent of that cover. They are just putting a toe in the water of
reinsuring P&amp;I claims, and we are developing a good relationship." That relationship led to Bilbroughs
seeking cover for its own contribution to pool claims. Munich Re again led that, and the club now has
$25m cover with an excess of $5m for its own contributions to any pool claims. "Not all clubs do this,"
says Mr Gaze. "But we think it is prudent. We did try to reinsure our contribution to other clubs' pool
claims too, but Munich Re didn't like that idea. They are comfortable with us and our claims record,
but didn't want to go beyond that."
<P>
In a slightly controversial move, Bilbroughs led the London Club away from the International Group
joint proposal to cover the fifteen per cent vertical co-insurance of the pool which clubs took on this
year. "The idea was to distance the clubs from the London market and spread the risk," says Mr Gaze.
"But there were capacity problems which took them back to Lloyd's. So we thought it sensible to go
direct to Lloyd's to cover our exposure. There is no point in going elsewhere if the right cover is
cheaper in our traditional market."
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
</A><BR>
<br>
<TABLE BORDER=2>
<CENTER>
<CAPTION ALIGN=bottom><FONT  SIZE=-1><I>
<BR>LEADING Korean shipowner Hanjin Shipping has placed its newbuilding containership, the 65,643gt </I>Hanjin London<I>, with the London Club. Hanjin Shipping has been a member of the London Club since 1955, and currently has over 500,000 gt entered.</I></FONT></CAPTION>
<tr><td><CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn5_1.jpg" ALT="Hanjin London" WIDTH=267 HEIGHT=178 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1></TR></td></table></CENTER>
