<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Far East"><BR>
<H3>Club sharpens  Far East focus</H3>               

THE Asian Shipowners Forum is a growing force in world shipping. Something like forty per cent of
world shipping is now owned and operated from the Asia Pacific region, and trading patterns will
make that percentage grow. 
<P>
Asian owners increasingly look for local services and partners who can
understand their particular needs and ways of looking at problems. Over thirty per cent of the LondonClub's membership is already drawn from the Far East, and the managers have extensive experience
in the region. But that will not be enough to ensure the club retains its leading position. 
<P>
New London
Club chairman John M Lyras is leading a drive to sharpen the club's focus on  Asia and will be
travelling with Graham Edmiston, chairman of A Bilbrough, and Lance Johnson, the director
responsible for the Far East, to Hong Kong, Singapore and Kuala Lumpur during May. "We want to
get closer to the managements of the members who make up such a large part of our club, and to hear
their views," says Mr Johnson. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Talking Point</H3>

DURING his recent address to the Lloyd's of London Press 1st Asia-Pacific P&amp;I Conference in Hong
Kong, Lance Johnson provided examples of claims in a number of different categories which have
benefited from being handled on a representative basis by the club manager's Hong Kong office.
<P>
Speaking about problems involving stowaways and refugees, Mr Johnson told the conference that it
was important to maintain a good working relationship with immigration authorities. And he
recounted a story involving a vessel entered with the club which picked up some refugees while bound
from Bangkok to Hong Kong.
<P>
The refugees, who were packed tight in a badly leaking boat, were in a poor state of health. They
included a number of women and children. The master felt he had no alternative but to take them on
board.
<P>
When the vessel arrived in Hong Kong it was ordered to the Western Quarantine anchorage, where
the authorities boarded and began counting the refugees.  The first official number count produced a
staggering total of 1,002 people on board. But, following a second headcount the next day, the number
came out at 1,003. A third count was rendered unnecessary when it was discovered that a baby had
been born to one of the women during the night. We are reliably informed that Mr Johnson refrained from making any comment about the advantages of being in the club.
<P>
<I>Further details of  his LLP conference paper are available from Lance Johnson on +44 (0)171 772 8000, or using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co';return true">e-mail form</A>.</I>
<P>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Liaison"></A><BR>
<H3>On-the-spot liaison</H3>
<P>
Why would a P&amp;I club choose to have an office in one of the most expensive places in the world? 
<P>
At the end of 1976, A Bilbrough decided to open an office in Hong Kong, for the simple reason that about a third of the business entered with the London Club came from members based there. And, according to Lance Johnson (right),<IMG SRC="images/lcn5_2.jpg" ALT="L Johnson" WIDTH=125 HEIGHT=193 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right> director of A Bilbrough, making the most efficient use of time and maintaining a close liaison with members are two of the most compelling reasons for having set up and maintained the Hong Kong office.
<P>
Mr Johnson recently addressed the Lloyd's of London Press 1st Asia-Pacific P&amp;I Conference in Hong
Kong on the subject of "P&amp;I Claims Handling in Hong Kong". He  explained that working in a time
zone which is several hours ahead of London  has clear advantages. Mr Johnson pointed out that it is
possible for the Hong Kong office to have instructed correspondents, surveyors and/or lawyers and,
if necessary, to have provided security to prevent a vessel being arrested, all before London has started
work for the day.
<P>
Although it was originally intended that the Hong Kong office would handle only the claims of the
Hong Kong membership, the concept was so successful that it was extended to the majority of the Far
Eastern membership. And Mr Johnson used specific examples of claims to illustrate to the conference
the value to the club managers of having an office in a strategic geographical location. Whether
dealing with crew claims, stowaways and refugees, collisions, cargo claims, oil pollution, wreck
removal or any type of claim, there are clear advantages to on-the-spot 
representation.
<P>
It is not just claims which are dealt with by the Hong Kong office. Mr Johnson pointed out that the
club prefers to be proactive, and that having a permanent regional presence enables  the club to offer
on-the-spot advice on such matters as contracts of carriage, anticipated fixtures and the carriage of
intended cargoes. "Prevention is better than cure," said Mr Johnson.
<P>
The club managers have legally trained staff in the Hong Kong office who can handle various disputes
for which there is cover available under the FD&amp;D class. Having a presence in Hong Kong has
enabled the club managers on a number of occasions to handle disputes through to a successful
conclusion at arbitration, including the preparation of submissions, thereby saving on legal costs.
<P>
Mr Johnson told the conference that having a presence in Hong Kong enables the staff to gain what
he called "local knowledge". He said, "I recall, when I was based in Hong Kong, it was difficult for
those in London to comprehend why on earth we should need to close the Hong Kong office merely
because a typhoon was passing by."  Spoken like a native.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Circulars"></A>
<H3>Club Circulars published in booklet form</H3>

INFORMATION is one of the prime assets of any P&amp;I club. But that information is useless if it is not
shared amongst those who stand to benefit from it.
<P>
The London Club's policy of issuing circulars on matters of importance to members has for a number
of years been a fundamental part of its planned dissemination of information. Now the club has
brought together many of those circulars in one compact volume for the convenience of members.
<P>
The booklet contains reprints of various circulars that the club considers to be either relevant or
important. It does not contain reprints of all previous circulars, some of which may also still be
relevant, and so should be regarded not as a definitive work of reference but as a useful compendium
for easy reference.
<P>
Some circulars have been included for reference purposes, even though they are out of date. Care
should also be taken over references to specific rules which may subsequently have been amended.
<P>
The booklet contains a host of information on a wide variety of subjects. Here you will find everything
from last year's high-profile Limit on Club Cover circular, through the detached-back-of-the-settee
charm of 1964's Smuggling in India circular, to the thankfully largely unplumbed depths of the
seminal Berth Standard of Average Clause to be Renamed Charterers' Contribution Clause of 1971.
Bedside reading for the technician and historian alike. 
<P>
<I>If you would like a copy of the Circulars booklet, you should contact Lance Johnson on +44 (0)171 772 8000, or using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co';return true">e-mail form</A>.</I>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Brazil"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Brazil crew crackdown </H3>

BRAZIL is cracking down on certificates relating to crew competence and classification requirements
in respect of both national and foreign-flag vessels calling at the country's ports.
<P>
The Brazilian Directorate of Ports and Coasts has issued a decree stipulating that the qualification certificates of crew members on both coastwise and foreign-trading vessels must be checked for compliance with STCW requirements. 
<P>
Failure to produce the proper crew qualification certificates will result in a demand on the part of the 
authorities that the shipowner or operator replace the relevant crew members with properly qualified
personnel. Vessels which fail to comply with these rules will not be allowed to clear Brazilian ports.
<P>
Original certificates - or properly authenticated photocopies - relating to crew competence and
covering the classification details of vessels have to be presented to the Brazilian authorities under the
new regulations.
<P>
Pandibra, the club's correspondent in Santos, says members should ensure that their owned or
chartered vessels comply with the new regulations before fixing to Brazil. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Florida's COFR ruling</H3>
<P>
FLORIDA has changed its policy regarding Certificates of Financial Responsibility (COFRs) for
vessels carrying pollutants. Owners and operators of such vessels must now exhibit, on request when
in Florida waters, a current copy of a United States Coast Guard-issued COFR to officials of the
Department of Environmental Protection of the State of Florida. Possession of a COFR eliminates the
need to file a Vessel Financial Security Statement with the Florida authorities. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>First Person</H3>
<P>
STEVE Roberts was one of the first trainee claims handlers taken on by Bilbroughs straight from
school. He is also one of only two who has stayed the course. "I've been here thirteen years now," says
Steve. "I can't see me moving on. I don't think I would find the member-conscious 
philosophy we have here anywhere else." 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn5_4.gif" ALT="S Roberts" WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=108 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left>Steve (left) is ambitious, and wants to climb the management ladder in Bilbroughs. As an assistant director
with responsibility for claims handling for the Greek members, he works with a team of claims
handlers and adjusters. "I allocate work, encourage people when I can, follow up on problems and
from time to time visit the members so that they can keep personal contact," says Steve. "There is a
tremendous team feeling here, it's a youthful team and with a slimmer management structure we see
more decisions delegated to us."
<P>
One thing that Steve has delegated himself is the helm of the 505 dinghy he races with his wife, Sue.
"She is the skipper," smiles Steve, "I crew because I am unbearable as helmsman." He hasn't delegated
work on the Lotus Elan Sport he has been rebuilding for nearly eight years. That 
explains why it is taking so long, because Steve himself puts in more hours at Bilbroughs than is really
sensible. "The only thing that irritates me a bit here is having to do some of my own typing," says
Steve with a grin. "It's only because the secretaries don't stay to seven in the evening." According to 
Steve,  working late is a temporary phase, but one that never seems to end.
<P>
If that sounds a bit of a marathon, Steve is training for that too, running seriously with his two dogs,
one a neurotic pointer and the other a soppy bull terrier cross which Steve says is totally loyal. Some
might say the same about Steve and his attitude to Bilbroughs. He wouldn't dispute that. "This is a
respectful company which treats people well, you feel that you are taken seriously," he says.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Summer sports</H3>
<P>
Summer comes around, and the sporting season starts. First off the blocks was the six-a-side football
team. Hugh Brennan says three matches have already been played this year, against the UK Club,
Jackson Parton and Thomas Cooper. Hugh still hopes to get a team into the Lloyd Thompson
six-a-side tournament. Volunteers?
<P>
The first cricket match this year will be against Holmans on June 25, and Chris Nason is negotiating
more fixtures. Tina Warwick says she can make a rounders team available to play at any of the cricket
fixtures.
<P>
Marcus Bucknall is organising  sailing teams for the Brookes Bell Mari-Team Racing at Millwall docks.
<P>
Mental agility has had its day, with a company quiz night on April 17. The winning team was Claire Boggas, Ernie Chaplin, Keeley Goodge and Chris Nason. Lance Johnson's team would have done better if he had been allowed "P&amp;I Rules 1965-1967" as a specialist topic.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Social News</H3>

<IMG SRC="images/lcn5_5.jpg" ALT="K Atkinson" WIDTH=106 HEIGHT=101 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>Keith Atkinson (right) has decided to take early retirement following his 55th birthday and will be leaving 
at the end of May. He joined Bilbroughs in 1972 and has been a director since 1980.  
<P>
Louise Coles and Ian Gooch, now seconded to Greece as a claims handler, were married in April.
<P>
Denis Gare, claims adjuster, has retired after sixteen years with the company. 
<P>
Bilbroughs has hosted an introduction to P&amp;I seminar for students at Denmark's Marstal Nautical
Institute. 
<P>
