<A NAME="Rating"></A><BR>
<H3>Rating clubs - more than a numbers game</H3>

COMPETITION is forcing P&amp;I clubs to become less like clubs and more like commercial insurers. But the clubs are trying
to do that while retaining the essence of mutuality which gives them a market advantage. That essence - good service
born out of long relationships and the idea that shipowners should be buying insurance at cost through the club -
makes it difficult to analyse the financial performance of clubs in a realistic way. Yet every year US-based Standard
&amp; Poor tries to do just that. It takes the clubs' annual published accounts, sends out a short questionnaire, puts the
numbers into a magic box and produces its Marine Mutual Report.  The report rates all the clubs. But how much use
is it?
<P>
According to Bryan Gaze, vice-chairman of A Bilbrough &amp; Co, it is getting more useful as it develops. But as a rating
system it is still deeply flawed. "One big problem is the timing," says  Mr Gaze. "The report comes out in February,
which means that a lot of the information on which it is based is two years out of date by the time it can be used
by a shipowner thinking about renewals." As an example, Mr Gaze points to the way reserves are assessed, and the
weight given to them in the report. "Our reserves at the time of publishing our annual report in 1995 were $16.4m,"
he says. "After this February, they will be about $46m. Yet this report comes out now based on the $16m figure. It
is not very helpful to anyone."
<TABLE>
<TR><TD><IMG SRC="images/lcn4_2.gif" ALT="3D bar chart" WIDTH=251 HEIGHT=146 BORDER=1><BR><br><I><FONT  SIZE=-1><CENTER>Calls Equalisation Account <BR>balances at 20 February<BR>in US$ millions</CENTER></FONT></I><br><br></TD>
<TD>
Mr Gaze says the benefit of the S&amp;P report is that the publicity it generates is pushing clubs towards a greater degree
of financial openness. "We have led the drive towards clearer and more useful P&amp;I club accounts," says Mr Gaze. "S&amp;P
helps to push some of the others. But there are still many things, such as reinsurance programmes, the ability to
assess outstanding claims and the ability to collect debts, which S&amp;P cannot assess objectively. So in practice there
is no useful difference between the two- and three-flag ratings it awards."
</TD></TR>
</TABLE>
<P><CENTER><I>A <A HREF="../press/rating.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Related article by Bryan Gaze';return true"> related article</A> by Bryan Gaze, published in </I>Lloyds List,<I> is also available on this site.</I></CENTER>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Renewal"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Firm renewals in soft climate</H3>

THIS year's renewals had one disappointment for the London Club, but there was a lot of good news too. "We are
disappointed that World-Wide moved tonnage away," says Graham Edmiston, chairman of A Bilbrough. "But we have
gained some interesting fleets and overall we had a good renewal."
<P>
According to Mike Hill, senior underwriting director, the general climate was soft, but his team was firm on rates. "We
have kept our premium income up," says Mr Hill. "We didn't soften rates. It would not benefit the members in the
long term." Following the renewal, the London Club now has 25.4m gt of direct entered tonnage. With the reinsured
American Club tonnage and charterers' entries, the club has over 30m gt of entered 
tonnage. 
<P>
World-Wide's joint-venture company with Chinese interests still has its bulk carriers with the London Club. Almost
700,000 gt of new tonnage was entered, including 310,000 gt of bulk carriers in the Trade &amp; Transport fleet, 198,000
gt owned by the Turkish Marti group, 90,000 gt from Transmed and 75,000 gt from leading shipmanager V Ships. The
estimated total call will be $100m. An estimated 3.5 per cent saving on reinsurance costs was passed on to the
members.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Chairman"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Continuity and balance</H3>

THE London Club has a new and young chairman. Should the members and managers be bracing themselves
for the new broom? John M Lyras smiles. "My priorities as chairman will be to develop both the strength of the club,
in tonnage and economic terms, and the strength of the managers and board, to give us continuity," he says.  "The
financial strength is there, now I want us to develop the geographical balance and emphasise that we are a club in
which a well-managed fleet would feel at home."
<P>
Mr Lyras comes from a traditional shipping family, and his father was a director of the London Club for eighteen
years. Mr Lyras has been on the board for fifteen years and is the first Greek chairman of the London Club. "I am
proud of that," says Mr Lyras, "and proud to acknowledge the practical hands-on interest that our Greek members
take in the club. The directors and the managers appreciate that. I see it as one of my tasks to get owners from
other regions to take such an active role."
<P>
Later this year Mr Lyras and Graham Edmiston, chairman of the club managers, A Bilbrough &amp; Co, will be making a
major trip to the Far East in a bid to emphasise and develop the club's important ties with that region. "We will be
looking for members who want to join us not just for our reputation for good service, but because they will fit in with
the well-run tonnage we have," says Mr Lyras. "We would like more medium-size fleets with dynamic owners."
<P>
Mr Lyras wants that balance in the managers and on the club board too. "I want to build up a continuity of structure
through the management to the top, and through the board," says Mr Lyras. "That means not being afraid to employ
the people we need, from different cultures, people who can bring something to the club and strengthen it."  
<P>
Last year, as vice-chairman of the club and using his influence on the numerous bodies where he holds office, Mr
Lyras was a leader in the campaign to reduce limits on catastrophe calls. The London Club was portrayed as being
less than enthusiastic about the unity of the International Group. Mr Lyras sees it differently. "I strongly believe in
the importance of the International Group, " he says. "It is getting more important, not weaker. But perhaps its
structure is not keeping up with the times. Shipowners, club members, want more say in how their clubs are run.
Managers have to take into account owners' priorities, as well as their own. Owners respect the club managers, but
want that respect to be mutual. As chairman of the London Club, I will be pushing for the International Group to
develop the same relationship between managers and members as has developed in our club." 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Talking point</H3>

GRAHAM Edmiston, chairman of A Bilbrough &amp; Co, gave a paper to the recent P&amp;I - Is There A Future For Mutuality?
conference in London. The title of Mr Edmiston's paper was "Has The Catastrophe Debate Changed The Relationship
Between Managers And Members?" 
<P>
Having reviewed the historical background to the manager/member relationship, and provided a concise summary of
the catastrophe limitation debate, Mr Edmiston concluded that the relationship had changed. He pointed out that
the public nature of the limitation debate had accelerated a process of change which had already been under way.<P>
"Competition and globalisation were already forcing club managers to pay close attention to the needs of their
members," concluded Mr Edmiston. "But this debate has shown both managers and members that club boards don't
always represent the full scope of the membership. It has shown club boards that they should not take for granted
what managers tell them. The result is that clubs will have to tell their members more, and members will demand
more of their clubs. This is surely a healthy change for P&amp;I as a whole."
<P>
The two-day conference was attended by a hundred delegates from a number of different countries. It included
speakers from mutual clubs, club managers, shipowners, P&amp;I brokers, law firms and accountants.
<P>
<CENTER><I>A copy of Graham Edmiston's <A HREF="../press/ibc.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Related article by Graham Edmiston';return true"> related article</A>, published in </I>P&amp;I International<I> is available on this site.</I></CENTER>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Malaysia"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Malaysia coastal controls</H3>

MALAYSIA is taking a tough stance on illegal discharge and sludge dumping. It is pushing for standard operations and
communications procedures to be introduced throughout the ASEAN region.
<P>
Malaysia is particularly concerned in this respect about tankers which have undertaken what are deemed to be illegal
ship-to-ship transfers in Malaysian territorial waters. 
<P>
On several occasions, the Malaysian authorities have detained ships following such alleged offences. Spica Services (S)
Pte Ltd, the club's correspondent in Singapore, says owners should be aware that ship-to-ship operations have in
the main been moved away from areas which might be considered to overlap Indonesian and Singaporean waters,
particularly the southern end of the Malacca Straits. Spica emphasises that advice is available locally on currently
preferred areas.
<P>
The Malaysian authorities also contend that sludge dumping is invariably connected to ship-to-ship
transfers. Spica says that monitoring of the area, including naval and air force surveillance, has been stepped up, and
advises ships which are going to deballast prior to cleaning or docking to do so before entering Malaysian waters.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Santos"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Warning on Santos piracy</H3>

INADEQUATE security in major Brazilian ports has prompted the London Club's correspondent in Santos, Pandibra, to
issue a list of recommended procedures to follow in the event of pirates boarding vessels at Santos Roads. The pirates
are normally armed but not violent, so crew members are advised not to resist if they are held hostage. 
<P>
Any incident
should be reported as soon as possible to the police, port captain and customs. New seals should be placed on any
open containers. It is vital that the authorities are advised of incidents without delay.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Loss Prevention - Ivory Coast...</H3>

CUSTOMS in Adibjan have resumed the imposition of heavy fines on vessels for infringements of regulations, and
particularly for non-declaration of bunkers.
<P>
The London Club's correspondent in Abidjan, Eltvedt &amp; O'Sullivan, cites a recent example involving a vessel on a
regular liner run to Abidjan which failed to declare bunkers on board and was fined Ffr6.69m. Following some lengthy
negotiations, the fine was reduced to Ffr230,000 ($46,000).
<P>
Eltvedt &amp; O'Sullivan says it can find no reference in the Abidjan customs code to any requirement to declare bunkers
on board. Management at the maritime branch of the customs authorities, however, insists that a decree to this effect
has been published. 
<P>
Eltvedt &amp; O'Sullivan advises that, pending further investigation, it would be prudent for all masters visiting the IvoryCoast to declare bunkers on board when entering Abidjan.
<P>
<BR>
<H3>...and Turkey</H3>
OMUR Marine Ltd, in Istanbul, Turkey, has reminded members about restrictions currently in force against vessels
operating from ports in southern Cyprus. The Turkish maritime authorities have forbidden any vessel, of any flag,
entry to Turkish ports if it has come directly from a port in southern Cyprus. Vessels not registered in southern
Cyprus will be allowed to call at Turkish ports if they have called previously at a foreign port. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>First Person</H3>

THE first person into the Bilbrough office in Leman Street in the morning is Jim McGrane (below). As Office Services Supervisor
he is there every day before six o'clock, making sure the building's systems are up and running properly. Jim is also
the first person to write the history of the Bilbrough family. After twenty-two years in the Army and ten years
making Bilbrough's offices run smoothly, Jim seems an unlikely historian. "When we were moving offices I started to
read the archived letters of the family," says Jim. "That was back in 1987, and I got more and more fascinated with
the history of the family. You could see everything through the documents of the time." Jim went through seven
thousand letters in fourteen volumes. It took him seven years.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn4_4.gif" ALT="J J McGrane" WIDTH=132 HEIGHT=127 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>
He wrote the family history, which was then published by Bilbroughs to coincide with the centenary of Tower Bridge,
in 1994. Now Jim is busy on another Bilbrough family project, writing a book on the war diaries of the family. "I'm
hoping to have it published independently," says Jim. Any money coming from that will take Jim and his wife of
thirty-one years standing to Singapore on holiday. Jim remembers Singapore from his army days, when he travelled
extensively all over the world. But today he says he enjoys coming to work, and doesn't miss the Army at all.
<P>
"The only thing I miss nowadays," smiles Jim, "is when I go shopping at Lakeside and I'm not getting paged all day
on the tannoy." Jim has a reputation as a joker, and as Mr Fixit, so he is continually paged at Bilbrough. When he is
not making the building run smoothly, or making jokes, he is making a museum of old publications and artefacts
which will sit in a new cabinet in reception. "This isn't just a building to me," says Jim. "It runs like a ship, and I
take a real interest in P&amp;I. I like to be able to talk to the adjusters and really know what is going on."
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<h3>Social News</h3>

MR John M Lyras, of Lyras Maritime Ltd, has been elected chairman of the committee of The London Club. He succeeds
Mr  Russell A Peters, who had been chairman since 1992 and who remains a member of the committee and is also
president of London Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association (Bermuda) Limited.
<P>
<BR>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn4_5.jpg" ALT="R Peters" WIDTH=187 HEIGHT=133 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1>
<BR>
<I>Russell Peters, chairman of the London Club for  four years, was presented with a silver salver by Graham Edmiston following his decision to step down in 
January.</I></CENTER>
<P>
Mr Peter J Goulandris of Orion &amp; Global Chartering Inc, New York, and Mr Robert Ho of Fairmont Shipping (HK) Limited,
Hong Kong, have been elected vice-chairmen of the committee.
<P>
Mr Amnon Lion of Zodiac Maritime Agencies Ltd, London,  and Mr Bendix Todsen of H Schuldt, Hamburg, have been
elected chairman and vice-chairman respectively of the Finance and Audit Committee.
<P>
<H4>New appointments - A Bilbrough &amp; Co.</H4> 
Peter Staples has joined the company as Deputy Manager - Claims Services, and Garry Stevens has
been recruited as a Claims Adjuster. Katy De Viell has joined as a Junior Accounts Clerk, while Elaine Jeffery has
started work as an audio typist.
<P>
