<BR>
<A NAME="Limit"></A><BR>
<H3>Still debating the limitation issue</H3>

1995 probably saw more column inches in the shipping press devoted to the London Club than in any other year in
the club's 130-year history, much of it as a result of the club's rejection of the twenty per cent limitation proposal,
which was put to club boards or committees in April 1995.
<P>
The club committee was unanimous  in rejecting this proposal - which produced a  theoretical limit on club cover
of about $20bn - and in  stipulating that the limit should be set at a realistically collectable level.
<TABLE>
<TR><TD><CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn3_1.gif" ALT="M G Edmiston" WIDTH=105 HEIGHT=154 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1><br><br><FONT  SIZE=-1><I>A Bilbrough &amp; Co chairman<br> Graham Edmiston - the managers of the London Club are in no doubt that their first duty lies towards their members</I></FONT><br><br></CENTER></TD>
<TD>
The London Club's position gathered support among shipowners and shipowners' associations as the voice of
commercial reality and common sense. A number of shipowners' associations, from the Union of Greek Shipowners to
the Asian Shipowners' Forum, have now come out in favour of a lower limit. A number of P&amp;I clubs followed the London
Club's lead in criticising the compromise proposal  but, apart from the Swedish Club, which finally rejected the 
proposal in October but agreed to implement it in November, the three other clubs  in favour of a limit reluctantly
went along with the compromise proposal. However, an overwhelming majority of members of the UK Club have now
voted in favour of a realistically collectable limit, and the managers expect pressure from owners in various clubs and
owners'  associations to lead to a reduction in the limit on cover within the next two years. 
</TD></TR></TABLE>
The London Club and its
managers have been criticised in some quarters for bringing division and acrimony into the club community, but are
in no doubt whatsoever that their first duty lies towards their own members and that their first priority is their own
members' best interests.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Promoting loss prevention</H3>
READERS of this newsletter should by now have seen the first issue of a new quarterly publication from the London
Club - the StopLoss Bulletin.
<P>
The club is very aware of the vital role to be played by the promotion of loss prevention  awareness. It prides itself
on its quick response to claims made against its members, but it doesn't allow its determination to handle those
claims quickly and efficiently to prevent it from looking behind the incidents which give rise to the claims in the first
place.
<P>
The club has a Claims Review Body which each month reviews all live claims where the total estimated cost of
settlement has altered by more than $100,000 during the period under review. The purpose of this is twofold. First,
to monitior the development of the club's claims experience throughout the course of any given policy year. And,
second, to observe claims on an individual case basis to make sure that everything that should have been done has
been done and to confirm that individual claims handlers have a proper grasp of what is required of them.
<P>
The London Club is committed to improving loss prevention awareness throughout the industry. And it sees its
StopLoss Bulletin as an important part of the education process.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Australia"></A><BR>
<H3>Loss prevention in Australia</H3>

AUSTRALIA rightly enjoys a sound reputation for the efficiency of its port state control procedures. And the club's
legal correspondent in Sydney, Ebsworth &amp; Ebsworth, tells us it has recently received the PSC figures for 1994 from
the Australian Maritime Safety Authority (AMSA). This shows a total of 2,406 inspections and an increasing number of
detentions - 153 as against 72 the previous year.
<P>
Ships from a total of 72 countries were inspected during the year. The total number of individual ship visits to all
Australian ports in that time was 11,800, of which it is estimated that 4,198 were foreign ships not inspected during
the previous six months.
<P>
AMSA placed particular emphasis on the inspection of dry bulk carriers, which in 1994 accounted for over seventy per
cent of vessels detained. Meanwhile, deficiencies in lifesaving appliances and firefighting equipment accounted for more
than fifty per cent of all deficiencies recorded. It can therefore be expected that AMSA will pay particular attention
to these items in future years.
<P>
Ebsworth &amp; Ebsworth tells us that, in view of the increasing attention being paid by the Australian government to
marine safety, and the findings contained in its 1994 report, AMSA can be expected to have achieved, if not increased,
its inspection rate during 1995.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Size/claims"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Size up, claims down</H3>

"WHEN talking to prospective members about The London Club, they show most interest in our falling claims costs,"
says Mike Hill (right), underwriting director of A Bilbrough &amp; Co, managers of the London Club. "We are proud of our record,
which has seen claims cost per ton fall by thirty per cent since 1990. But it is no accident. We have a focused
underwriting policy, and that is what has produced these benefits for our members."
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn3_2.gif" ALT="M D M Hill" WIDTH=127 HEIGHT=131 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>
The most noticeable part of the London Club's underwriting policy is a shift towards larger bulk vessels. "We don't
exclude smaller vessels," says Mr Hill. "We welcome all good owners. But we do see that larger vessels, with their
reduced number of port calls, tend to have a lower incidence of claims. We have focused on these ships, and seen
our average size of vessel rise by fifty per cent from 18,000 gt in 1990 to 28,000 gt today."
<P>
Following this policy has led to the London Club taking top spot in the league of vessel sizes. But size isn't everything.
"We have concentrated our resources in the areas we understand," says Mr Hill, who emphasises that it is also a
question of management resources. "We want to understand the risks we are going into," he says.
<P>
"There is no doubt in my mind that new vessels operate with less problems than old ones," says Mr Hill. "The age of
our fleet is now below the world average, and we would like to keep it that way. In general it benefits all the
members to be part of a young fleet. "Last year, Mr Hill and his team turned away 240 potential members, with over
600 ships. "Most of them did not fit our criteria for size, age or type of operation," says Mr Hill. "But some simply
don't reach our 
quality threshold. We look for members with quality operating standards and strong financial backing."
<P>
Mr Hill says the club wants to expand, but not at any price. "We have grown 45 per cent in tonnage terms since 1990,
and we want to continue with that steady growth," he points out. 
<P>
He adds, "There is strong competition now, especially with so many split fleets. But we don't compete at any cost.
Maintaining the level of advance calls so that there are no nasty surprises later is most important." 
<P>
The whole underwriting policy is founded on the idea of selectivity. "Shipowners recognise that there is sub-standard
shipping about. Good shipowners recognise that we exclude bad ones, which helps us to attract the right people," says
Mr Hill. "And when the right people come, they find a concentrated underwriting team here in London. We have
developed a good team, and we like to keep it working together in London during renewal time for the benefit of the entire membership. The renewal period is critical to the club, and it is essential that we focus on getting it right." 
<P>
<I>If you have questions about underwriting  matters, you can ring Mike Hill on +44 (0)171 772 8081, or send an email for his attention using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co'; return true">form</A>, and he and his staff will be happy to answer them.</I>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="NZ"></A>
<BR>
<H3>New Zealand law reform</H3>

NEW Zealand has recently undergone the biggest revision of its maritime law in living memory. This culminated in the
coming into force last year of  the Transport Law Reform Bill. 
<P>
Not all provisions of the new legislation will have immediate effect because New Zealand has still to ratify, for example,
the International Convention on Salvage 1989. But there are some significant changes, and P&amp;I Services of Wellington
has summarised the main aspects of the new legislation which will be of interest to the club and its members.
<P>
New Zealand adopted the Hague Visby Rules with respect to outward shipments on bills of lading issued after February
1995. It has made no mention in the new legislation of the Hamburg Rules. The Sea Carriage of Goods Act 1940 has
been repealed and, with it, the provision whereby a ship's agent could be sued in respect of cargo claims. The 1976
Limitation Convention anomaly on the definition of an owner - which did not include charterers - has been tidied
up.
<P>
Provision has been made for the 1989 Salvage Convention to become part of New Zealand law at a later date.
<P>
Title to sue issues have been addressed through amendment of the Mercantile Law Act 1908, bringing into New Zealand
law provisions similar to those contained in the UK Carriage of Goods by Sea Act 1992.
<P>
The Convention-based approach to pollution issues has been carried through in the new legislation. The current
overlap between the Marine Pollution Act 1974 and the Resource Management Act 1991 will be removed through the
eventual repeal of the Marine Pollution Act. Provision has been made for New Zealand to adopt MARPOL. And a system
of planning and response for oil spills has been established.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Nigeria"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Nigeria immigration reminder</H3>

FAILURE to comply with the stringent immigration regulations in force in Nigeria could result in serious repercussions
for ships operating to that country. Pandiship, a correspondent in West Africa, has circulated the club with details
of a recent communication issued by the Nigerian Immigration Service (NIS), which all club members are asked to note
well.
<P>
The NIS circular points out, among other things, that all passengers on vessels entering Nigeria must have entry visas
or be covered by visa abolition agreements. Trainees, supercargoes and wives and children of crew are considered to
be passengers for this purpose.
<P>
All crew must  have seamen's books or valid Nigerian visas in their passports, and all non-Nigerian citizens who are
required to sign on as members of a crew in Nigeria must do so with the immigration authorities.
<P>
Non-Nigerian crew must not be discharged in Nigeria without the approval of the immigration authorities, and all such
crew will be given transit permits on leaving the vessel.
<P>
Stowaways apprehended in Nigeria will be treated as prohibited immigrants and will not be allowed into the country.
Repatriation costs will be borne by shipowners or agents, and owners or their representatives will be penalised.
Penalties are likely to be particularly severe in the case of prohibited immigrants of Nigerian nationality.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>First Person</H3>

JOHN Williams (below, pictured <I>without</I> pipe), head of Bilbroughs office in Hong Kong, was called to the bar in 1975. There is no record of whether
or not he walked there, but there is a fair chance he did.
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn3_4.jpg" ALT="J Williams" WIDTH=131 HEIGHT=140 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left>
John, who lists hill walking as one of his main recreations, joined Bilbroughs in October 1977. He moved to the Hong
Kong office in June 1980, initially for a one-year stint, and has been there ever since.
<P>
John has had a close involvement with the Korean market for a number of years, and in 1988 he brought his work
home when he married his delightful Korean wife. A daughter, Constance Emily Rebecca, was born in December 1992.
<P>
The Hong Kong office was set up almost twenty years ago, and is staffed by expartriate and Chinese-speaking people.
It is a vital part of the London Club operation, with between thirty and thirty-five per cent of the club's business
emanating from the Asia region.
<P>
John enjoys life in Hong Kong, and he enjoys also looking after the Far East membership. If he could walk to work
he surely would. As it is, he is a familiar figure on the No 28 light bus, going to and from the office each day. He isn't
mean. He just doesn't like wasting money on taxis.
<P>
John is also a familiar figure sitting outside his office door, reading through his files and smoking his pipe, or a good
cigar . He doesn't suffer from claustrophobia. It's just that it has been known for the fumes from his pipe to reach
the rest of the staff, courtesy of the office air conditioning system. John is also an inveterate eater of curries, the
hotter the better. Clearly a man who warrants his own office. John is obviously considerate, if not flamboyant. His
main vice is said to be a compulsion to buy made-to-measure suits. He is believed to have over thirty, almost all
of them grey - a rather  inappropriate colour for one of the best-known club people in the Far East.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<CENTER>
<CENTER><IMG SRC="images/lcn3_5.jpg" ALT="FAC meeting" WIDTH=334 HEIGHT=210 BORDER=1><I></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
A lot of the hard work that goes towards making the club what it is  today is undertaken by committees whose work
is largely unseen, although very effective. Here, then,  a rare photo of a committee meeting, this one of the finance
and audit committee which sat in Athens last October.</I></CENTER>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<h3>Social News</h3>

THERE have been some new appointments to the committee of the club. The following have been elected as committee members, with effect from January 24, 1996: Capt Du Bao Ming, of Cosco (Hong Kong); A N Hamid, of Malaysia International Shipping Corporation Bhd, London.
<P>
KEITH Atkinson was recently presented with a silver salver by Mr Garbutt of S W Garbutt &amp; Son, the club's
correspondents in Messina, Sicily, in recognition of a sixty-year association between the two organisations.
<P>WELCOME back. Ergin Ahmet has rejoined the company as a senior systems analyst within the computer department.
Ergin worked in the computer department from July 1984 until December 1989. 
<P>
OTHER appointments include Tom Saul (assistant director, finance), Anna Kalathakis (claims adjuster). And Vivienne
Finch is now employed by the company as a full-time receptionist and switchboard operator.
<P>
