<A NAME="Strength"></A><BR>
<H3>Financial strength vital to future of mutuality</H3>

Shipowners do not want to be hit by unexpected supplementary calls," says Russell Peters (pictured below), chairman of the London
Club. "That means clubs must build up not only sufficient assets to cover known and expected liabilities, but must
also retain a flexible surplus to allow them to cope with unexpected claims without having to make large
supplementary calls which owners have not budgeted for."
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn2_1.gif" ALT="R Peters" WIDTH=93 HEIGHT=133 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left>
Mr Peters commented on the need for a conservative approach to calls shortly after the London Club board considered
proposals for a general rate increase for the 1996/97 year. The 1995/96 year is showing an impressive investment
performance for the club, and so far the claims experience of the London Club has not reflected the rising trend seen
by other majors. Mr Peters says the committee questioned managers closely over the justification for a rate increase
against this background.
<P>
"We understand that there is a general trend of raising claims for all the clubs," says Mr Peters. "And we know well
that the doctrine of pure mutuality, where you collect only what you need when you need it, can lead to an
uncomfortable position." The committee is considering a modest increase in the standard advance call, with any
surplus that might arise going towards the Call Equalisation Account. This fund stands at $14m, providing a buffer
against unexpected  supplementary calls.
<P>
Mr Peters  has been at the forefront of rebuilding the club's financial strength following the need for large calls in
1990. "Mutuality will always be better than commercial insurance," says Mr Peters. "But owners don't like surprises.
They prefer strong clubs. It is no coincidence that as our assets and reserves have grown, so has our entered
tonnage."
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>   
<A NAME="Debate"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Clubs call for more debate</H3>

FOUR influential clubs in the International Group have backed calls by the London Club for more debate on the issue
of catastrophe liability. And one club, the West of England, has called for a radical rethink of the way the
International Group makes decisions. Graham Edmiston, chairman of A Bilbrough, says the whole question of liability
limits must be taken out of the spotlight and debated more thoroughly between the clubs, their managers and their
members. "It was a mistake to try and push this compromise through too quickly," says Mr Edmiston.
<P>
Mr Edmiston says  shipowners may  now press for a greater involvement in the formulation of P&amp;I policy on key issues,
to avoid the controversy which has arisen over the question of limitation. "A working group of a few managers
effectively presented the members of all clubs with a fait accompli," says Mr Edmiston. "But shipowners want and
deserve the opportunity to debate matters which affect them in such a vital way."
<P>
Initial attempts by clubs opposed to limits on liability to impose a moratorium on discussion  were first rejected by
the London Club. Since then, the Swedish Club has followed this lead and the North of England and UK Clubs have
declined to support a moratorium.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Bermuda"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Restructuring combines flexibility and tradition</H3>

THE London Club is to restructure its Bermuda operations in order to gain flexibility. From February 20, 1996, ninety
per cent of P&amp;I and FD&amp;D risks will be reinsured with a Bermuda-based parallel company, The London Steam-Ship
Owner's Mutual Insurance Association (Bermuda) Ltd.  
<P>
This will replace the present arrangement under which the same percentage of the risks is reinsured with a
Bermuda-based subsidiary, the London &amp; Bermuda Reinsurance Co Ltd. 
<P>
A structured reinsurance programme, designed to protect the interests of members, is of increasing importance to
marine mutuals such as the London Club 
<P>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn2_2.gif" ALT="B C Gaze" WIDTH=125 HEIGHT=129 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>
Bryan Gaze (right), deputy chairman and financial director of A Bilbrough, says the new structure will give the club the
flexibility it needs to cope with modern conditions,  while maintaining the traditional base in  London. 
<P>
Russell Peters, current chairman of the London Club, will assume the chairmanship of LSSO(B), which will have a
separate board to the London Club committee. But all members entering or renewing entries of ships in Class 5 (P&amp;I)
or Class 8 (FD&amp;D) for the 1996/7 policy year will automatically become members of LSSO(B) as well as the London Club.
Parallel membership will be made a condition of entry.
<P>
"We have had a parallel company in Bermuda since 1978, but it has never traded," says Mr Gaze. "Now we have looked
at the geographical composition of our membership, the new regulatory regime for insurance  in Europe and the
demands of long-term strategic tax planning, and it makes sense to move to a parallel rather than a subsidiary
structure."
<P>
The London Club will continue to be regulated by the UK Department of Trade and Industry, and the results of the
Bermuda company will be aggregated with the London operations in published financial statements. 
<P>
<I>For information on the financial affairs and structure of  the London Club please ring Bryan Gaze, deputy chairman,
on +44 171 772 8000, or send an e-mail for his attention using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='E-mail form pre-addressed to A Bilbrough &amp; Co'; return true">form</A></I>.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Loss Prevention</H3>

BUNKER fuel short delivery disputes are very common and can be very contentious. Chief engineers and bunker barge
operators in some parts of the world are notorious for having a few extra tons up their sleeve. Salters Marine
Consultants of Athens says this sort of malpractice may be on the wane, because surveyors are becoming more vigilant
and simply because of the number of times bunker surveys are carried out when vessels go on and off hire. But it
adds that some highly innovative 'sleeves' have been created in which to secrete the few extra tons. 
<P>
Salters warns that the chief engineer and surveyor should check the bunker receipt before bunkering takes place.
The tanks of the receiving vessel and the bunker barge should then be carefully measured to ascertain the exact
quantities on both vessels. Once the measuring has taken place, the quantity on board the barge should be calculated
using officially approved calibration tables. Salters says it has encountered poor quality, non-approved tables, and
even cases where no tables have been made available and where the attending surveyor has been asked to accept the
customs loading chit as proof of quantity on board. Salters warns that, if no tables are provided, the fuel on the barge
should be rejected, even if there is a delivery meter onboard. The veracity of fuel meters should be regarded as
suspect, even when meter correction factors and calibration certificates are present.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="Chinese">
<BR>
<H3>Chinese time limitation</A></H3>

EXTENSIONS of time limits for bringing proceedings in maritime law cases in China may no longer be valid following
a recent ruling of the Supreme People's Court of China. Following a meeting of judges from all Chinese maritime
courts, the Supreme Court issued a protocol stating that stipulations in respect of limitation of time in the maritime
code of the People's Republic of China must be strictly adhered to. This means that any agreement reached between
parties to extend time limits for starting legal proceedings will be invalid.
<P>
Huatai Insurance Agency &amp; Consultant Service Ltd of Shanghai warns that any dispute falling within Chinese
jurisdiction which can't be settled amicably within the agreed time limit  should now automatically be brought to
the courts by one of the parties. Failing this, the dispute will not be heard by the courts, which will deem invalid
any agreement on time extensions which might exist between the parties.
<P>
The Maritime Code of the PRC stipulates a one-year time limit for bringing claims against the carrier in a carriage
of goods by sea dispute, and two years under a voyage charter party agreement. There is a three-year limit in respect
of pollution claims. A one-year time limit applies to General Average contributions. It is therefore important to be
alert to the need to start proceedings within one year of the issuance of the adjustment in circumstances where cargo
interests fail to pay General Average contributions.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<A NAME="US damages"></A>
<BR>
<H3>Punitive damages ruling in US</H3>

THE US Court of Appeals for the Fifth Circuit has ruled that punitive damages can no longer be awarded in
maintenance and cure cases. The ruling was handed down in the case of Guevera v Maritime Overseas Corp. 
<P>
The trial court had found that maintenance payments had been willfully and callously withheld from an injured
seaman, who was awarded punitive damages. Subsequently, the question before the Supreme Court was whether the
Miles concept, set forth in the 1990 Supreme Court decision in Miles v Apex Marine Corp, precluded recovery of
punitive damages in maintenance and cure cases. It was held that it did.
<P>
The Fifth Circuit has now adopted the view that punitive damages cannot be awarded in an action based on the
wrongful withholding of maintenance payments, although a seaman can still recover attorneys' fees incurred to obtain
maintenance and cure wrongfully denied.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Deep draft problems in deep south</H3>

THE US Coast Guard has reminded shipowners and operators of  their  responsibilities under US law following recent
incidents of steering and main propulsion failures on deep-draft vessels calling at ports in southern Texas. The
coastguard has drawn owners' attention to the fact that no vessel can enter or get under way in US waters unless
it has undergone a testing of steering gear and propulsion machinery in the previous twelve hours. The rules also
require that, whenever there is a hazardous condition on board a vessel, the port captain at the place of destination
and the place where the vessel is located have to be informed. Failure to comply with these requirements could result
in a civil penalty of  up to $25,000.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>First Person</H3>

K S SOHN might not be the first person you meet when you visit the Seoul offices of P&amp;I Services of Korea (Pandiko). But you have at least a fifty per cent chance. The other first person you might meet is Sin-Young Kim, who has been assisting KS since August 1993 in the offices of Pandiko, the exclusive correspondent in Seoul for the London Club - and with whom he is pictured, right.
<IMG SRC="images/lcn2_4.gif" ALT="KS Sohn &amp; Sin-Young Kim" WIDTH=123 HEIGHT=122 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>
<P>
Pandiko was formed in 1981. KS, the representative director, has been there from the start. He graduated from Korea Maritime University at the end of 1973 and served as chief officer on a variety of vessels for Korea Shipping Corporation and Sanko Line. He came ashore in 1977 and worked as claims manager for KMTC, a long-time member of the London Club, before joining Pandiko. Making the most of his accumulated experience and knowledge, he was appointed an arbitrator by the Korean Commercial Arbitration Board in 1993.
<P>
Pandiko's role is to act as correspondent for all London Club members and to provide first-hand assistance to the membership. KS enjoys his work. The part he enjoys most is "evaluating shipowners' liabilities". This, and reporting generally to the club, keeps him very busy. He likes all sports and he enjoys playing golf. So pack your clubs the next time you're going to Seoul.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Social News</H3>

BILBROUGH'S tennis team rolled into action in August, taking on London law firm Holmes Hardingham. The match was
staged at the P&amp;O sports ground in leafy Worcester Park, Surrey, where the most difficult thing to negotiate was the
entrance to the ground, which was designed to be transited by nothing larger or less flexible than a small, coiled
spring. The team did us proud, pulling off a victory in a closely fought match. A thoroughly enjoyable afternoon's
tennis was followed by a barbecue supper, which not even all the wasps in Surrey could spoil.
<P>
The staff party at the Dicken's Inn, on Friday, September 29, had a pub theme. The yard of ale demonstration took
a minute and a half. Marcus Bucknall downed it in one minute. He is from Yorkshire. Gary Durham won the arm
wrestling, having developed his skills in the computer department.
<P>
Forty-eight pensioners and hosts had lunch in the new offices on Tuesday October 10. They all regretted retiring too
early.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn2_5.gif" ALT="Lynda Sharp" WIDTH=121 HEIGHT=115 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=left>
Lynda Sharp (left) has been appointed secretary to Lance Johnson, and Angela Eades has joined as secretary to
Graham Edmiston. Monica Cooper and Dawn Jordan have joined the company as audio typists, while another newcomer
is Jamie Lawson, who has started as a Post Room junior.
<P>
Sally Ager left the Claims Support department at the end of September to study History and Russian full-time at
university. Keely Goodge has moved from reception to take over from Sally.
<P>
Stephen Michaels has been promoted from Filing Clerk to Trainee Claims Technician within the Claims Support
Department, while Donna Sievey has been promoted from Post Room Junior to Filing Clerk, also in the Claims Support
Department.
<P>
Finally, our congratulations to Claims Adjuster Simon Chapman, who married Emma on August 12.
<P>
