<A NAME="Owners"></A><H3>Owners back call for limitation re-think</H3>

SHIPOWNERS across the globe are asking their P&amp;I Club managers to re-think the proposed International Group compromise on limitation of liability. And differences over the way in which clubs have approached the problem may lead to a fundamental shift in the relationship between shipowners, club boards and club managers.
<P>
John M Lyras, a member of the board of the Baltic Exchange and a leading shipowners' representative, says, "Shipowners will begin to question the way their clubs act. The strong protests from the Union of Greek Shipowners and the Greek Shipping Co-operation Committee show that too many owners were not consulted before this compromise was presented as a <I>fait accompli.</I>"
<P>
Apart from the powerful Greek owners' bodies in London and Piraeus, Swedish, Asian and European owners have voiced their concern. Robert Ho, managing director of Hong Kong-based Fairmont Shipping, has asked the Hong Kong Shipowners Association to protest at the speed with which the International Group clubs wish to implement the proposal. Ho wants more time for the Asian Shipowners Forum to consider the matter. And Geneva-based Mediterranean Shipping Company has told its brokers it may seek alternatives to traditional P&amp;I Clubs unless it receives assurances that it will be protected from liabilities which could exceed $60m under the proposed regime.
<P>
Shipowners have taken unlimited cover under the P&amp;I system for granted. But Russell Peters, managing director of E&amp;F Lines, says not all owners realise the dangers in the mutual system today. "One owner's unlimited cover is another owner's unlimited liability," says Peters. Owners are still exposed to unlimited potential catastrophe claims, and John M Lyras says, "When shipowners are given sufficient time and information to consider this matter properly, they will show that they prefer a collectable limit on liability, one that will not break the back of world shipping." 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Annual"></A><H3>Annual Report Highlights Strong Growth</H3>

THE London P&amp;I Club grew strongly in 1994/5. Assets were up five per cent to $355 million, and direct entered tonnage grew by ten per cent to 26.5 million gross tons. Russell Peters, chairman of the committee of the London Club, says, "It is most encouraging to note the significant increase in the Club's directly entered tonnage in the early months of 1995."
<P>
The annual report of the London Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association, published today, shows how the growth has come despite a strict underwriting policy which meant that two hundred and forty potential members, with more than 650 vessels, were declined. During the year fleet replacement by members meant the average age of vessels entered in the club fell to sixteen years, two years below the world average age.
<P>
Financially, the Club had total assets at February 20th of $355 million, up five percent on the previous year, despite a poor investment climate. The supplementary call for the 1994/5 policy year was reduced to 30 per cent from 40 per cent. No further call is expected for that year.
<P>
A much improved claims experience helped the London Club figures. Peters says in the report that the improvement is in contrast to the experience of some other P&amp;I Clubs, and it reflects an improvement in the quality of the entered tonnage. 
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Investing"></A><H3>Investing in efficiency</H3>

The London Club has a new home. In a $5.2m investment move, the club has moved its managers into a 27,000 sq ft building in Leman Street. Financial director of A. Bilbrough, Bryan Gaze, says the move has already led to an improvement in staff morale and efficiency. "And with us as tenants, the building is already worth more than we paid for it, including the cost of fitting it out."
<P>
<IMG SRC="../images/ldn_off.jpg" ALT="50 Leman Street" WIDTH=198 HEIGHT=142 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 BORDER=1 ALIGN=right>The move to 50 Leman Street (pictured right) at the end of May, was just in time for Bilbrough staff to get the benefit of the effective air conditioning as heatwaves struck London. The staff liked that, and like the space and facilities of the new office, which include a gymnasium. Club members like the economics of the move, and the benefits it will bring to the club as a whole.
<P>
"A subsidiary of the club bought the building for $3.72m as a shell," says Gaze. "It cost about another $1.5m to fit out, including furniture." That compares with about $12m for a similar building in Leadenhall Street, or $0.75m per year to continue renting the previous Leadenhall Street offices, which were less than half the size, hot, cramped, and in need of refurbishment. Gaze explains that the club managers had been seeking new premises for some time. "We had to make an urgent decision now," says Gaze, " as we saw the market drying up." The club committee saw the advantages of investing in a property now, and moved swiftly. "On top of the gain in staff morale and efficiency,  we have space to expand here," says Gaze. "We couldn't hire more staff before, there was no space. Here we have room to expand and we can support that with the  technological update we have made." 
<P>
Gaze estimates that the club has made a handsome capital gain, as the building is already worth about $7.5m. Also, the club is protected against rent rises on its manager's office. But money isn't everything. Location is important, and Leman Street is definitely on the unfashionable eastern fringe of the City area. "It is a rapidly improving area," says Gaze, and he can point to the rash of pubs, restaurants and wine bars opening in the streets around. Other big name shipping entities have buildings in the same area, and you have to pass the Sedgewick building to get to the nearest tube. David Bundock, company treasurer, says its takes him just over twenty minutes to walk from London Bridge rail station, across Tower Bridge. Does he like the building? "I love it," says Bundock. "It creates efficiency."
<CENTER><P>
<I>If you have not visited the new offices of A. Bilbrough &amp; Co, please ring Lance Johnson, marketing director, on +44 (0)171 772 8031 (or send an e-mail for his attention using this <A HREF="mailto:webmail@a-bilbrough.co.uk" onMouseOver="self.status='Pre-addressed e-mail form to A Bilbrough &amp; Co';return true">form</A>) and he will be glad to arrange a tour of the building for you.</I></CENTER>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<A NAME="Scrap"></A><H3>Loss prevention</H3>

SCRAP metal can carry unexpected hazards, both for ships' crews and charterers. In a recent case, a vessel loaded scrap in Kaliningrad, Russia, for southern Europe. After loading, the master noticed a representative of  the shipper measuring nuclear radiation from the cargo. The master became alarmed when he saw increasing geiger-counter readings and informed his owners. They in turn insisted to the shipper and charterer that the entire cargo be unloaded again at Kaliningrad. 
<P>
According to Bremen-based Pandi Services, this is the only case of nuclear contaminated scrap that  they are aware of. However, Pandi says it should be strongly recommended that any owner or charterer who is to load scrap in a country where nuclear contamination is likely should begin monitoring prior to loading. 
<P>
Pandi says owners and charterers should protect themselves and their crews by employing an experienced expert with suitable and reliable instruments to measure possible radiation from the cargo. Monitoring should commence before loading and continue throughout the loading operation.
<P>
If masters suspect that the scrap is radioactive, they should stop loading and seek advice from the local club correspondents. If owners wish to load a scrap cargo which is known to be emitting radiation above ambient levels, then they should seek permission from the load and discharge port authorities, and inform their P&amp;I Club, as cover may be affected.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>

<A NAME="Malaysia"></A><H3>Malaysia cracks down </H3>

THE Malaysian government is cracking down on vessels dumping slops into its coastal waters. The level of policing of coastal waters has been increased since May, and nine vessels were denounced for alleged pollution offences in that month alone. One vessel was chased and fired on by a Malaysian Naval patrol vessel.
<P>
Government sources in Kuala Lumpur say they will establish a laboratory, to be staffed by foreign experts, which will have the sole task of fingerprinting oil samples taken from vessels alleged to have polluted the sea. A new agreement between the Malaysian armed forces, its police and its environment department is aimed at cutting response times to reported pollution incidents to less than one hour. Joint investigative teams will be on the scene and aboard the vessel to take samples. Local P&amp;I correspondent Spica Services warns owners that if vessels are detained in Malaysian waters, there will be delays and probably subsequent fines, in addition to adverse publicity in the regional press. 
<P>
Spica also says Malaysian Shipyard &amp; Engineering is to build a RM25m sludge reception facility. But until that comes along, vessels must either use Singapore's facilities, or exercise extreme care. 
<P>
<UL>
<LI>Malaysia wants to lengthen the Malacca Strait traffic separation scheme to 160 km. It will raise the subject at the IMO in September.
</UL>

<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Brazil targets older bulkers</H3>

BULK carriers over eighteen years old must now have a full structural survey before they can load in Brazil. Two correspondents in Brazil, Pandibra, of Rio de Janeiro, and Proinde, of Santos, both warn that bulkers must now present themselves for loading five days in advance, and owners must contract an approved class surveyor to inspect the ship in accordance with the decree from the Director of Ports and Coasts. The class surveyor must be from an IACS society, but not the society which classes the vessel. In addition to examining the structure, and the vessel must be free of cargo to facilitate this, the surveyor will check that the vessel has valid P&amp;I cover with a recognised club.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Singapore acts on emergency plans</H3>

SINGAPORE'S marine department has taken a tough line on the need for ships to carry emergency plans for dealing with oil spills. The International Convention on Oil Pollution Preparedness, Response and Co-operation 1990 came into force internationally in May this year. It requires all tankers over 150 gt and all other ships over 400 gt to carry a Shipboard Oil Pollution Emergency Plan (SOPEP). The Marine Department in Singapore has reinforced that with a marine notice which says that current Oil Pollution Prevention Certificates, either International or issued by the Singapore marine department, will not be valid from April this year unless an approved SOPEP is carried.
<P>
The plans must include a national operational contact point for urgent reports on incidents involving harmful substances. For Singapore, the contact point is: Port Master, Port Master's department, Port of Singapore Authority. Tel: +65 274711 Ext 1166  Fax: +65 321 1777.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>

<H3>First Person</H3>

THE first person you meet when you visit the London Club <IMG SRC="images/lcn1_4.gif" ALT="Sonia" WIDTH=96 HEIGHT=107 HSPACE=6 ALIGN=right>is not the chairman of the committee, nor the chairman of the managers. It is one of the two receptionists, Sonia Pascall (right) and Keely Goodge (left)<IMG SRC="images/lcn1_5.gif" ALT="Keeley" WIDTH=101 HEIGHT=109 HSPACE=6 ALIGN=left>. They meet visitors and handle telephone calls from all over the world. Sonia, who is learning Russian and Italian as a hobby, says she loves meeting people, and likes the international feel of Bilbroughs. "And you get treated as a person here," says Sonia. "This isn't a yuppy company."
<P>

Sonia lives in Fulham, where she grows vegetables in her spare time. She says she is too independent to be married, and she joined Bilbroughs just one year ago, after temping for some time. Keely is even newer. She joined Bilbroughs six months ago, after a spell of travelling abroad. She worked in claims in an insurance company before joining Bilbroughs, and has her eye on a move up in the company. She also has her eye on a move into the tennis team, which she says is dominated by adjusters at present. 
<P>

Keely says since the move to the new building, she and Sonia see less people. "I like to be busy," she smiles.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<IMG SRC="images/lcn1_6.gif" ALT="Khin Maung Htoo" WIDTH=93 HEIGHT=82 HSPACE=6 VSPACE=6 ALIGN=left>
Three new members have joined the committee in 1995. Captain Khin Maung Htoo, of Myanma 
Five Star Line, Yangon, (left) Peter Cowling, of Wallem Ltd, London and EM Kelly, of Amoco Corporation, Chicago, were appointed in April.
<P>
Lance Johnson, the director responsible for the Far East region, completed thirty years service with Bilbroughs in May.
<P>
Charlie Mold has handed over as senior underwriting director to Mike Hill after reaching the age of sixty.  Charlie will stay on for one year as a consultant.
<P>
Denis Mead has retired after fifteen years with Bilbroughs. Martyn Hughes has taken over from him as manager in Piraeus, and Ian Gooch, claims adjuster, has moved from the London office to join him.
<P>
Ethne Jessop, who processed fees and claims, has retired after eighteen years with the company.
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
<H3>Social News</H3>

JULY was a busy social month for Bilbrough's London staff. Over one hundred and fifty guests enjoyed Singapore dim sum and drinks in the boardroom at a cocktail party held after the first committee meeting in the new building on July 5th. The air conditioning and the carpet both passed the test. Russell Peters paid the managers a compliment, and Graham Edmiston recalled some of the previous Bilbrough offices when thanking the 
committee for providing the new building.
<P>
The football team excelled itself at a tournament hosted by brokers Lloyd Thompson. Competing against twenty teams from other London-based P&amp;I clubs and firms of solicitors, Bilbroughs were knocked out in the semi-final after a penalty shoot out.
<P>
Even honours to the cricket team so far. In July Bilbroughs beat London law firm Richards Butler by eight wickets in a limited overs match held at Guy's Hospital sports ground. The previous match was lost to Holman Fenwick &amp; Willan. 
<P>
