<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The London Club </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>

<H3>Rating The Mutuals - A Club Perspective</H3> 

<B>By Bryan Gaze</B>
<P>
In recent years, assessment of the various entities that make up the P&amp;I industry has become increasingly important. The amounts of money involved are substantial, and most P&amp;I clubs experienced considerable supplementary call volatility in the late 1980's and/or early 1990's. In addition, the well-publicised problems at Lloyd's, and the failure of several insurance companies, led to questions being asked about the relative strengths of enterprises in the P&amp;I field.
<P>
Those interested in the results of such assessments include shipowners and their brokers, bankers, port and other controlling authorities. Most of the P&amp;I industry is made up of mutual organisations, and most of those are members of the International Group. It follows therefore that any assessment of the industry will have to concentrate on the mutual sector. Its unusual characteristics, which are discussed below, make analysis difficult, and may frustrate attempts to rate the mutuals objectively.
<P>
Although several brokers had produced, and continue to produce, quite comprehensive annual reviews of the P&amp;I clubs, these reviews made no attempt at rating. Interested bankers also produce their own analyses, but again without rating.
<P>
Nevertheless, the need for objective assessment led the rating agency, Standard &amp; Poors' (S&amp;P), to publish its 1994 Marine Mutual Report, which has been followed by similar reports in 1995 and 1996. 
<P>
S&amp;P stated in its 1994 Report: "In a departure from normal S&amp;P practices, S&amp;P ranks most of the clubs based on assessments of relative strength, compared with S&amp;P's more normal use of assessments to indicate an opinion of absolute financial strength". 
<P>
S&amp;P identified several areas which it found difficult to analyse, and it may be that the difficulty of analysis caused S&amp;P to adopt its "relative strength" approach. Certainly the unusual characteristics of the clubs, which were summarised by S&amp;P in that report, make a daunting list:     
<OL>
<LI> Lack of paid up capital, profits, and shareholders' funds.
<LI> Difficulty in assessing the strength resulting from "free reserves".
<LI> Lack of consistent information about underwriting year results. 
<LI> Inconsistent accounting treatment of supplementary calls.
<LI> Difficulty in assessing reserving practices, including IBNRs. 
<LI> Difficulty in analysing loss ratios due to volatility of calls. 
<LI> Difficulty in assessing the underlying financial strength of shipowner members. 
</OL>
<P>
It is interesting to consider whether S&amp;P's ratings are as meaningful and authoritative as possible, but first, each of these characteristics needs to be examined in the light of present circumstances:
<P>

<H5>1. Lack of paid up capital, profits, and shareholders' funds.</H5>

This point is incontrovertible - there are no shareholders or profits. However genuinely free reserves are analogous to shareholders' funds, and could be considered to be the clubs' capital. 
<P>
<H5>2. Difficulty in assessing the strength resulting from "free reserves".</H5>

The criteria to be considered would include: - the pattern of growth of those reserves;
- clubs' stated intentions as to the circumstances under which they may be used; 
- the ratios of free reserves to total assets; liabilities; annual call income, etc.
<P>
Considerable volatility was experienced in the late 1980's or early 1990's, with most clubs having had to levy unexpectedly high supplementary calls. That volatility could reappear, but most clubs have now taken steps to build up significant reserves so that only in an exceptionally expensive year would extra supplementary calls be needed.
<P>
<H5>3. Lack of consistent information about underwriting year results.</H5>

Detailed information is now available for most clubs. In addition, although the basis of accounting may vary, the requirements of the EU Insurance Accounts Directive, which are now mandatory for British insurance companies, should lead to even greater disclosure. It should now be possible to obtain adequate comparison of clubs' policy year results, and deteriorations.
<P>
<H5>4. Inconsistent accounting treatment of supplementary calls.</H5>

Supplementary calls which have been authorised but not levied at balance sheet dates are treated in varying ways by different clubs. However, sufficient information should now be available for adequate analysis to be made.
<P>
<H5>5. Difficulty in assessing reserving practices, including IBNRs.</H5>

Unfortunately, it is still not possible to obtain enough information for reliable comparison to be made. All clubs, however, have become aware of the need for early and adequate estimating of individual outstanding claims, and it should not be too long, therefore, before all clubs publish this information on a Policy Year basis. Many clubs now use consulting actuaries to project Incurred But Not Reported claims (IBNRs), together with actuarial forecasting techniques, and again it must be hoped that this information will soon be explicitly published.
<P>
S&amp;P has done great service in this regard, as it has requested that clubs provide information regarding the amount of IBNRs included in their total outstanding claims estimates, and most clubs consider it is in their interest to co-operate with S&amp;P, which therefore should have the beginnings of a powerful additional database. 
<P>
<H5>6. Difficulty in analysing loss ratios due to volatility of calls.</H5>

This point may be less relevant now than it was when S&amp;P prepared its first report.
<P>
<H5>7. Difficulty in assessing the underlying financial strength of shipowner members.</H5>

It is impossible to evaluate accurately the underlying "capital" of the clubs, but it should always be borne in mind that clubs have formidable legal powers to make extra calls on their members if required. This factor, more than any other, provides assurance to those concerned with all aspects of shipping, that clubs are financially extremely sound organisations.
<P>
S&amp;P has made a major contribution to the subject of assessment of clubs, and its reports are most valuable. However, it seems rather unfortunate that S&amp;P has found it necessary to prepare relative, rather than absolute, rankings. S&amp;P states, under the `flag' system it adopts, that clubs have financial characteristics which suggest a lesser (three flags), average (two flags), or greater (one flag) expected need to rely on unforecast supplementary funding from members to meet claims.
<P>
As noted above, most clubs are now maintaining, and increasing, reserve funds, and are therefore unlikely to suffer from unexpected fluctuations in supplementary calls except in years which are abnormally claims-heavy. The `average expected need to rely on unforecast supplementary funding from members to meet claims' is therefore very low, and the relative ratings are less useful as a consequence. 
<P>
Absolute ratings, on the other hand, would be much more useful. Financially interested parties would find it easier to assess the mutuals, and clubs could all aspire to the highest rating, which, if achievable, would be of great benefit to the whole of the shipping and related industries. By definition, whilst `average' criteria are adopted, this cannot be possible. The progress made in respect of most of the special characteristics listed above means that absolute ratings must now be a realistic proposition.
<P>
<BR>
<CENTER><I>Bryan Gaze is deputy chairman, A Bilbrough &amp; Co Ltd, managers of the London Steam-Ship Owners' Mutual Insurance Association Limited.</I></CENTER>
<P>
<HR WIDTH=80% ALIGN=center SIZE=2>
<BR>
The above article was published in <I>Lloyds List</I> on 5 June 1996
