<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The London Club </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>The P&amp;I Industry today
</H3> 
<B>by Graham Edmiston, chairman, A Bilbrough &amp; Co, managers of the London P&amp;I Club
</B>
<P>
THE P&amp;I industry is facing up to change. It is a long-established, respected and vital part of shipping, but it has, until now, been a low-key and often misunderstood  sector of the industry. Today the P&amp;I clubs are changing internally to become more responsive to the needs of the shipowners who are the club members, and changing  externally as they need to fight more vociferously and openly for their interests. Inevitably, this puts the spotlight on P&amp;I as a whole, and that light has shown up some divisions in what was traditionally a united front put up by the club managers. But the fundamentals have not changed.
<P>
P&amp;I is big business. About ninety per cent of the world's ocean-going merchant fleet, over 400m gt, is entered in the fourteen protection and indemnity clubs which make up the International Group. Together, the group clubs' annual premium income is about $1.7bn, and they hold assets of about $4bn.
<P>
The clubs insure shipowners on a mutual basis against third party liabilities. But they do more. They also protect shipowners' interests generally. They provide security by way of club undertakings if needed to get a member's ship released from arrest, they handle and defend claims against shipowners with the help of  a worldwide network of correspondents, lawyers, surveyors and technical experts. And they are taking an increasingly high profile role in representing shipowners' interests in international organisations such as IMO, Intertanko, The ICS, BIMCO and the CMI. 
<P>
Many of the senior club managers are lawyers and they are relied upon as legitimate, respected and authoritative spokesmen for shipowners at international conferences. Club managers have a strong professional ethos and they have rightfully earned the respect of the shipping community over many years.
<P>
Clubs are not simply insurers. They work to help shipping generally. They are currently active in analysing the causes of  marine casualties and claims. Since over sixty per cent of major claims on the clubs are attributed to human error, they are also taking an increasing interest in the manning of ships. Using this analysis, and their experience of what can go wrong, the clubs are promoting loss prevention polices, and have put their weight behind the ISM Code, which is intended to strengthen the management of ships.
<P>
The clubs are at the forefront of efforts by the world's marine insurance industry to improve maintenance, manning and operational standards ashore and afloat. Their own programmes of ship inspections anc condition surveys are an important part of international efforts to eliminate sub-standard ships.
<P>
Most of the group clubs were formed in the nineteenth century. There are nine British managed clubs, three in Scandinavia and one each in America and Japan. A  strong family tradition runs through club management, with families such as the Rileys, the Millers, the Holmans and the Poulssons having been involved for more than a century. Club managers are part of a proud tradition and managers take a very paternalistic and protective attitude towards their members.
<P>
That may change slightly as today's shipowners are less willing to take for granted that the clubs  will always be right. It came as a surprise to the shipping community when differences between club managers and club boards over the issue of the introduction of a limit on P&amp;I cover spilled over into the press during 1995. Cover was traditionally unlimited, but many shipowners feel that this is too risky a position to continue. A majority of the clubs forced the group to adopt the so-called "twenty per cent compromise", which introduces a notional overall limit on club cover of about $20bn. In practical terms this preserves unlimited cover, and of course, unlimited risk. That will stand for the 1996 policy year, but several clubs have now sent questionnaires to their members on the issue and it appears that an overwhelming majority of shipowners are in favour of a lower limit. We expect to see a more realistic limit within the next two years.
<P>
The Greek shipping community has relied heavily on the services of club managers and individual owners have shown great loyalty to their chosen clubs. Today Greek owners are part of the movement of change within the clubs, and are playing an increasingly prominent role in the direction of club policy. Miles Kulukundis was the last chairman of the UK Club, John M Lyras is current chairman of the London Club  and these two clubs, which have the largest Greek membership, and the West of England Club, all have Greek vice-chairmen. These three clubs also have offices in Greece.
<P>
There have been times when Greek owners have opposed International Group policy, and Greek owners' associations are taking an active role in the debate over limitation on cover. But overall, the relationship between the Greek shipping community and the International Group P&amp;I clubs has been close and harmonious. Change will come, but that relationship is likely to grow closer in the future as Greek influence on club boards grows.
<P>
<I>This article was written for</I> Naftemoriki<I>, May 1996</I>
<BR>
