<HEAD>
<TITLE> The London Club </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<H3>Greece and the P&amp;I Clubs
</H3> 
<B>By Graham Edmiston, Chairman, A Bilbrough &amp; Co, Managers of the London P&amp;I Club</B>
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, Greece was not, by and large, a very sophisticated shipping market. Today, it is both sophisticated and knowledgeable, and second only as a shipmanagement centre to the Far East. It is home to the head offices of some of the largest and most advanced shipmanagement operations in the world. And it is a very demanding and discriminating consumer of shipping services.
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, many small Greek shipowners bought defence cover as part of their P&amp;I
package, without knowing what it offered. Now most Greek shipowners and their managers are well-acquainted with the P&amp;I rulebook and expect and demand a high standard of service from
their clubs.
<P>
Any P&amp;I club competing in the Greek market has to provide a high standard of service, both in
terms of time and commitment and in practical experience and legal and technical knowledge.
Greece is a very demanding market for P&amp;I club managers, because Greek owners tend to lean
heavily on their clubs for legal and professional support and advice.
<P>
Greek shipping companies, being family-controlled, value personal relationships with the providers of shipping support services. They also value tradition, and they often show remarkable loyalty towards - and confidence in - their professional advisers, including their P&amp;I club managers. Many old-established Greek shipping companies have remained with the same P&amp;I club for many decades, in some cases approaching a century.
<P>
Traditionally, Greek shipowners eat, sleep and drink the business. Many Greek owners have learnt
the lesson that good service counts for much more than a marginal reduction in premium rating,
which may well prove an illusory benefit, if higher supplementary calls result.  Any reduction in premium rating can soon be offset by the loss of income to shipowners if their ships remain under arrest for a period of days, while their clubs investigate the casualty and take time to arrange the necessary security to release the ships.
<P>
Greek shipowners take their membership of P&amp;I club boards seriously and take a very active
interest in club affairs. Thus, it was not surprising that they should have reacted more quickly and more strongly than other shipowners' associations to the 20 per cent compromise proposal for the limitation of club cover, which was introduced to the shipowning community, by stealth, in April 1995.  
<P>
The Greek shipping organisations were the first to protest publicly against the compromise proposal and attracted some unpopularity as a result. However, it is quite clear from the response received to the UK Club's recent questionnaire to its membership that the desire for a lower limit on club cover is shared by shipowners in North America, Scandinavia, the Middle East, the UK, France, Germany and the Far East as well as in Greece.
<P>
Given their traditional distrust of bureaucracy, authority and regulation, Greek owners will continue to question established practice and convention and to challenge accepted wisdom. They are strong supporters of the P&amp;I mutual system although, to date, they have not played a prominent role in club management. There are now a number of Greeks employed by the clubs, however, and it seems inevitable that some will rise to the top in the foreseeable future.
<P>
The relationship between the Greek shipowning community and P&amp;I clubs has been somewhat
shaken over the last twelve months by the compromise limitation debate, and the owners will be
expecting their club managers to press their demands for a lower limit during the current year.
However, the relationship between Greek owner and P&amp;I manager remains, for the most part, one
of mutual trust and respect. 
<P>
The London Club's Greek membership has more than doubled over the last five years and stands
at 12.5m gt today - almost half the club's directly entered tonnage. The managers are confident
that, provided they can maintain the level of service to this growing clientele, then their links with the Greek shipping community will continue to strengthen.
<P>
<I>This article was written for </I>Naftiliaki, <I>April 1996</I>
<P>
<BR>
