</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The London Club </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<H3>A healthy change
</H3> 
<B>By Graham Edmiston, chairman of A Bilbrough &amp; Co, managers of the London Club</B>
<P>
<I>Graham Edmiston recently addressed the "P&amp;I - Is There A Future For Mutuality" conference organised by IBC in London. In this article he looks at the changing relationship between P&amp;I clubs and their managers</I>
<P>
ALL fourteen clubs in the International Group are well-established institutions. Indeed, nine of them are over a hundred years old. Most clubs can boast the continuous membership of some shipowners since the turn of the century.
<P>
The relationships between the managers and the members of these clubs is also steeped in tradition.  But the relationship has changed a great deal over the years, most recently as a result of the debate among the clubs over whether to accept the International Group compromise proposal on limitation of liability.
<P>
While many of the founding club managers were shipowners, most now have a professional rather than a commercial background. Many are lawyers, some are former seafarers and former employees of shipping companies, some come from the Lloyd's insurance market and a few are accountants.
<P>
Until recently, the general ethos and spirit of club management was professional, with a strong legal bias. There was not a terribly strong reputation for financial management because the financial growth of the clubs was not considered to be of prime importance. Close financial estimating, budgeting and control was not considered an essential of club management.
<P>
Now there is a much stronger focus on the financial affairs of the clubs. This includes sophisticated computer programing and actuarial projections for budgeting and forecasting purposes, strategic control of the management of club investment funds, and corporate strategic planning in order to make use of the most favourable tax and regulatory environments. Thus, financial directors are now vital members of the new senior management teams.
<P>
The relationship between the manager and the member has strong similarities to the lawyer/client and doctor/patient relationships. The manager is in a position of fiduciary trust, operating in accordance with a rulebook which effectively constitutes a code of ethics. Managers must try to treat all members alike, from the largest to the smallest, in a fair and even-handed - but, if necessary firm - manner. They do of course have the power to exercise the ultimate sanction - termination of membership - but members are entitled to the benefit of the doubt for as long as they are with the club. In the past, managers have not been in the habit of taking a member's premium and then rejecting a claim on a technicality.
<P>
In recent years, club managers have taken a greater interest in the condition of  entered ships. Many clubs now undertake pre-entry condition surveys and continuous ship inspection programmes. Some club managements have taken a particular initiative in helping their members to introduce and improve their safety management systems. Club managers are also taking a more active and positive role in promoting greater loss prevention awareness and safer working practices on board their members' vessels.
<P>
Very few club managers have a commercial or business background. In the absence of any formal management training or qualifications, they pick up management skills as they go along. They learn by trial and error. Most club managements are independent companies which negotiate a management fee with the club's board on an annual basis. Many are partnerships. As a general rule, they do not expect to make a fortune. They do expect to make a decent living as successful professionals.
<P>
Club managers are not exposed to the commercial vagaries of the shipping market. Indeed, they have in the past been described as sitting on an unsinkable raft. There was a time when club management in the UK was  established and conservative, with each club having its traditional geographical areas of influence. Managers wouldn't dream of visiting the members of other clubs in order to solicit their business. It was not the done thing. It was not cricket. Subsequently, the entry of the Scandinavian clubs into the international market introduced an element of much more aggressive competition, which is still with us today.
<P>
Today, managers spend much of their time marketing or selling, trying to attract new business. They are selling not so much a service as a product. Competition is based more on cost. Under the International Group agreement, holding clubs can indicate to a shipowner that they are likely to be cheaper in the long run than competing clubs. They can point to their supplementary calls record. They can claim that their management costs are less and their service just as good. Indeed, in recent years, many clubs have concentrated on building up their financial strength so as to be sure of keeping within their originally estimated supplementaries.
<P>
Despite all the competition that exists today, the best shipowners and shipping companies usually remain loyal to their clubs and thereby reap the benefits of mutual trust and respect which come from having a long relationship with their managers.
<P>
Past financial performance and future financial projections are not the best ways in which to judge the true worth of a club. All club managers claim to provide a high level of service, but some devote more resources to their service than others. The clubs do not have a uniform reputation for service.
<P>
Clubs are so very well-established and such old institutions compared with most shipping companies that the attitude of the managers towards their members sometimes appears to be paternalistic or patronising. Managers often know what is best for the member and take a decision or give instructions on behalf of the member without fully explaining the options or seeking prior approval. This is understandable, for many reasons.
<P>
Sometimes, a decision has to be taken urgently, and it is often the club funds which are ultimately at risk. Moreover, it is often difficult and time-consuming to explain every aspect of a problem, or a complex point of English law, to a member whose mother tongue is not English. 
<P>
Such difficulties, however, are no excuse for not taking the time and trouble to explain everything that has to be explained. Too many club managers have taken too little trouble in the past, There is evidence that shipowners will expect more in the future. This must be right because, without shipowners, there would be no P&amp;I clubs, and there is no reason why those shipowners should be English.
<P>
The catastrophe/limitation debate, which crystallised into the acceptance of a group compromise proposal at renewal this year, has further changed the relationship between managers and club members. It has revived the interest of the shipping and insurance industries in P&amp;I, and of shipowners in their clubs. It has also led to the managers of all the clubs writing to their members at some length on the subject, and justifying the position they have taken in the debate. It does seem that the managers and boards of a number of clubs want to canvass the views of their members and will be doing so this year.
<P>
Some participants in the debate remain of the view that the maintenance of group unity is of such paramount importance that club boards should have accepted the recommendations of the working group of club managers without question. The compromise proposal certainly represented an attempt by the managers of the leading club protagonists, for and against the limit, to find a peace formula which would put this troublesome and divisive subject to rest for as long as possible. But it is unsatisfactory.
<P>
We effectively have a continuation of unlimited cover, with the member just as exposed to the risk of bankruptcy in the event of an overspill claim as ever before. I can only conclude that the debate which has ensued is healthy. Club managers have served their members very well over the years but they should not always presume to know what is best for them. Managers should be prepared to listen to their members as well as guide and protect them.
<P>
The public nature of the catastrophe debate has accelerated a process of change in the manager/member relationship which was already under way. Competition and globalisation were already forcing club managers to pay close attention to the needs of their members. But this debate has shown both managers and members that club boards don't always represent the full scope of the membership.
<P>
If club managers continue to turn a deaf ear to the views of their members, the relationship of trust and respect which has been developed between managers and members over many decades will gradually be eroded. Club managers must help develop practical, commercial solutions to shipowners' legitimate needs - and the simpler the better. Complicated, intellectual, theoretical, legalistic castles in the air are a complete waste of time.
<P>
Club managers are professionals serving a very commercial insustry. They must find commercial solutions. They will only find those solutions by listening carefully to their members. If club managers become too remote and aloof from shipowners, they will no longer be able to serve them properly. Club managers should not assume a position of intellectual superiority. 
<P>
The limitation debate has shaken up the relationship between managers and members. Managers now realise that they must inform, advise and consult their members more on important subjects. Members will be looking at their managerrs and their clubs with a close and more critical eye in the future. They will be less inclined to accept their managers' recommendations without question, particularly on important matters of general principle.
<P>
The commercial interests of club managers and club members do not always coincide. But it would be a gross exaggeration to say that that the limitation debate has undermined for ever the relationship between the two. The relationship is in fact still a strong and healthy one.
<P>
The jury is still out on the compromise limitation solution, as it now stands. Members, and informed market commentators, are waiting to see what club managers will do next. Whatever happens, club managers will not be able to hide behind their club boards. It will not be good enough for them to say that they have no mandate from their boards to participate in further discussions on limitation. 
<P>
Members still have a great fund of trust and confidence in their managers, but they will be watching them closely during the new club year.
<P>
<BR>
<I>This article was written for </I>P&amp;I International<I>, May 1996</I>
<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
