<HEAD>
<TITLE> The London Club </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<H3>Greece and the P&amp;I market</H3> 
<P>
<B>By Graham Edmiston, Chairman, A Bilbrough &amp; Co, Managers of the London P&amp;I Club</B>
<P>
Having been involved as a P&amp;I and defence club manager with the Greek shipping community over the last 25 years, I have witnessed at close hand the steady development of this market, both in numbers and size of ships and owners and in the standards of ship maintenance, operations and management, in professional and technical training and in organisation and skills. 
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, Greece was not, by and large, a very sophisticated shipping market. In those days, an expatriate shipping executive in Piraeus could say with some justification : In the kingdom of the blind, the one-eyed man is king.
<P>
Now Greece is a very sophisticated and knowledgeable shipping market and the major centre of shipmanagement outside the Far East.  It houses the head offices of some of the largest and most advanced shipmanagement operations in the world. And it is a very demanding and discriminating consumer of shipping services.
<P>
Twenty-five years ago, many small Greek shipowners bought defence  cover as part of their P&amp;I package, without knowing what this cover offered. Now most Greek shipowners and their managers are well- acquainted with the P&amp;I rulebook and expect and demand a high standard of service from their P&amp;I clubs.
<P>
Any P&amp;I club competing in the Greek market has to provide a high standard of service, both in terms of time and commitment - which often extends outside normal office hours - and in practical experience and legal and technical knowledge. Greece is a very demanding market for P&amp;I club managers. Greek owners tend to lean heavily upon them for legal and professional support and advice.
<P>
The reward for providing a good and reliable service and constant support and assistance to the shipowner in its hour of trial and need is the shipowners' respect, loyalty and friendship over many years.  Greek shipping companies, being family-controlled, value personal relationships with the providers of shipping support services and also tradition, and they often show remarkable loyalty towards, and confidence in, their professional advisers, including their P&amp;I club managers. Many old-established Greek shipping companies have remained with the same P&amp;I club for many decades, in some cases approaching a century.
<P>
While Greek shipowners demand a great deal from their P&amp;I club managers from time to time, they are not slow to show their appreciation for good work done. Traditionally, Greek shipowners eat, sleep and drink the business, and if their P&amp;I club managers support this dedication, then a close relationship of mutual trust and respect will develop. Many Greek owners have learnt the lesson that good service counts for much more than a marginal reduction in premium rating, which may well prove an illusory benefit, if higher supplementary calls result.  Any reduction in premium rating can soon be offset by the loss of income to shipowners if their ships remain under arrest for a period of days, while their clubs investigate the casualty and take time to arrange the necessary security to release the ships.
<P>
The Greek shipowning community is now well-represented on the boards of P&amp;I clubs. Until October 1995, Miles Kulukundis was chairman of the UK Club.  In January 1996, John M Lyras was elected chairman of the London Club, and Spyros Polemis is chairman of the Newcastle Club.  The West of England has two Greek vice-chairmen.
<P>
Greek shipowners take their membership of P&amp;I club boards seriously and take a very active interest in club affairs. Thus, it was not surprising that they should have reacted more quickly and more strongly than other shipowners' associations to the 20 per cent compromise proposal for the limitation of club cover, which was introduced to the shipowning community, by stealth, in April 1995.  The Greek shipping organisations were the first to protest publicly against the compromise proposal and attracted some unpopularity as a result. However, it is quite clear from the response received to the UK Club's recent questionnaire to its membership that the desire for a lower limit on club cover is shared by shipowners in North America, Scandinavia, the Middle East, the UK, France, Germany and the Far East as well as in Greece.
<P>
Because P&amp;I clubs are mutual organisations, Greek shipowners will continue to play an increasingly active role at board level, in the direction and policy-making of the clubs. With their traditional distrust of bureaucracy, authority and regulation, they will continue to question established practice and convention and to challenge accepted wisdom.  They are strong supporters of the P&amp;I mutual system because of the clubs' strong traditions of professional service and dedication and because the clubs are living, evolving institutions, responsive to the members' needs and demands.
<P>
To date, Greeks have not played a prominent role in club management, but there are now a number of Greeks employed by the clubs, and it seems inevitable that some will rise to the top in the foreseeable future.
<P>
The relationship between the Greek shipowning community and P&amp;I clubs has been somewhat shaken over the last twelve months by the compromise limitation debate, and they will be expecting their club managers to press their demands for a lower limit during the current year. However, the relationship between Greek owner and P&amp;I manager remains, for the most part, a healthy one of mutual trust and respect. Both sides recognise the value of each other's traditions and also look towards the future with pride and confidence.
<P>
The London Club's Greek membership has more than doubled over the last five years and stands
at 12.5m gt today, almost half the club's directly entered tonnage. The managers are confident
that, provided they can maintain the level of service to this growing clientele, then their links with the Greek shipping community will continue to strengthen.
<BR>
<BR>
<A HREF="../press.htm" onMouseOver="self.status='Top of this selection of magazine articles';return true">Back to the London Club magazine articles page</A>
<P>
<BR><I>This article was written for</I> Baltic Magazine, <I>May 1996</I>
