<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> The London Club </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<P>
<H3>Vital role for surveyors in London Club ship inspections
</H3> 
<P>
TAKE one ship, preferably empty, one day and one surveyor, and you can get a good idea if there are problems there or not. That is what Keith Atkinson, director of A Bilbrough &amp; Co, which manages the London Club, thinks. Ship inspections on behalf of P&amp;I Clubs has become solid business for marine surveyors  in the last few years. "We spend a lot on ship inspections each year," says  Atkinson. "But the savings are worth it."
<P>
Atkinson is an ex-seafarer himself, and is not alone in that on the board of Bilbroughs. The managers have a reputation for working with owners and helping them, but that doesn't mean they will tolerate ships which do not meet the standards of the club. And their own expertise gives them confidence when it comes to judging the work of surveyors. The London Club carried out 508 ship inspections in the 1994-95 policy year, using contracted surveyors for all of them. "We used to employ staff surveyors, " says Atkinson. "But it is not cost effective as almost all the inspections are done outside the UK, and it is easier and cheaper to use surveyors who are on the spot." 
<P>
To ensure consistency and quality, Bilbrough has a technical manager, James Croall, who assesses surveyors and checks their credentials before entering them on the list of approved surveyors for use by the club. Standard guidelines are given to each surveyor for the inspections. "We call these inspections, not condition surveys," says Atkinson. "We expect surveyors to complete the inspection in one day. A condition survey would take much longer. But a good surveyor can get a fair idea of the ship and crew in one day." The guidance notes come with a standard report form, which allows the surveyor to report items in a YES/NO/Not Examined format. This cuts down on the amount of subjective reporting required. That makes analysis simpler, and reporting more certain. But Atkinson does not discourage amplifying remarks, which the surveyor can attach, and he certainly wants to hear about items of concern, if any, even if they are not specifically asked for on the form.
<P>
"It is essential that the surveyors know exactly what we want," says Atkinson. "Different clubs have different requirements, which is why we give surveyors our own standard guidelines."  That contrasts with the approach taken by Bilbrough when employing surveyors for cargo and property damage surveys. "In most cases the choice of surveyors for damage surveys is left up to our local correspondent," says Atkinson. "We expect them to know the right person for the job locally, but we do keep a register of technical experts in the UK who we can send out if required." 
<P>
For ship inspections, The London Club expects surveyors to liaise with the shipowner to find a suitable time to inspect the ship when it is free of cargo. However, hose tests and pressure tests of tanks are not mandatory at each inspection unless visual inspection makes them seem a good idea. Likewise, if the surveyor can safely enter topside tanks, an inspection of a sample of two is considered enough.
<P>
Tanker inspection is difficult, because cargo tanks are unlikely to be gas free, but the club says a representative sample of two tanks should be inspected if gas free, and two ballast tanks should be inspected internally and reported on. 
<P>
At the end of the inspection, masters get a deficiency list and James Croall wants to see a preliminary report on the fax straight away. A full report, with colour photos, is expected within ten days. But surveyors are warned not to step out of their ground, as it is the prerogative of the club managers to take action over deficiencies, and if follow up inspections are needed, they will normally be to owner's account.
<P>
The results of the inspections show that the same old problems just keep coming back, and certain classification societies seem to be more prone to have ships with deficiencies than others. Hatch covers are a perennial problem, and despite all the effort put into education, the number of deficiencies relating to hatch covers is still higher than Atkinson would like, making up a large proportion of all cargoworthiness deficiencies. Seals, channels, cleats and wedges make up the bulk of the problems. 
<P>
But inspections are not just about steelwork and hatch covers. "We need independent inspectors to look at crewing practices and operational procedures," says Atkinson. "Claims don't arise just because of mechanical items. Shipboard management, manning and qualifications are of vital importance and we want to see them assessed and reported on." Atkinson says that by including the personnel element, P&amp;I ship inspections go beyond class surveys, and enable the managers to form a view of the underlying quality of the owner's operation.
<P>
Ship inspections lend themselves to standard forms and check lists. But Bilbroughs has not attempted to enforce standardisation on cargo and damage surveys. "Each case is different," says Atkinson. "We expect competent surveyors to know what is needed, and if they are not competent, we don't want to employ them." The occasional problems which Atkinson sees with survey reports come from surveyors who express an opinion when no opinion is needed on matters which are not within their areas of technical competence. "If we ask for a report on fire damage, for example," says Atkinson, "we want a report of what the surveyor sees, but an opinion as to cause at that stage may make it difficult for the fire expert later." Other surveyors are too brief, and Atkinson says there is the very occasional unsatisfactory report from far flung places. "Then we have to decide if it is worth flying someone out there or not," he says.
<P>
Surveyors compete fiercely for P&amp;I business, and the advent of containerisation has meant less local cargo damage work to be shared out. To some extent, the new work that ship inspections created has compensated. But Atkinson says there is likely to be a downward trend there, at least as far as the London Club is concerned. "We inspect ships which are over  ten years old," he says. "But as the average age of our fleet improves, there are less inspections." In 1991/92 the London Club had 909 ships eligible for inspection and 573 were selected. Last year, despite an increase in tonnage for the club, there were 775 ships eligible, and 550 were selected. The age profile is falling constantly as the club's underwriters actively exclude older and smaller tonnage, concentrating on  less risky newer and larger bulk tonnage. The London Club has definite plans to get bigger, but not at the expense of taking on poor quality tonnage. That must mean a boost for ship inspection work when the new members first come along. But as most of the new tonnage will be in the younger bracket, there will be less inspections overall and in the future. Inspections will remain as a major tool in the club's loss prevention programme, helping to control claims and so rewarding members by reducing the total claims cost. Good news for the London Club, mixed news for surveyors.
<P>
<BR><I>This article was written for </I>The Maritime Consultant &amp; Surveyor, <I>May 1996</I>
<BR>
