<h3>Foreign Media Reaction </h3>
<H2>Digest</H2>
<p>
<h4>Office of Research and Media Reaction</h4>
<p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC=foot.gif><p>
<i>Thursday, June 27, 1996</center></i>
<p>
<h3>
<p>DHAHRAN BOMB ATTACK:<br>
'A STRIKE AGAINST U.S. INFLUENCE'</H3></center>
<p>
<p>
The bomb attack that left a wake of death and destruction in the U.S.
military complex in Dhahran, Saudi Arabia, topped all electronic and print
coverage around the world, with most commentators stressing that it
represents both a challenge to "U.S. influence in the region" and to the
Saudi ruling family.  One other target frequently cited was the Middle
East peace process itself, with analysts pointing to Secretary
Christopher's mission in the region to buttress this argument.  The
independent, centrist Jordan Times concluded, "We believe that the peace
process in the  Middle East, and the regional order that is emerging as a
result of its  progress and development, is the real target of the two
acts."   In Israel, pluralist, independent Maariv asserted, instead, that
the attack:  "lends extra weight to Prime Minister Netanyahu's argument
that combatting terror transcends all other issues."  Moscow's reformist,
youth Komsomolskaya Pravda held, "Moscow was right...in that by putting
pressure on Arabs, while supporting Israel, Washington was courting big
trouble."
 
Observers sharply disagreed as to who might be responsible for the blast. 
Many argued that it was "home grown" terrorism directed at the
"feudalistic" rulers of Saudi Arabia.  Others, however, saw the hand of
Iran or other terrorist states behind the tragedy.   The conservative
Daily Telegraph of London insisted that Iran must be "isolated," since its
"shadow hangs over all Western allies in the region."   Tehran TV aired
Iran's foreign minister's vehement denials of these charges.  Journalists
also differed over what the law-abiding nations could do against
terrorism, although most concluded that the U.S. would not withdraw from
Saudi Arabia, as it did from Lebanon during the Reagan years.    Finally,
pundits speculated as to how the death of American soldiers would affect
President Clinton during an election year.  "This (attack)," Paris's
influential Le Monde concluded, "limits the U.S. president's  room for
diplomatic maneuver, at a time when he needs it (most) in the  Middle
East."<p>

        G-7 SUMMIT:  A VARIED AGENDA; QUESTIONS ABOUT EFFECTIVENESS<p>
                                       
As the 22nd G-7 summit begins today in Lyon, France, scenesetters posed
the usual questions the annual get-together seems to generate:  What
should be the focus of the summit agenda; should  G-7 summitry be
reformed; are the pronouncements by the G-7 useful and effective?  Some
analysts reviewed the history of the G-7, begun in the 1970s as a response
to the worldwide recession, and urged the industrialized countries to
refocus on economics. One trade issue sure to loom large, some writers
said, will be U.S. trade sanctions policy--particularly as spelled out in
the Helms-Burton Act.  However, opinionmakers held that other issues will
probably dominate the agenda, with several noting the announcement by
President Clinton that he will push action against international terrorism
as the top issue in the wake of the bombing of the American military
complex in Saudi Arabia.  Some media focused on U.S.-European
confrontation inside the G-7.  The absence of Russian President Yeltsin
was the focus in Moscow papers.<p>

BRIEF
   --  Secretary Christopher In The Middle East<p>

EDITORS:  Mildred Sola Neely and Diana McCaffrey<p>


          DHAHRAN BOMB ATTACK:  'A STRIKE AGAINST U.S. INFLUENCE'<p>
                                       
BAHRAIN:  "Criminal Act Against Innocent Civilians And Military Men"<p>

Leading, semi-official Akhbar Al-Khalij (6/27) opined, "The criminal act
was directed against innocent civilians and military  men. And when we say
innocent military men, we mean what we say.  It is not magnanimity nor
heroism attacking military men in their houses away from  the
battlefields.  Not saying that those military men came according to a
bilateral agreement between two countries which have complete independence
and will to decide issues of mutual interests....  The Al-Khobar terrorist
and cowardly operation was not directed against the Americans as much as
it  was against the security of Saudi Arabia, the Gulf region and the
entire Arab nation.  It is also directed against the moderate policies in
the  region."    <p>

ISRAEL:  "Saudi Attack Lends Weight Netanyahu's Argument" <p>

Pluralist, independent Maariv's editorial asserted (6/27),  "The fatal
terror attack in Dhahran lends extra weight to Prime Minister Netanyahu's
argument that combatting terror transcends all other issues and that Syria
is no less a terror sponsoring nation than Iran.  The war on Islamic
terror is a goal common to all civilized nations.  And it's a war that
must be waged immediately, before Muslim radicals get hold of nuclear
weapons."<p>

JORDAN:  "Share Of Responsibility"
  
Columnist Fahed Fanek stressed in pro-government, influential, Arabic-
language Al-Ray (6/27), "America has the right to be angry and call the
doers terrorists....  We  are not looking for an excuse for killing and
violence, but we request  that all parties bear their share of the
responsibility.  Why does the  United States keep tens of thousands of its
soldiers in Saudi Arabia when it knows  that they are not wanted by the
people there?  If the target is to  control Arab oil, then they will have
to pay in American blood....  We  are against anything that puts the
stability of our sister country in danger, but it is more appropriate to
give people the opportunity to express themselves in a more civilized way
and we wonder why people use  explosives instead of ballots."  
    
"Real Target:  Middle East Peace Process"<p>

The independent, centrist, English-language Jordan Times (6/27) concluded,
"We believe that the peace process in the  Middle East, and the regional
order that is emerging as a result of its  progress and development, is
the real target of the two acts."  <p>

GERMANY:  "Democracy, Market Economy"<p>

Siegfried Buschschlueter commented on national radio station
Deutschlandfunk of Cologne (6/26): "What the government in Washington is
demanding from  the Russian government--democracy and market economy--
should also be a demand for the Gulf states.  It should do this quickly,
since the  disintegration of the formerly rich feudalistic oil states
could result  in shake-ups that could have more disastrous consequences
than  yesterday's detonation of the murderous car bomb." <p>

"Election Year Question"<p>

In the view of Jochen Winter in an editorial in left-of-center Frankfurter
Rundschau (6/27), "The United States is paying a dear price for its global
policy and  military engagement.  The attack in Saudi Arabia is not the
first and  will certainly not be the last terrorist attack against U.S.
soldiers and  their families....  Even though the U.S. government has now
said that it will not  give in to terrorism and promised to pursue the
attackers until they have  been caught, many Americans will wonder why
their sons and daughters have  to die in remote countries in which <p>

there is not even the slightest touch  of democracy.  But this is an
election year in the United States, and this is why  Bill Clinton and his
challenger Bob Dole must address this question.  But  it is likely that
the United States will maintain its engagement in the Saudi Arabia."<p>

"A Strike Against U.S. Influence"<p>

Left-of-center Berliner Zeitung (6/27) judged in an editorial by Martina
Doehring, "This terrorist attack is also a strike against the influence of
the  United States in the region....  With great perseverance the United
States  has tried over the past several years to bring quiet and stability
to the  region which is so important for the strategic and economic
interests of  the West....  So far, these successes have been considered
trump cards  in Bill Clinton's election campaign....  But the Middle East
peace  process has bogged down, the problems with Iraq are unresolved,
Iran continues to create trouble and there is unrest in the Gulf states. 
Not  only Bill Clinton's re-election is in jeopardy, but in the long run
also  the U.S. role in the region." <p>

"Target:  Peace Process"<p>

Centrist Der Tagesspiegel of Berlin (6/27) concluded, "It was not a
coincidence that the attack in Saudi Arabia took place  during Warren
Christopher's trip to the Middle East.  The allegedly  Islamic attackers
also wanted to hit the peace process."<p>

BRITAIN:  "Saudi Arabia Key To U.S. Position In Region" <p>

An editorial in the conservative Daily Telegraph commented (6/27): "For
all the comparisons with the bombings of the U.S. Marine barracks and
embassy in Beirut in the mid-1980s, this is one commitment from which no
American government could be seen to retreat.  To do so would encourage
worldwide terrorism against its personnel and installations.  Saudi Arabia
is the key to the American position in the region....<p>

"But whoever did it, Western policy should be based on three constants:
First, that for all its faults, the House of Saud remains the best option
available.  Second, that the Western powers should not be panicked into
precipitate action: although the domestic opposition, of various stripes,
has become bolder, the regime's problems are still light years away from
those of Algeria just before large-scale violence broke out there.  And
third, none of this should preclude Western governments from quietly
urging the Saudis to adopt a cautiously reformist program to introduce
greater political pluralism, of the kind initiated by King Hussein in
Jordan. <p>

"Even if it turns out that indigenous Saudi groups were solely to blame,
none of this removes the need for European nations to do more to combat
the menace of Iran, whose shadow hangs over all Western allies in the
region.  Iran needs to be isolated: it must become a pariah permitted to
talk and do business only with other rogue states, such as North Korea. 
The policy of 'critical dialogue," pushed by the EU, has served only to
convince Iran that Western Europe puts commercial interests ahead of
security needs."<p>

"Focus Anti-Terrorism Efforts In Region"
 
According to the conservative Times (6/27), "Lyons is not where America
needs to concentrate its efforts (against terrorism).  The main need is to
coordinate a more effective regional response to Islamist extremism.  The
bombing has been as firmly condemned by Syria's President, Hafez Assad,
and by Yasser Arafat as by America's traditional allies in the Middle
East.  They must be assumed to be sincere; instability in Saudi Arabia
unsettles the entire region, to the profit only of Iraq and Iran.  This
atrocity should therefore assist the American drive...to convince Arab
governments and security forces that terrorism is their common enemy."<p>

<p>

<p>

"Home Grown Saudi Affair" <p>

Middle East correspondent Robert Fisk wrote for the centrist Independent
(6/27): "Yesterday, Middle East experts were producing their usual
theories of an international Muslim conspiracy....  If only it was that
simple.  Iran's religious leaders will feel no pity for the Americans, but
the chances are that yesterday's bombing was a home-grown Saudi affair, a
new phase in the most violent internal opposition ever to confront the
House of Saud and its Western supporters." <p>

FRANCE:   "Iranian Connection?"<p>

Private, influential TV TF-1 and public France 2-TV (6/26) hinted at 
Iranian connections.  <p>

"No U.S. Disengagement, On The Contrary"<p>

Jacques Malmassari said in an editorial in influential Liberation (6/27):
"For Washington, protecting the Saudi regime is (a) strategic imperative. 
The U.S. energy policy and, to some extent, its arms  industry depend on
it.  The collapse of the Saudi kingdom, which would  weaken the entire
Gulf region, would be a success for Washington's two  bete noires, Iran
and Iraq.  Also, it would represent a threat to Israel.   This is why one
should not expect the United States to disengage itself from  Saudi
Arabia.  On the contrary, Washington will reaffirm its  interests....  All
the more so since the entire Middle East region may  enter an era of
severe turbulence and increased terrorism if, as one  might fear, the
intransigence of the new Israeli leaders amounts to a  betrayal of
moderate, realistic Arab leaders." <p>

"Limits Clinton's Room For Maneuver"<p>

Influential Le Monde's (6/27) correspondent in the Gulf region Mouna Naim
filed, "This attack represents a risk for Bill Clinton, that of reminding 
voters that this administration, which was elected in 1992 to focus on 
domestic policy, has had to commit itself on multiple fronts abroad and 
that this commitment, in Bosnia or in the Gulf, represents a danger for
U.S. troops involved....  This (attack) limits the U.S. president's  room
for diplomatic maneuver, at a time when he needs it (most) in the  Middle
East." <p>

RUSSIA:  "U.S. Troops To Stay" <p>

Vladimir Dunayev said in reformist Segodnya (6/27): "Washington does not
intend to withdraw its troops from that strategic region." <p>

"More To Come" <p>

Dmitry Kulik filed from Damascus for reformist, youth Komsomolskaya Pravda
(6/27): "The Arab summit in Cairo might provide an impulse for those
seeking to unite the Middle East under the green banner of Islam.  For
them, Israel and the West, primarily the United States are an impediment. 
Evidently, this terrorist act, alas, won't be the last one this year.... 
Many Arabs feel uncomfortable seeing U.S., French and British troops
'trample on the holy places' in the home-land of Islam.  It was not for
nothing that the blast coincided with Warren Christopher's visit to that
region....  The summit in Egypt gave Netanyahu time to think and soften
his stand.  Radicals decided they could not afford that and struck at the
Israelis' ally, the Americans.  The U.S. secretary of state did not listen
when his Russian counterpart warned that a half-hearted decision on the
Lebanon-Israel conflict would not bring peace.  As long as Israel remains
an occupying force, the guerrilla war will continue.  Moscow was right
also in that by putting pressure on Arabs, while supporting Israel,
Washington was courting big trouble."<p>

<p>

<p>

ITALY:  "The West Should Move Together"<p>

Former Under Secretary of Defense  Stefano Silvestri observed in leading
financial Il Sole-24 Ore  (6/27): "This is not the first terrorist attack
against the Western  military presence in Saudi Arabia, but certainly it
is part of a series of moves aimed at destabilizing Arab nations in the
Gulf and penalizing  pro-Western choices: A policy approved and often
encouraged by Iran.   Unfortunately these local threats are part of a more
general problem,  that of U.S. policy toward the countries indicated as
sponsors of  terrorism, mainly Iran and Libya.  That policy has always
been  characterized by very tough positions as well as concrete threats,
but it  now may grow even tougher because of the atmosphere around the
U.S.  presidential elections.  A substantial part of Congress (and of the 
Republican Party, but not only) seems tempted by unilateral choices which 
have a strong hold on public opinion, but which may have serious 
repercussions internationally, such as the Helms-Burton act....<p>

"There are  far more reasonable ways to go.  For example, one could begin
from the  declaration signed in Cairo by the leaders of an overwhelming
majority of  Arab nations (including Syria and Libya) which condemns `all
forms of  terrorism and acts of sabotage and destruction....'  One cannot
deny that,  if nothing else, they indicate at least a possible and ample
area of  understanding and cooperation which it would be absurd and 
counterproductive to ignore, and which could be much more useful against 
terrorism than rash unilateral moves." <p>

THE NETHERLANDS:  "A Threat To Saudi Royal Family"<p>

Influential liberal left  De Volkskrant (6/27) commented, "The attacks in
Saudi Arabia are not only aimed at the American presence  in the Kingdom
and the close political and military ties with the 'big  satan', but they
are also aimed at the regime of King Fahd... It is a regime which does not
tolerate public participation, does not have a parliament, and which
forbids political parties; it is also accused of deviating from  the
Islamic path and having sold its skin to the West.... Corruption and
nepotism are a thorn  in many a Saudi eye... Muslim militants complain
that the thousands of princes live above the  law and ignore Islamic
rules."  <p>

TURKEY:  "Countries Which Support Terrorism Must Pay Price" <p>

Extensive coverage today and last night on TV and the printed press
included 
this column by Hasan Cemal on page one of mass-appeal Sabah (6/27), "If
cooperation against terrorism will not just continue to be rhetorical
following the bombing in Dhahran, then it must be demonstrated in concrete
ways that countries in the region which support terrorism must pay the
price in one way or another.  Otherwise it is impossible to break the
influence of those who dance with terrorism for their political ends.... 
In deploring the attack yesterday President Clinton named Iran and Iraq
but failed to mention Syria.  I wonder why?" <p>

IRAN:  "We Strongly Reject Any Kind Of Involvement In Dhahran
Explosion"<p>

Tehran IRIB television in Persian said (6/26), "Following a joint meeting,
Weizman, the President of the Zionist regime, and U.S. Secretary of State
Christopher accused the Islamic Republic of Iran of involvement in the
Dhahran explosion.   Responding to the accusations, our country's foreign
ministry spokesman today called Weizman and Christopher two ringleaders
and supporters of state terrorism, and rejected their accusations against
Iran.    Mr. Mahmud Mohammadi said America and the Zionist regime are busy
hatching a joint plot aimed at damaging the reputation of the Islamic
Republic of Iran.  He said: blaming Iran for such actions has roots in
America's and Israel's joint hostility against Islam and the Islamic
Republic of Iran, and we strongly reject any kind of involvement in the
Dhahran explosion.    The foreign ministry spokesman added: it seems that
suspicious efforts are under way to strengthen the climate of mistrust in
the region, aimed at paving the way for expanding the Zionist regime's
influence in the region's political, economic, and security structures.
<p>


"We hope that regional countries will vigilantly block the destructive
policies of America and Israel, aimed at creating rifts among Islamic and
Arab countries in the region." <p>

PAKISTAN:   "U.S.:  Obvious Target Of Hate"<p>

An editorial in Islamabad's centrist News (6/27) commented, "The bomb
blast...has to be seen in the context of Washington's policy in the Middle
East.  The Gulf was has long ended but the American troops have stayed
behind....  There is every likelihood that the anger against the Americans
and their troops in Saudi Arabia could have found expression in this
extreme and sad form.  Moreover the Americans have not popularised
themselves in the region by their neurotic obsession with fundamentalism. 
Their support to Hosni Mubarak and their clearly articulated pledges to
blunt the cutting edge of fundamentalist Islam has made anything
associated with them an obvious target of hate." <p>

INDONESIA:  "Who Was Real Target Of Bombing In Saudi Arabia?"<p>

Leading independent Kompas (6/27) declared, "Let the FBI find out who was
behind the bombing.  Regardless of their findings, it is clear that U.S.
interests in Saudi Arabia have become a target.  We can only say that the
people behind the bombing were desperate and bold, risking beheading like
those behind the November bombing....That case was deemed political, as
some felt that the Saudi kingdom had become too close to the U.S....  We
hope the incident will not affect stability in Saudi Arabia, as it is the
only Arab country which has so far taken a moderate stance on the Middle
East issue."<p>

THAILAND:  "Saudi Bomb Spotlights Continued Terror Risk" <p>

The lead editorial of largest circulation, English-language Bangkok  Post
(6/27), strongly condemned the Saudi Arabia truck bombing in the following
editorial:  "In recent times, the car and truck bomb have become a weapon 
throughout the world.  Far from being a weapon of war, these are weapons
against peace.  They are not used by soldiers, but by cowards.  They do 
not terrorize regimes or governments, but only peaceful citizens.  There
are those who will excuse the Dhahran bombing on the basis that most of 
the victims were American servicemen.  This is beside the point.  The 
victims were asleep or at rest, and their duties were not in any way aimed
against Saudi citizens.  Most of those killed or wounded were  involved in
UN and allied efforts to keep the peace in Iraq.   The argument that Saudi
Arabia somehow makes such acts inevitable by its  harsh laws against
internal dissent is equally specious...  The battle  against terrorism
must proceed across borders and must be universal.   Civic, political and
religious leaders have a duty to condemn all  terrorism.  Ends do not
justify the means.  Even the high ideals of a  group do not excuse use of
random and deadly violence against the  innocent"<p>

ARGENTINA:  "The New Logic Of Terror: An Attack With Domestic Roots"<p>

Left-of-center Pagina 12 (6/26) opined, "Like in Lebanon,  there is in
Saudi Arabia a growing Islamic fundamentalist opposition which rejects the
presence of foreign troops--particularly from the  U.S.--and that wish for
an 'Islamization' of life in the country. But  in this case, there are new
ingredients.  Saudi Arabia, main oil producer and exporter, is really a
double-fronted state: Outwardly it is decidedly pro-West and pro-U.S.;
inwardly it is a  closed monarchy, dictatorial and corrupt, in which the
secret police and censorship rule, there is no democratic or semi-
democratic instance and  the Muslim and theocratic faith coexists
uncomfortably with the, literally, pharaonic and squandering lifestyle of
the ruling class....  One would be tempted to ascribe this attack--like
yesterday's -- to an  'Iranian connection', due to the severe opposition
the Saudi monarchy has  consistently maintained against any kind of
expansion of Khomeinism and  Fundamentalism in the area.... 
Unfortunately...the explosions seem to have more domestic origins." <p>

<p>


        G-7 SUMMIT:  A VARIED AGENDA; QUESTIONS ABOUT EFFECTIVENESS<p>
                                       
FRANCE:  "Lyon Air Will Reinvigorate Clinton"<p>

Washington correspondent Stephane Marchand asserted in conservative Le 
Figaro (6/27),  "Five months prior to the presidential election, the Lyon
air will  reinvigorate Bill Clinton.  Thousands of kilometers away from
White House  scandals, far from the Republican Congress, he will claim
credit for the excellent performance of the U.S. economy....  In order to
prevent Bill  Clinton from imposing himself as a star at the summit,
Jacques Chirac  intends to criticize the U.S. attitude vis-a-vis the Third
World." <p>

"Terrorism Should Not Dominate The Agenda In Lyon"<p>

Lise Patelli wrote in regional L'Est Eclair (6/27), "Bill Clinton said
yesterday that he intended to focus on the fight  against terrorism in
Lyon....  However, one hopes that this issue, though  important, will not
(dominate the agenda) of the talks on jobs, currency  and financial issues
and international trade." <p>

"G-7 Works"<p>

Regional Le Republicain Lorrain said (6/27), "Having implemented the 
recommendations of previous G-7 summits, the United States is healthy
again, with  a stable growth rate, low inflation, reduced deficits, a
reasonable  unemployment rate and 10 million jobs created in three
years."<p>

"European Should Present A Truly Collective Front"<p>

In his editorial on Europe One radio, political analyst  Alain Duhamel
said (6/27),: "To make the G-7 summits really balanced, therefore
fruitful, it would be necessary for the Europeans to be better organized
vis-a-vis the United States, i.e., to present a truly collective front. 
Then the G-7 would really be useful."<p>

GERMANY:  "Time To Reform G-7 Meetings?"<p>

Carl Graf Hohenthal judged in right-of-center Frankfurter Allgemeine
(6/27), "The state leaders should try to find out whether the time is not
ripe for a comprehensive reform of  the agenda and the form of the
meeting....  In addition, the economic summit is ailing because too many 
problems are being put on the agenda....  And the subjects are being 
discussed in such a manner that it is being too much for the state 
leaders to comprehend everything.  What have questions to do on the 
agenda such as a discussion about credit financing mechanisms of the IMF 
or the development of an early warning system against debt crises?  These 
questions are important but they must be discussed in the corresponding 
bodies.... <p>

"The state leaders do not really want to address these issues.  They  are
much more interested in presenting themselves.  The U.S. president  wants
to demonstrate new strength and wants to cut a good picture for his 
reelection, the Russian president wants the same and is sending his 
premier, the Japanese premier will refer to the growing significance of 
Asia, and the French president, as the host of the meeting, wants to try  
to present his country from its best side.... It is favorable that
Chancellor Kohl, as the most experienced  leader, wants to remind his
colleagues of the fact that, among the G-7,  there is no leader but only
partners.  The chancellor knows much better than all the other leaders
that an informal get-togethers of equal  partners are much better than
communiques that address all kinds of  subjects....  It would be much
better if the summiteers talked about the  following subjects at the
coming G-7 summits: (to establish) an informal  round of talks without any
communique and the state leaders of important  Asian and Latin American
states would also attend these meetings.  If the  G-7 found an
understanding on this approach, a lot would have been gained  in Lyon."
<p>


BRITAIN:  "Clinton Determined To Put Terrorism At Top Of G-7 Agenda"<p>

On BBC TV's Breakfast News, reporter Brian Hanrahan said from Lyon (6/27),
"President Clinton arrived determined to put action against terrorism at
the top of the G-7 agenda.  He argues that the Dhahran bombing showed
there can be no economic security unless they can stand together against
the forces of terrorism....  The security which surrounds the summit will
reinforce the report of experts who are to submit practical
recommendations to the leaders to deal with terrorism, international crime
and drug smuggling.  It is part of a trend which has turned the summits
away from grandiose plans on foreign affairs and economics.  The leaders
have accepted that they either cannot agree on common policies or they
cannot implement them.  Instead, they agree on common approaches to common
problems."<p>

ITALY:  "Disputes Among Members" <p>

Ennio Caretto wrote in centrist, top-circulation Corriere della Sera
(6/27), "Occurring between the crucial elections in Israel and  Russia,
and on the eve of those in Bosnia in September and the United States in
November, the G-7 summit is likely to have as its watchword  `don't rock
the boat.'  But the G-7 horizon presents more clouds than  clear skies,
and if the summit concludes with a series of postponements  there could be
serious repercussions.... The risk of an impasse at the summit stems from
the unexpected disputes among its members .  Over the  last few months,
America has adopted an exaggerated unilateralism.  It  has placed itself
on a collision course with Europe, in addition to  Japan, regarding trade,
even accusing the latter of stealing contracts  with China.  With its `no'
to Boutros Ghali's re-election, it has  provoked a crisis which could have
been avoided.  It is a strategy which  smells of blackmail, justified by
an America with a superior record of  performance and morality.  U.S.
Treasury Minister Rubin noted, `over the  last three years, we have
created seven times as many jobs as all G-7  nations together, and have
fought G-7 enemies alone.'" <p>

RUSSIA:  "G-7 Will Take Advantage of Yeltsin's Absence" <p>

Dmitry Gornostayev opined on page one of centrist Nezavisimaya Gazeta
(6/27), "The G-7 is likely to take advantage of Boris Yeltsin's absence in
Lyon....  As a participant in so important a forum, Chernomyrdin, being no
big, world-class politician, is quite predictable and is no match for
Yeltsin who can be stunning, at times appearing rather self-confident and
shocking to Western leaders." <p>

"G-7 Members Disappointed Over Yeltsin's  Absence" <p>

Oleg Bergazov reported from Lyon in reformist Segodnya (6/27), "G-7
members were somewhat disappointed on learning that Russian Premier
Chernomyrdin will stand in for President Yeltsin in Lyon, but the leaders
of European countries and the United States said they appreciated the
reasons why Boris Yeltsin could not come." <p>

JAPAN:  "Clinton, Hashimoto Should Discuss Trade Issues Candidly" <p>

Liberal Tokyo Shimbun remarked (6/27), "In his personal letter to Prime
Minister Hashimoto, President Clinton said a successful settlement of
semiconductor, insurance and civil aviation issues is just as important as
the settlement of bilateral security issues.  The president and the prime
minister are to meet prior to the start of the G-7 summit.  Cabinet-level
talks on trade issues are also planned during the Lyon meeting.  We hope
Clinton and Hashimoto will discuss the trade issues in a candid manner. 
As long as the U.S. position is politically-motivated because of the
presidential election, the Clinton-Hashimoto meeting will be futile.  The
U.S. should study--in a serious manner--Japanese proposals for switching
from the governmental semiconductor accord to the establishment of a
private-sector 'cooperation framework' and for holding a multilateral
conference on microchips."<p>

<p>

CHINA:  "Trade Frictions With U.S. Trouble G-7 Summit"<p>

The official Communist Party People's Daily Overseas Edition maintained
(6/27), "The (Helms-Burton) Act, in which the United States unilaterally
imposes sanctions against Cuba and punishes foreign companies having
business with Cuba, has angered allied nations.  A few days ago, the EU
leaders issued a strong warning against this new U.S. trade policy.  EU
leaders denounced the extraterritorial law, saying that it infringes upon
the interests and unity of the allied nations and undermines free trade
principles....  The trade frictions between the United States and the EU
and Canada will trouble the G-7 summit...  Although the summit is not a
forum for resolving international trade disputes, U.S. legislation that
infringes upon the trade interests of the allied nations will inevitably
cast a shadow over the summit.  This situation will further reveal the
awkward and isolated position of the U.S."<p>

 BRIEF<p>

                 SECRETARY CHRISTOPHER IN THE MIDDLE EAST<p>
                                       
EGYPT:  "What Is The U.S. Position"<p>

Salama Ahmed Salama, columnist, pro-government daily Al  Ahram (6/27),
wrote,: "There was no choice before the Arab  summit....  Arab countries
could either accept Netanyahu's  program...and decide to stop
normalization...or to waste  the chance of the Israeli right-wing and
confirm their  insistence on a comprehensive and just peace....  They 
have given Netanyahu's government a chance to reconsider  until...after
the American elections. It was clear that  this chance was meant to be
given to the United States itself....   It is not enough that Washington
demands Arab countries to  be patient and not to stop normalization. 
Christopher has  to tell us what the U.S. position is after Arab countries 
have fulfilled U.S. demands." <p>

"Astonishing"<p>

Pro-government Al Ahram (6/27) opined:  "Strangely, while the new Israeli
government claims that  it supports peace in the region, all its
statements have  nothing to do with the peaceful settlement.  More 
strangely, it has declared this position in Secretary  Christopher's
presence and with his consent....  It is  very astonishing that the
Israeli and American parties  raise the issue of Egypt's obtaining land
missiles...while  Israel is not ashamed to obtain nuclear weapons and to 
refuse to join the NPT.  Then what kind of peace about  which Israel is
talking and what is the meaning of the  American support for its
positions?"<p>

ISRAEL:  "Tough Posture" <p>

Liberal, independent Haaretz (6/27) held, "Prime Minister Netanyahu
displayed in his talks with Secretary of State Christopher a tough posture
which, it must be admitted, was consistent with his election campaign
slogans.... The Prime Minister appears not to have demonstrated even the
tiniest amount of flexibility .... The American reaction can be measured
by the polite reprimand Netanyahu received from the U.S. Secretary who
told him that there can be no security without peace.  Christopher's
comments reflect his disappointment with what he had heard from the Prime
Minister .... That said, it is too early to give Netanyahu up as a lost
case.  He may yet soften his attitude and he may wait for his meeting with
President Clinton to display that change.  It is also true that Netanyahu
owes it to many of his voters to go about the diplomatic process in a
different and slower fashion  than his predecessor."
<p>

