<HTML><BODY><TITLE>USIS Foreign Media Reaction Digest</TITLE>
<center>
<IMG align=left SRC=g7logo.gif>
<h3>Foreign Media Reaction </h3>
<H2>Digest</H2>
<p>
<h4>Office of Research and Media Reaction</h4>
<p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC=foot.gif><p>
<i>Wednesday, June 26, 1996</center></i>
<p>
<h3>
<p>TRUCK BOMB IN SAUDI ARABIA</H3></center>
<p>
<p>
The detonation yesterday evening of a truck bomb outside a Saudi
Arabian
compound housing U.S. and other foreign military personnel came
too late
for commentary in most foreign media, but straightforward reports
of the
explosion and statements by U.S. officials were broadcast by
radio
stations in Iraq, Syria, Jordan and the West Bank.  In London, a
BBC
correspondent speculated that, although the scene in Saudi Arabia
is "very
reminiscent" of the 1983 Beirut bombing that "forced" the
withdrawal of
the Americans from Beirut, "they cannot withdraw from Saudi
Arabia.  Their
commitment to Saudi security is absolute."  Private RTL radio in
Paris,
and Rome's influential <b><i>La  Repubblica</b></i>  both
speculated that
as a result of the bombing, "terrorism may impose itself at the
G-7 summit
in Lyon."<p>
        CHRISTOPHER IN MIDDLE EAST:  'FRUSTRATION OF HOPES' FOR
PEACE?<p>
                                       
Foreign observers' pessimism regarding peaceful progress in the
Middle
East grew stronger following yesterday's talks in Jerusalem
between
Secretary Christopher and Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu.  The
bluntest
assessment came from Moscow's reformist, business-oriented
<b><i>Kommersant Daily</b></i>: "Clinton," it said, "will have to
abandon
his hopes for laurels as a Middle East peacemaker, after all." 
Journalists focused on Mr. Netanyahu's "firmness" in refusing to
commit
himself to a Hebron withdrawal or a meeting with Palestinian
leader Arafat
and on Mr. Christopher's "unhappy and concerned" appearance
during their
press conference.  Israeli Channel 2-TV observed that the
"Americans were
irritated" and top-circulation <b><i>Yediot</b></i> described
them as
"stunned by...Netanyahu's radical positions regarding the
negotiations
with Syria and the Palestinians."  The common perception, shared
by
Israeli and Arab observers, was that Mr. Netanyahu "wants to go
back to
square one" or "wipe the slate clean" and start all over again.

In Cairo, where the secretary holds talks today with the Egyptian
leadership, the press voiced its resentment with developments and
its
disappointment with Mr. Christopher's stance.  Pro-government
<b><i>Al
Akhbar</b></i> stated, "Christopher found nothing to say...but to 
agree
with Netanyahu....  All this indicates that the secretary has
gone  to
Israel not to push the peace process but to ask for Netanyahu's
blessing
of U.S. policies."  The German media were the only ones still
holding out
hope that the "peace process will go on."  Centrist
<b><i>Sueddeutsche
Zeitung</b></i> of Munich insisted that the U.S. secretary of
state
remains, for the peace process, "the right man for the right
time."


BRIEF<p>

 --  G-7 Summit: Clinton 'Strong,' Yeltsin Absent, Europe
'Gloomy'
<p><p>

EDITORS:  Mildred Sola Neely and Pat McArdle<p>


                <center>TRUCK BOMB IN SAUDI ARABIA</center><p>
                                       
IRAQ:  "A Very Powerful Explosive Charge"<p>

Baghdad's <b>INA</b> radio (6/26) noted, "Washington said the
blast, which was
caused by a very powerful explosive charge, destroyed an
eight-story
building which belongs to the Saudi Defense Ministry in which
foreigners
live.....  A senior Pentagon official, who requested
anonymity....spoke
about the way security agencies noticed the truck when it was
approaching
a residential area inside the base, which is surrounded by a
fence.... 
Residents of Al-Khubar, near Dhahran, said the explosion rocked
the
city."<p>

JORDAN:  "All The Hallmarks Of A Deliberate Bombing"<p>

Amman's <b>Radio Jordan</b> in English (6/26) said, "By this
morning, no group
had claimed responsibility for the explosion, but U.S. officials
said the
blast had all the hallmarks of a deliberate bombing....   King
Fahd of
Saudi Arabia has telephoned President Bill Clinton to express his
deep
concern and to offer condolences after the explosion." <p>

SYRIA:  "Intensive Security Efforts Under Way To Arrest
Perpetrators"<p>

Damascus <b>Syrian Arab Republic Radio</b> (6/26) carried this
report:  "The
Saudi Interior Ministry confirmed that 16 Americans were killed
when a
booby-trapped car exploded in front of a building belonging to
the
Ministry of Defense and Aviation in Khubar City in the Eastern
Province.   
The Saudi Press Agency cited a responsible source at the Interior
Ministry
as saying hat it has been confirmed that 16 people were killed,
all
American, and that 252 people of different nationalities were
injured,
some seriously."<p>

WEST BANK:  "Nobody Has Claimed Responsibility"<p>

Jericho's <b>Voice of Palestine</b> (6/26) said, " U.S. President
Bill Clinton
said that the explosion is evidently the result of a terrorist
action.  So
far, nobody has claimed responsibility."<p>

BRITAIN:  "Revenge"<p>

The <b>BBC</b>'s Middle East correspondent Jim Muir said (6/26)
from Nicosia:  "I
think (the bombers) have already achieved what they wanted, which
is
revenge for the execution of the four Saudi nations last
month....  The
Americans have been fearing exactly such an attack, and I think
obviously
it will be deeply alarming both to the Saudis and to the
Americans that
despite the very heightened security precautions that have been
taken,
these people, these Islamic militants, were able to carry out
such a
massive attack under the noses of the authorities."  Asked if the
Americans would now consider leaving Saudi Arabia, Muir said:  "I
think it
will certainly force them to rationalize their presence there,
and the
softer targets, I am sure, will be withdrawn into closely-guarded
compounds--it will be a bit like Beirut.   The scenes we are
seeing now
are very reminiscent of the American Embassy in Beirut, which was
bombed
back in 1983....  That forced the withdrawal of the Americans
from Beirut. 
 They cannot withdraw from Saudi Arabia.   Their commitment to
Saudi
security is absolute.   They will stay there, but they will have
to take
much tighter security precautions."<p>

FRANCE:  "Terrorism In Lyon?"<p>

Private <b>RTL</b> radio in Paris speculated that, "Terrorism may
impose itself
at the G-7 in Lyon."<p>

ITALY:  "Bombing Will Become An Issue At G-7 Summit"<p>

Arturo Zampaglione from New York wrote in left-leaning,
influential
<b><i>La Repubblica</b></i> (6/26): "It is very likely that the
Dhahran
terrorist attack  will end up as an issue on the agenda of the
G-7 summit,
the more so as  Washington, even before the attack, intended to
raise the
issue of  international cooperation in order to isolate countries
such as
Libya,  Iran and Cuba that, according to the United States,
encourage
terrorism.   Last night's explosion...brings American soldiers
back as
targets of   Middle East terrorism, just as in Lebanon in the
'80s."<p>

      CHRISTOPHER IN MIDDLE EAST:  'FRUSTRATION OF HOPES' FOR
PEACE?<p>
                                       
ISRAEL:   "Americans Irritated"<p>

<b>Channel 2-TV</b> observed (6/26), "Should Netanyahu fail to
deliver, his warm
relations with the Americans won't last much beyond November." 
Diplomatic
correspondent Immanuel Rosen added, "The Americans were irritated
by the
rather undiplomatic announcement of the Prime Minister's Office
that
Netanyahu was not going to go into specifics in his talks with
the
secretary."   Diplomatic correspondent Shimon Shiffer also said
in top-
circulation, pluralist <b><i>Yediot</b></i> (6/26), "Secretary
Christopher's entourage has been stunned by Prime Minister
Netanyahu's
radical positions regarding the negotiations with Syria and the
Palestinians....   It is obvious that a special effort will be
required to
create an atmosphere of trust between Netanyahu's close
associates and the
American peace team." <p>

"Netanyahu Wants To Go Back To Square One"<p>

Diplomatic writer Aluf Ben observed in liberal, independent
<b><i>Haaretz</b></i> (6/26),  "Netanyahu yesterday spelled out
Israel's
new foreign policy, stressing that he is not going to follow in
the path
of Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres....  He wants to go back to
square one
and make a fresh start.  He has revived the slogans and
terminology of the
last Likud government....  When (Christopher) meets with Arafat,
he will
have to use all his diplomatic skills to turn Netanyahu's
ambiguous
comments into a reassuring message." <p>

"A Poor Start" <p>

Under the headline above, veteran pundit Yosef Harif wrote in
pluralist
<b><i>Maariv</b></i> (6/26) regarding Christopher's
'instructions' to
Netanyahu on Hebron, "Simple good manners and fairness should
have told
the secretary to let the prime minister handle with great caution
the very
complex issue of Hebron and not to try to push him into a corner. 
Didn't
the secretary realize that his remarks would only make Arafat
toughen his
stand?"<p>

EGYPT:  "What Made Christopher Change U.S. Policies Overnight?"
<p>

A commentary on the front page of pro-government <b><i>Al
Ahram</b></i>
(6/26) noted, "In the strange press  conference which he held
with...Christopher, Netanyahu blew up all the international 
resolutions
with a simple wave of his hand. He disregarded all Security
Council
resolutions and the agreements reached according to the Madrid
formula and 
Oslo which define the rights of all the Arab states as  well as
the rights
of Israel.  His statements came as a  challenge to peace and
peace-loving
nations all over  the world.... The strangest thing is
that...Christopher...announced in the  press conference that the
United
States supports such  irresponsible statements.  The question is
what made 
Christopher change U.S. policies overnight, when it  approved
Security
Council resolutions and the Madrid  and Oslo agreements, and has
a stable
position on  Jerusalem?  We hope that Mr. Christopher would
answer all our
questions when he comes to Cairo today." <p>

"Why Egyptian Attitudes Toward U.S. Have Changed"<p>

Gamal Badawi, editor-in-chief of opposition <b><i>Al Wafd</b></i>
(6/26),
concluded,: "I wish that his  excellency would spend an hour of
his short
visit and  walk in the Egyptian streets to listen to the
Egyptians
protesting U.S. policy which sided publicly and secretly with
injustice. 
It deviated from the  principles of fairness and freedom on which
the
United States  was founded....  The United States continues to
pamper  the
criminal and refuses to publish the report that  indicts <p>


Israel.  When...Boutros  Ghali publishes the report, he is
punished by
being  deposed from his position.... Your injustice and illogical
acts,
Mr. Christopher, made the people turn their backs  to you and
discredit
your claims that you support  peace,  justice, equality and human
rights."
<p>

"Pitiful"<p>

In the view  of editor-in-chief Galal Dweidar in pro-government
<b><i>Al
Akhbar</b></i> (6/26): "What the  secretary of the world's sole
superpower
said in  Jerusalem was pitiful....  Christopher found nothing to 
say in
the joint press conference with Netanyahu but to  agree with
Netanyahu.... 
All this indicates that the secretary has gone  to Israel not to
push the
peace process but to ask for Netanyahu's blessing of U.S.
policies....
What  Netanyahu and Christopher said shows no respect for the UN
and for
all international agreements." <p>

JORDAN:  "We Hope Christopher Can Put Israel Back On Peace
Track"<p>

Center-left, influential, Arabic-language
<b><i>Al-Dustur</b></i>'s
editorial (6/26) said, "Information and news reports that came
out
following Christopher's talks with the Israeli prime minister
confirm the
fears  that arose as a result of the Israeli right-wing party
coming to 
power....  We hope that Christopher will be able to determine 
the Israeli
policy vis-a-vis the peace process and will succeed in  putting
Israel
back on track again with the requirements of the peace  process."
<p>

"Wiping The Slate Clean, Starting All Over Again"<p>

Columnist Ahmad Muslin judged in pro-government, influential,
Arabic-
language <b><i>Al-Ray</b></i> (6/26): "As for the Israeli stand
on peace,
it is a  different.  It is like an attempt to wipe the slate
clean and
start all  over again." <p>

GERMANY:  "Peace Process Will Go On"<p>

National radio <b>Deutschlandfunk</b> of Cologne (6/25)
commented, "Of course,
the peace process will go on....  Netanyahu has no interest in
reducing
the chances  of Israel-friendly President Clinton at the U.S.
presidential
elections.   For this reason, we can assume that Netanyahu will
avoid
everything that  could seriously threaten the peace process.... 
It is
very unlikely that  far-reaching decision will be made before the
U.S.
elections.   Only then  will it become clear which direction the
Netanyahu
government is heading  for.  A premier who repeats again and
again that
security is for him the  most important subject cannot avoid
cooperating
closely with the United  States.  This offers the United States
influence
and peace a real  chance." <p><p>

"The Right Man For The Right Time"<p>

Josef Joffe had this to say in an editorial in centrist
<b><i>Sueddeutsche
Zeitung</b></i> of Munich (6/26) under the headline above, "This
new
Israeli government has not yet fallen into step.  It would  be
too early
to insinuate that it pursues a tough right-wing policy, and  it
would also
be wrong to say that it would follow the footsteps of the Peres
team. 
This is why an end to any statements would be very helpful.   The
same
would also be helpful for the Arabs, since provocations only
result in a
more rigid attitude.  For Christopher, a Nobel Peace Prize is 
still not
in sight in the region, but an open field for discreet 
diplomacy.  His
equanimity and his poker face are now the right  thing for the
Middle
East." <p>

"What To Tell Cairo"<p>

Left-of-center <b><i>Frankfurter Rundschau</b></i> (6/26) ran
this
editorial, "Christopher will hardly  be able to tell his partners
in Cairo
something new."<p>

<p>

<p>

BRITAIN:  "Netanyahu Firm In Face Of U.S. Peace Pressure" <p>

According to the conservative <b><i>Times</b></i> (6/26):
"Unequivocal
backing from Netanyahu...for increased Jewish settlement in the
occupied
West Bank yesterday cast a shadow over attempts by Warren
Christopher...to
revive the flagging Middle East peace process....  He failed to
satisfy
American hopes that he would provide a firm commitment to pull
Israeli
troops out of the West Bank city of Hebron as agreed in the 1993
peace
deal between Israel and the Palestinians." <p>

"Frustration Of Hopes For Middle East" <p>

The centrist <b><i>Independent</b></i> stressed from Jerusalem
(6/26):
"Mr. Christopher gave no hint of distress during a joint press
conference,
but the election of Mr. Netanyahu...has meant that his almost
ceaseless
shuttle diplomacy between Damascus and Jerusalem has counted for
nothing....  The frustration of his hopes for Middle East peace
may also
ensure that Mr. Christopher will not be tempted to prolong his
stay at the
State Department."<p>

FRANCE:  "Empty-Handed Christopher"<p>

Under the above headline, conservative <b><i>Le Figaro</b></i>'s
Jerusalem 
correspondent Philippe Gelie filed (6/26) : "After the warmth in
the past,
the time is now that of  somewhat distant, composing
diplomacy.... 
Christopher is leaving  for Cairo empty-handed.  This is almost a
setback. 
In a communique which  was not very diplomatic, the Israeli prime
minister
had indicated that he  would not unveil his positions until he
meets with
President Clinton in  July in Washington.  (The communique) said
that the 
solid'  Israeli-American friendship is  intact.'  This needs to
be
confirmed." <p>

"Netanyahu Snubs Christopher"<p>

Under the above headline, Christophe Boltanski wrote from
Jerusalem in
influential <b><i>Liberation</b></i> (6/26): "Did he travel for
nothing?...  The Americans get no  encouraging sign about Syria
either."
<p>

"U.S. Campaign"<p>

Influential <b><i>Le Monde</b></i>'s correspondent for the Middle
East
Mouna  Naim wondered (6/26): "It remains to be seen whether
Washington,
for domestic political  purposes, will not increasingly come
closer to the
positions of the new  Israeli government." <p>

RUSSIA:   "Abandon Hopes For M-E Peace Laurels"<p>

According to Valeria Sycheva in reformist, business-oriented
<b><i>Kommersant Daily</b></i> (6/26): "Basically, the situation
in the
'Palestinian sphere' is not hopeless, and Christopher is sure to
try to
present the case as if the peace process in that region
continues, for all
the changes in the Israeli leadership.  It seems that Clinton
will have to
abandon his hopes for laurels as a Middle East peacemaker, after
all, as
his only concern now is to try to avoid being accused of a
Mideast policy
disaster." <p>

ITALY:   "Unhappy, Concerned Christopher"<p>

A dispatch from Jerusalem in left-leaning, influential <b><i>La
Repubblica</b></i> (6/26) read:  "During the press conference at
the  end
of his meeting with the new Israeli prime minister, the secretary
of state
looked unhappy and concerned.  Three hours of talks were not
enough  to
obtain from Netanyahu even the slightest promise to withdraw
Israeli 
troops from Hebron, or a clear commitment to meet Arafat.  It
seems that 
Netanyahu intends to discuss more thoroughly this and other
issues linked 
to the implementation of the peace process when he meets
President 
Clinton...on July 9. <p>


"But what he told Christopher yesterday did  not help to dispel
the
shadows hanging over the negotiations." <p>

"Back"<p>

Lorenzo Cremonesi remarked from Jerusalem in centrist,
top-circulation
<b><i>Corriere della Sera</b></i> (6/26): " With  yesterday's
meeting
between Christopher and Netanyahu, Middle East  negotiations seem
to
returned to the delaying strategies of past  conservative
government
coalitions in Israel." <p>

SWITZERLAND:  "Most Troubling Issues Sidestepped"<p>

Ouri Daniel observed for centrist <b><i>Tribune de Genve</b></i>
(6/26),
"The most troubling issues were carefully sidestepped--including
Jewish
colonization of the West Bank and potential sanctions against
Syria for
its support of extremist groups.  Israelis and Americans--as
allied as
ever--took each others' pulses in response to the changing
electoral
climate. Netanyahu and Clinton have no choice but to work
together, even
if the vibes between them are not ideal."<p>

BRIEF<p>

G-7 SUMMIT:  YELTSIN ABSENT, CLINTON 'STRONG,' EUROPE 'GLOOMY'<p>

FRANCE:  "U.S. Self-Satisfaction"<p>

Conservative <b><i>Le Figaro</b></i>'s economic
<b><i>Fig-Eco</b></i>
(6/26) observed, "Bill Clinton is coming to Lyon with pride.  He
can claim
having created  9,700,000 jobs over the past three and a half
years.... 
With this  record, a campaigning Bill Clinton expects the Lyon
summit to
be an  opportunity for him to show to his fellow citizens that
America is
again a model for the whole world.  But this may not be the case,
given
the  strong criticism which the United States is receiving from
its
partners, above all  regarding its trade policy (Helms-Burton,
D'Amato)....  Another point of  friction is development aid for
LDCs.... 
The lack of interest in the  U.S. public for these development
issues has
saved Bill Clinton from any  criticism at home on these
questions." <p>

"No Russian President: Fragility of Russian Reform"<p>

Rightist <b><i>Le Quotidien</b></i> (6/26) said: "The absence of
the
Russian president...will remind the West of the  fragility of
economic and
political reforms in Russia--reforms which the  G-7 traditionally
supports."<p>

RUSSIA:  "Russia As Market-Economy Country" <p>

Tatyana Yudina asserted in centrist <b><i>Nezavisimaya
Gazeta</b></i>
(6/26): "The symbolic aspect of Russian participation, based on
the
recognition of Russia's role in world affairs, increasingly
recedes into
the background.  Its foreign policy is getting more pragmatic. 
Now it is
no longer 'participation for participation's sake,' as we need to
work
more to establish equal, mutually advantageous cooperation in
specific
areas.  In that regard, acknowledging Russia as a market-economy
nation is
vital....  The development of partnership with the leading powers
and
continued integration with the world's economy remain a priority
in
Russian foreign policy."<p>

CHINA:  "Take Precautions Before G-7 Summit"<p>

Moscow Correspondents Gao Faming and Jia Yanjing wrote in the
official
Communist Youth League <b><i>China Youth Daily</b></i> (6/26): 
"The G-7
meeting in Lyon meeting will face two tough problems.  First, the
Russian
president will not be able to attend, and this will cause the
momentum of
the 'seven plus one' political consultations to slow....  Second,
development assistance will be a hot topic at the Lyon summit. 
France...
particularly wants to make the <p>


United States bear more responsibility in this area.  If... there
is a
breakthrough on the issue of development assistance, that would
be a major
success for France." <p>

JAPAN:  "G-7 Summit Should Show Way To Peace And Development"<p>

Top-circulation, moderate <b><i>Yomiuri</b></i> (6/26) held, "The
Lyon G-7
summit, opening on Thursday, is called an economic summit meeting
to pave
the way into the 21st century.  As host of the summit, France has
proposed
that economic globalization be a focus of the talks.... The G-7
leaders
should engage in meaningful and straightforward dialogue aimed at
realizing peace and balancing economic development throughout the
world.... <p>

"One of the central themes during political discussions will be
to further
efforts to cooperate on matters related to the 'safety and
stability of
the international community' as the 21st century approaches. 
Taking into
account the interests of the United States and the European
countries,
discussions will almost certainly center on supporting Russia's
reform
efforts, rehabilitation of war-torn Bosnia and encouraging the
Middle East
peace process.  Patience on the part of the G-7 leaders will be
crucial in
solving these weighty problems if a better world order is to be
established in this post-Cold War era.  The leaders also have a
responsibility to demonstrate direction and must pledge to
cooperate
closely in tackling these various problems."<p>

INDONESIA:  "Gloomy G-7 Summit"<p>

The pro-government, English-language <b><i>Indonesia
Times</b></i> (6/26)
held, "The coming G-7 summit may be gloomy because there is still
anger in
Europe over the U.S. trade policy, particularly over the prospect
of
sanctions for foreign firms doing business with Cuba....  The
problem is
that unilateral action by the United States is increasingly seen
as a
challenge to the multi-lateral trade policies which the WTO was
set up to
encourage.... The threat is no empty one.  The Clinton
administration has
already warned three companies...to get out of Cuba or face
sanctions
under which their senior executives could be denied entry into
the United
States."<p>

