<HTML><BODY><TITLE>USIS Foreign Media Reaction Digest</TITLE>
<center>
<IMG align=left SRC=g7logo.gif>
<h3>Foreign Media Reaction </h3>
<H2>Digest</H2>
<p>
<h4>Office of Research and Media Reaction</h4>
<p>
<CENTER><IMG SRC=foot.gif><p>
<i>Monday, July 1, 1996</center></i>
<p>
<h3>G-7 IN LYON:<br>
SUMMIT OF 'APPARENT AGREEMENTS?</center></H3>
<p>
<p>

There were mixed reviews from observers abroad for the Group of
Seven leading industrialized nations' "fireworks of
recommendations, resolutions and decisions"--as described by
Paris's influential, private <b>TF-1</b> TV--at the end of their
weekend gathering in Lyon.  While Paris's <b>TF-1</b> TV judged
that these summits are "effective," German regional radio
Hessischer Rundfunk held that this one offered no "tangible
results."  Even the declarations championed by President Clinton
regarding strengthening the international fight against
terrorism--in the wake of the bomb attack in Saudi Arabia--
received contradictory assessments.  Edinburgh's centrist
<b><i>Scotsman</b></i> asserted that Lyon would be a "success" if
it produces the practical measures Mr. Clinton introduced.  Many
other analysts, however, instead emphasized the differences
remaining among the participants concerning the root causes of
terrorism and how best to stamp it out.  They highlighted the
Europeans' "rejection" of Washington trade sanctions legislation
aimed at Cuba, Iran and Libya as perceived supporters of
terrorism.<p>

The summit's pronouncements on the Middle East peace process were
hailed by Arab media--from Syria to Egypt, as support for their
stance against the newly installed Netanyahu government in
Israel.  Cairo's pro-government <b><i>Al  Akhbar</b></i> said,
"The  G-7 adoption of the principle of 'land for peace' proves 
the soundness of the Cairo Arab summit resolutions."  This
conclusion was shared in Israel by mass-appeal, pluralist
<b><i>Maariv</b></i>, which commented, "The leaders of the seven
rich nations plus Russia sent from Lyon a crystal clear message
to Benjamin Netanyahu:  Don't lose any time."  Other significant
issues raised by commentators included the absence of Russian
President Yeltsin at a time when Russia is being considered for
admission to the exclusive club of seven, China's desire to be
admitted and the need to solve U.S.-Japan trade disputes by the
end of July.  <p>


BRIEFS<p>

   -- CTBT:  'Test Ban Talks In Trouble'<br>
   -- Russian Elections:  All Eyes On Lebed<br>
   -- Bosnia:  Stop Karadzic<p>


EDITORS:  Mildred Sola Neely and Pat McArdle<p>


FRANCE:  "Fireworks Of Recommendations" <p>

Commenting on the variety of issues examined, influential,
private TV <b>TFf-l</b>'s Regis Faucon spoke (6/28) of "'the
fireworks' of recommendations, resolutions and decisions" and
concluded: "In general, G-7 summits are effective." <p>

"A Rather Disunited Front Against Terrorism"<p>

Under the headline above, special correspondent to Lyon Pierre
Haski filed for influential <b><i>Liberation</b></i> (6/29): "It
has been difficult to translate the U.S. dramatization of the
terrorism issue, in the wake of the Saudi Arabia attack, into
concrete action in Lyon....  The U.S.  focus on terrorism is due
to presidential candidate Clinton's political motivations.  But
it is also linked to a political vision which he tried to convey,
vainly, at the Sharm El-Sheikh summit in March: the United States
condemns the European policy of 'critical dialogue' with Iran."
<p>

"Expand G-7"<p>

Influential <b><i>Le Monde</b></i> (6/29) reported on the
"confrontation" between the United States on one side and Europe,
Japan and Canada on the other concerning how to deal with
countries suspected of supporting terrorism, saying that "the
anti-Washington front held firm."  In its unattributed lead
editorial, the paper argued that it is necessary to "expand the
G-7": "How can one discuss the rules of the game needed to
control economic globalization without (some) major players in
this globalization, whose explosive growth disturbs the old
economic order?...  The current composition of the G-7 lacks
coherence....  The G-7 must open itself to new powers, or it will
not meet its ambition of becoming a regulator of globalization of
the economy." <p>

GERMANY:   "No Tangible Results"<p>

Regional radio <b>Hessischer Rundfunk</b> of Frankfurt (6/28)
aired the following editorial:     "After each summit meeting
there is a growing impression that  the many difficult problems
which the summiteers have to deal with could  be better resolved
on a bilateral basis....  Ill feelings are developing  because
there are no tangible results, no quick solutions because, when 
they talk about globalization, a great part of this world is not 
represented on this type of club membership meetings." <p>

"Economic Issues On Backburner"<p>

A commentary on national radio <b>Deutschlandfunk</b> of Cologne
(6/28) maintained: "What the seven most important industrialized
countries had to say  regarding the solution of the unemployment
problem was meager....  Obviously, the unemployment problem is
not considered  a dangerous fire that could easily spread.  All
in all, compared to  political subjects, economic topics were put
in the background at this  summit." <p>

"Superficial Declaration On Terrorism"<p>

Centrist <b><i>Stuttgarter Zeitung</b></i> (6/29) said in an
editorial, "The United States is a big and sometimes difficult
partner, and  this at times when the president is also an
election campaigner, since  the United States then claims to play
the leadership role among the G-7,  too.  Bill Clinton referred
to the bloody bomb attack in Dhahran to  redefine the agenda of
the summit in Lyon...but the declaration on  terrorism remains
superficial....  The controversial subject between  Europe and
the United States as to what extent trade can contribute to 
change did not take place, although it should urgently be
discussed."<p>

<p>


BRITAIN:   "Lyon A Success If It Produces What Clinton Seeks On
Terrorism"<p>

According to the centrist <b><i>Scotsman</b></i> of Edinburgh
(6/28): "The Dhahran outrage will put valuable momentum behind
President Clinton's search for greater concerted efforts against
future crimes of this kind.  If Lyon produces the practical
measures that Mr. Clinton seeks, then it will be considered a
success." <p>

RUSSIA:  "It Takes Yeltsin To Make G-7 Into G-8" <p>

Alexander Golz wrote in centrist, army <b><i>Krasnaya
Zvezda</b></i> (6/29): "Too bad Boris Yeltsin couldn't go to
Lyon, as this is when Russia could really join the club of the
world's principal nations....  For G-7 to become a G-8, it
certainly takes Yeltsin being present in the flesh, with all his
vigor and authority....  Yet, the president's decision not to
come was quite justified and obvious....  The leaders of the
world's major powers are practical people.  They know only too
well that if the elections bring about cardinal changes in
Russia, they, Western leaders, will face totally different
problems....  Far be it from me to blame all our woes on the
West.  But throughout Russian reforms, our partners dawdled
around and bargained instead of acting swiftly and resolutely. 
Had they not done so, there wouldn't have been so much skepticism
in Russia these days regarding cooperation with the West....  And
as a result, the coming elections would have been less of an
epoch-making event." <p>

"Flee Lyon, Russia" <p>

Vladimir Bolshakov mused in neo-Communist <b><i>Pravda</b></i>
(6/29): "If we were to think of what converting G-7 into a G-8
might portend for this country, we would flee Lyon this minute. 
Today's Russia does not qualify as a highly industrialized
nation.  Whatever in its economy is fast rising these days has to
do with foreign debt, prices, taxes and inflation....  Under the
circumstances, admitting Russia to the Big Seven looks like
adopting a poor relative who will have to live by somebody else's
rules.  The Lyon summit may well become a prologue to the future
division of Russia which was planned by the West and partly
implemented by Gorbachev and his successors."<p>

ITALY:  "Europeans Won't Yield To U.S. Congress"<p>

Andrea di Robilant commented from Lyon in centrist <b><i>La
Stampa</b></i> (6/29):  "The  Europeans won't yield to the will
of the U.S. Congress, and unanimously  rejected the sanctions
approved in Washington against whoever invests or  trades with
Cuba, Iran or Libya.  This political-trade dispute  between the
two shores of the Atlantic, made even more sensitive by the
terrorist emergency raised by the Dhahran bombing, created the
only flaw  in an otherwise relaxed discussion of major economic
issues.  At the end,  the Europeans and the Americans remained
committed to their respective  positions."<p>

BELGIUM:  "Unanimity On Terrorism, None On Economic Issues"<p>

Conservative Catholic <b><i>Gazet van Antwerpen</b></i> (7/1)
remarked, "Immediately after the murderous bomb attack in Saudi
Arabia...U.S. President Bill Clinton decided to put the struggle
against terrorism at the top of the G-7 summit in Lyon.  As a
polite host, French President Chirac honored that request
immediately.  In retrospect, this change on the agenda has
yielded one of the few concrete decisions at the G-7
conference.... <p>

"There was much less unanimity--not to say none at all--in the
economic segment of the talks.  President Clinton was rebuffed by
everybody when he defended the so-called Helms-Burton law."<p>


HUNGARY:  "G-6+1"<p>

Highest circulation <b><i>Nepszabadsag</b></i> (6/29) held, "It
has been the impression during the Lyon summit that the
international conference hall was not so much a scene for the G-
7, but rather a  "G-6+1" where President Clinton was playing  the
thankless role of "+1."  President Chirac, hosting the event, has
made the situation more difficult by acting as a spokesman for
the Third World and turning down American demands for
strengthening the embargo against Iran and Libya.  Velvet
statements of support mask clashes of economic interest, since
French, Italian and German companies have fruitful business
relations in Iran and in Libya.  But it would be an exaggeration
to say that Lyon was the scene of permanent disputes, since the
leaders of the G-7 have after all had a good discussion,
indicating that the future of this exclusive club is not as
hopeless as it seemed before the summit."<p>

SPAIN:   "Apparent Agreement, But Differences Remain On
Terrorism" <p>

Madrid's leading liberal <b><i>El Pais</b></i>'s editorial said
(6/29), "The leaders of the G-7 in Lyon have been forced to add
to the concept  of global economy that of global terrorism, owing
to the truck bomb launched against U.S. troops in Saudi Arabia.
Terrorism is another facet of this  complex phenomena of
globalization...and global measures are needed to  fight it. 
However, after the Seven's apparent agreement, several profound 
differences on the origin of some terrorist movements and how to
fight  them remain.  The United States is trying to impose its
own views and take  reprisals against companies in any country
that maintains ties with Iran and  Libya.  This puts the United
States outside the legal framework of the WTO."<p>

BAHRAIN:  "Fighting Terrorism Is Our Issue Today"<p>

Leading, semi-independent <b><i>Al-Ayyam</b></i>'s editorial
(6/28) held, "Despite the great solidarity and Arab and
international support which sister state Saudi Arabia has
received, we, citizens and leaderships in  the region, must not
forget that all plots and terrorist actions against us target our
stability, security and prosperity.  Perhaps this reminds us  of
what Bahrain has called for--enhancing and activating security 
coordination in the Gulf and unifying all the efforts to fight
terrorism.  Fighting terrorism is our issue today and our duty
for the good, security and stability of the whole Gulf."<p>

EGYPT:   "Un Official For Development Proposal:  Positive
Result"<p>

An editorial in pro-government <b><i>Al Ahram</b></i> (7/1) said:
"The  proposal to appoint a UN deputy secretary general for
development [is one of the positive results of the  summit.]  It
confirms that the current economic world  order may have a bad
impact on poor and developing  countries.... Thus, the summit has
benefited the Third  World, especially after the American
proposal to hasten  breaking the barriers of international
trade...was  rejected." <p>

"G-7  Support For Peace Process"<p>

Galal Dweidar, editor-in-chief of pro-government <b><i>Al 
Akhbar</b></i> (7/1), observed, "Undoubtedly, the position of the
six world  powers... in Lyon has eased much of the embarrassment
of  U.S. policy which is unlawfully biased toward Israel.  
Certainly, the criminal act in Saudi Arabia...eased the  pressure
of succumbing to Netanyahu's extremist policy  toward the peace
process.  The G-7 support for the peace  process...in opposition
to the Israeli extremist  government's demands, expresses the
need to regard  international interests including American
interests.  The  G-7 adoption of the principle of 'land for
peace' proves  the soundness of the Cairo Arab summit
resolutions."<p>

ISRAEL:  "Message From Lyon" <p>

Mass-appeal, pluralist <b><i>Maariv</b></i> (7/1) commented, "The
leaders of the seven rich nations plus <p>

Russia sent from Lyon a crystal clear message to Binyamin
Netanyahu:  Don't lose any time.  Get on with the peace process
right away on the basis of the UN resolutions and Oslo
accords....  In other words, as if there were no elections in
Israel.  President Clinton felt uneasy about personally
delivering such a blatant message.  Therefore, he used the Lyon
summit to prod and even lean on Netanyahu....  It should be said
to President Clinton's credit that he also used the Lyon
conference to put the war on terror on top of the international
agenda.  Unfortunately, his colleagues did not go along." <p>

SYRIA:  "The G-7  Countries' Message To Israel"  <p>

Government-owned <b><i>Tishreen</b></i> (6/30) commented, "G-7 
countries and Russia called upon the countries  involved in the
peace process to immediately abide  by its commitments within the
framework of the land  for peace principles....  G-7 countries
called for the resumption of the  peace talks between Syria,
Lebanon and Israel  because it is a part of peace dynamics that
must be  preserved.  Clearly the message is directed solely to 
Israel."<p>

JAPAN:  "Strong Leadership Needed From Clinton, Hashimoto"<p>

Top-circulation, moderate <b><i>Yomiuri</b></i>'s editorial
concluded (6/29), "During their talks prior to the opening of the
Lyon G-7 summit, President Clinton and Prime Minister Hashimoto
agreed to settle semiconductor and insurance disputes by the end
of July...  But to do this...both Clinton and Hashimoto should
display strong leadership.  One factor that makes negotiations on
these two trade issues difficult is the U.S. presidential
election....  If President Clinton takes a weak stance toward
Japan, U.S. industries and companies will be furious, and he will
face a barrage of criticism from his Republican opponent in the
presidential race.  We understand the president's dilemma.  But
if he adopts an unbending attitude on the trade disputes, it will
not only increase antagonism in Japan but also damage the
reputation of the United States as the free-trade leader."<p>

"More Substantial Measures Needed Against Terrorism"<p>

In the opinion of business-oriented <b><i>Nihon Keizai</b></i>
(6/29), "The determination of G-7 leaders to fight terrorism is
significant, but more concrete and substantial measures are
needed to contain acts of terrorism....  Substantial measures
should be adopted to ease the 'frictions of society' that give
rise to terrorism.  The special statement against terrorism,
issued at the U.S. initiative at the Lyon G-7 summit, did not
address this aspect of the problem."<p>

CHINA:    "China's Influence Cannot Be Neglected" <p>

Zheng Ruelin wrote for official, Shanghai Municipal <b><i>Wenhui
Daily</b></i> (7/1), "If there is anything that merits attention
by the Chinese concerning the G-7 summit, it is  probably the
fact that China is excluded from the summit.  As far as past
summits were concerned, China did not exist at all.  Today,
China's shadow is pacing up and down in Lyon.  This is a change
worth noting.  Of course, China's shadow is still not big. 
However, it is certain that if China continues with today's speed
of economic development, in the near future it will be China's
turn to consider what advantages and disadvantages there would be
from participating in the G-7 summit."
     
INDONESIA:   "A Legacy Of Western Colonialism"<p>

Pro-government, Islamic-oriented <b><i>Pelita</b></i> (6/29) held
in an editorial, "The Middle East remains a hot spot...a legacy
of Western colonialism.  The hatreds and violence prevailing in
the region are the result of security and socio-political
conditions created by the United States, France and the UK.  The
bombing is also our concern.  The root cause must be determined
in order to prevent such a thing from recurring.  The
perpetrators should be caught.  But the most important thing is
whether the United States--and the West in general--can take a
moderate stance and review the fundamental issue at hand."<p>

<p>

