<HTML><BODY><TITLE>USIS G-7 Nuclear Security Page</TITLE>
<img align=left src="g7logo.gif" alt=G-7 Logo>
<B><h4><center>The United States at the G-7</h4>
<h2>Nuclear Security</B></center></h2>

<p>
<center><IMG SRC="foot.gif"></center>
<p>

Ever since 1991, Soviet President Mikhail Gorbachev met with the
G-7 leaders after the regular meetings, Russian President Boris
Yeltsin has been meeting with the G-7 leaders annually, usually
immediately after the G-7 meetings.  This year, there was a
summit in Moscow of the G-7 leaders on April 19-20.  
<p>

The most important issues between Russia and the Group of Seven
are development aid in the conversion of Russia to a free market
economy and nuclear safety and security.  
<p>

The following documents, which date back to immediately prior to
the Halifax Summit, are all USIA-produced articles in text format
and can be downloaded and used with all rights. 

<UL>
<li>The Halifax Summit <A HREF="95g7com.htm#nuclear">
Communique</A> section on Nuclear Safety.

<li>The Halifax Summit <A HREF="95g7pol.htm#armscontrol">
Political Statement</A> section on Arms Control and Disarmament.

<li><A HREF="nu50608.txt">June 8, 1995</A> G-7 Seeking Russian
Nod against nuclear cooperation with Iran.

<li><A HREF="nu50811.txt">August 11, 1995</A>  U.S. will insist
on ban on all nuclear arms test explosions (Clinton August 11
statement).

<li><A HREF="nufacts1.txt">August 22, 1995</A> Background on the
Conference on Disarmament.

<li><A HREF="nufacts2.txt">August 22, 1995</A> Fact Sheet listing
Conference on Disarmament members and observers.

<li><A HREF="nu51013.txt">October 13, 1995</A> Stage is set to
complete nuclear test ban treaty in Geneva (U.S. Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency fact sheet on CD).

<li><A HREF="nu51023.txt">October 23, 1995</A> Clinton, Yeltsin
endorse efforts on nuclear security (Joint statement, fact
sheet).

<li><A HREF="nu60118.txt">January 18, 1996</A> Christopher says
U.S. to stress peace, security, prosperity (Remarks at Harvard
University).

<li><A HREF="nu60119.txt">January 19, 1996</A> Comprehensive Test
Ban Treaty a top priority (ACDA fact sheet). 

<li><A HREF="nu60123a.txt">January 23, 1996</A> Zero yield
nuclear test ban treaty within reach, Clinton says (Message to
the Conference on Disarmament).

<li><A HREF="nu60123b.txt">January 23, 1996</A> CTBT "bulwark"
against nuclear weapons spread, holum says (remarks to Conference
on Disarmament).

<li><A HREF="nu60313a.txt">March 13, 1996</A> Study notes danger
of vulnerable Russian nuclear arsenal (Lugar, Nunn urge priority
U.S. attention to threat).

<li><A HREF="nu60313b.txt">March 13, 1996</A> Senator Nunn warns
of nuclear "leakage" from former USSR (Could become nuclear
"supermarket," Senator says). 

<li><A HREF="nu60313c.txt">March 13, 1996</A> Nuclear security in
NIS seen "disastrously inadequate" (Experts outline problems to
Senate panel).

<li><A HREF="nu60320.txt">March 20, 1996</A> text: State Dept.
Release: G-7 nuclear safety aid to Ukraine (G-7 Countries Have
Provided Assistance Since 1992).

<li><A HREF="nu60421.txt">April 21, 1996</A> President Clinton's
weekly radio address cites need for Comprehensive Test Ban
Treaty.

<li><A HREF="nu60425a.txt">April 25, 1996</A> IAEA on nuclear
power status in 1995 

